review_text:
I was NOT given this product for free or at a discount in exchange for an honest review.

Now that that's out of the way, I can tell you about my first experience with this washer. I live in a small apartment and the nearest laundromat is too inconvenient for me to walk to. My car is always on the fritz and there are no laundry departments in my building. So I decided to look into a portable washer. I found this one that holds up to about 9lbs of clothes for under $70 on Amazon. Pretty good bargain. It arrived yesterday and it is much bigger than I thought it would be but very light. When I took it out of the packaging, I noticed a red ink mark on the lid and some black ink smeared on the safety disc thing for the spin cycle. Wasn't sure if that came from manufacturing or not. I washed off the red ink but the black wouldn't come off. The way my kitchen is designed made it difficult for me to sit this on my counter so I sat it on a chair in the bathroom where I could easily fill it with a few buckets of water and drain straight into the toilet. The sink hook up does fit my kitchen sink so if I had the space, I could've hooked it up there with no problem. I filled the machine to the medium marker, added detergent, then clothes and filled with more water as necessary. The drain hose seemed like it was gonna spill out so I stuck my finger in it to prevent spilling since i didn't have anything small enough to fit the hole and left it the duration of the wash and the rinse. It drains very quickly which is good. I didn't use the spin cycle because I have a Nina Soft Spin Dryer by Laundry Alternative which is amazing for those who don't know. You can find those on Amazon as well. So I can't review the spin cycle. Overall I'm happy with the product. Makes my laundry days much easier. I only gave it 3 stars since I couldn't comment at all on the spin cycle. I would recommend to a friend though.

review_text:
To light the oven, you have to open the door all the way, turn the knob on full, and once the gas is lit, you have to wait a few moments to set the temperature you want, or the flame will go out. If you do it wrong, the oven will still release gas without lighting it. This strikes me as being extremely dangerous in a household appliance, particularly when most gas ovens let you just set the temperature, and everything works. I am astonished that they manufacture and sell an oven without safety interlocks to keep the oven from filling the house with gas.
I have only had it one day, but have already had to reset the clock several times, because it loses the time, resets itself to 12:00, and starts blinking. It seems to keep time for maybe an hour or so.
The instruction manual is very poorly written, and has two sections on how to set the clock. One of them is for how to set minutes, the other is for how to set hours, but you kind of have to figure that out for yourself.
The temperature settings are printed around the outside edge of the dial, making it very difficult to see what the temperature is set at unless you are right next to the oven. They should have been printed on the face of the dial so they could be seen from a few feet away.
This was the only 30" gas wall oven I could find, so I took a chance on it. I regret that decision, and wish I had gone with electric, because then I would have had a better selection.
Since I had to wait for a custom cabinet to be made, I was past the return time when I discovered these issues. Now I am stuck just eating the cost of this terrible product and installing something else that will not put my family at risk.
UPDATE - got it taken out, installed an electric oven in its place. I am much happier without this explosion waiting to happen in my kitchen. But I am still stuck with this terrible product taking up room in my garage, because I cannot in good conscience sell it to someone else and put them at risk.

I‚Äôm not a fan of screwing the dishwasher in to the neighbors oring counters and I didn‚Äôt want to try drilling into the counter. These worked perfectly and allowed me to get it perfectly straight and not have to line up the dishwasher with the cabinets.

When installing with these, get the dishwasher level with all 4 feet and with the pads in place and the tape backing still on. Then, lower the front feet enough to slide it forward and so the tape won‚Äôt touch while sliding it back. Peel off the backing then sliding it back in. Once everything is lined up again, raise the front feet until it‚Äôs back it position. Then you can just press the tape until it‚Äôs completely secure. review_title: Stick with the K Kup - REVISITED/REVISED
review_text:
My original comments were posted because - despite numerous attempts, the product did NOT work as advertised. After posting my observations, the owner of the company called. Apparently, the tinsel strength of the filter paper was an issue that impacted the viability of the product. Using two filters at a time, corrected that issue and the owner has not only offered to refund my purchase price, but also offered to replace the current inventory of filters I have with the newer improved version.
I must say, that his determination to make sure that the customer is happy with his product is to be commended. I will continue to use the filters and may even invest in a second EZ K Kup unit to keep my Keurig running for guests. This company certainly stands behind it's products and will go to great lengths to make sure that the customer is happy ...

review_title: Solid product. Straight forward to install.
review_text: Our Kenmore electric dryer finally stopped blowing hot air to dry our clothes. Instead of spending close to $1k to get a new dryer, I attempted to figure out what went wrong. After a few research on the web and watching a few YouTube videos, it was fairly straight forward to diagnose and I found out the heating element went bad. A few research on Amazon and I bump to this product. The site is very useful as it listed all the models that are compatible to the part number. Best yet, it also comes with the thermal fuse cut off kit. My thermal fuse kit still worked but I decided to replace them anyway. The product arrived fairly quick even with the situation that we have now and replacing the heat element and the thermal fuse cut off kit were straight forward. So far, it heating element has holding up for more than 2 weeks and we have gone through close to 8 loads of drying. I highly recommend this product and it has saved me hundreds of dollars from replacing the entire dryer.

Great price on this motor! Use the opportunity to vacuum out any lint and also cut any tangled hair from the drum rollers. Don‚Äôt forget to reconnect the plugs for the moisture sensor and the drum light before you put it back together, oh and the belt, line the belt up with the wear line on the drum and use tape to hold it to the drum, lean the machine back against the wall and pull the tension pulley over before you attach it to the motor spindle, it just makes it easier. review_title: Wouldn't every buy a Bosch dishwasher again!
review_text:
I purchased a Bosch SHX98M09UC dishwasher in less than a year ago in October, 2009 for about $1500. We do no more than 2 to 3 loads a week. Good points: EXTREMELY quiet. Bad points - just about everything else. The worst thing, and it is VERY BAD - is the smell. There is a "chemical" smell that eminates from the dishwasher that fills our kitchen. After doing Internet searches, I found this to be a common issue with Bosch dishwashers. It is truly nauseating and develops without any dishes in the dishwasher.

Now after about 30 loads (max) a "Check water supply" message is being displayed on the LCD and the dishwasher no longer works.

My only recommendation is to stay away from Bosch dishwashers!

bert

Update: We had a Bosch service company come down and look at it. It turns out that they had to replace the return hose - once they did this, the smell and message went away.

review_text:
It works well and is able to handle larger loads of laundry than other portable washers. Been using it for a few weeks and I don't have any major issues. Use is fairly self-explanatory and also comes with a simple guide on how to use it. I am able to wash queen-size bedsheets (one at a time) but the comforter really pushes the drier to its capacity. I wouldn't recommend anything larger or heavier than a light comforter.

Cloths will come out of the spinner damp so plan on air-drying your clothes after they are done washing. I have a simple hanger and set it under a fan.

Keep in mind that you're going to have to drain your machine after you're done using it. It does not have a motor to pump the water out and realizes on gravity. I place my machine in my shower so I can easily drain. Otherwise, I would recommend setting this up outside.

As other people have said it is a bit more laborious than a standard washer/dryer but you're probably purchasing this because a washer/dryer isn't an option where you're living.

Some complaints/suggestions:

I would have liked the hose to fill/rinse the machine to be a bit longer and provide some attachments so I can put it on a faucet.

The power cord is also quite short and I would have liked it to be a bit longer.

This machine comes with static feet so you will not be able to adjust it for an unlevel surface. This is probably my biggest gripe about the machine as my floors are not perfect. Having some adjustable feet would be very appreciated.

review_text: We were without ice on our LG refrigerator for about three years before I got smart and tried to fix the ice dispenser. I studied a bit online and our problem seemed to be this little micro switch. After carefully prying off the front plate with a small flathead, the highly corroded micro switch was in plain view with two easy connections. I had to use needle nose pliers to remove the connections since they were corroded to the terminals. I used my dremel to clean off the female terminals, then soldered on new male terminals (including some heat shrink) and re-attached but it was still no good. So I ordered this $10 part and it was the solution. I also used a small amount of Press and Seal to cover the switch area in hopes of preventing future corrosion to the terminals.

review_text:
First, this filter is shorter than the one I replaced, so I assume with less overall filtration surface the replacement won't last as long as the last one (which made it about a year). This particular replacement was cheaper than other options, so I assume this is why. I want to emphasize that this listing came up as an exact match for my Frigidaire Gallery. Next comes the key intel besides just the unit size...

Secondly -- remove the filter you are about to replace. On the top you will see a square ridge that runs the length of the filter - its even visible while it's installed - think of it as rail guide so you slide the filter in properly. If you see a SECOND narrower ridge beside this one - then the filter listed here is right for you. If there is NOT a second guide, you need to find one with only the one main guide.

I had to file that second ridge down with a hand file (10 minutes worth of filing) and this filter then slipped in no problem. I hope this helps others avoid this little surprise. Or, maybe you don't mind applying some "elbow grease" and want to go for the cheaper option. But be advised.

review_text: This washer uses load sensing technology to determine how much water required for each load. The agitator turns slowly then jets in the amount of water required for the load. Then washing commences. review_text: This was a rare impulse buy. I logged on that day looking to buy a supply of Grip-Stics, which I LOVE for sealing food products right in the bag - prepackaged salads, chocolate chips, pancake mix, pretzels, and many more items. These tiny things function somewhat similarly to Grip-Stics, but they are designed for very small bags or packets. I've already used them for soy and duck sauce packets, sauce packets from frozen foods that come with dipping sauces, spice packets, and even the flavoring packet from ramen noodles (we think using the whole packet makes the broth too salty!). They are also useful for non-food items, like small bags of seed beads, jewelry findings, or other craft items. Try them - at this price they are well worth it and you'll find more uses for them than you would expect.

review_text: We recently got a Keurig for my office, which I was very excited about.  The catch was, we had to supply our own coffee.  I know how expensive K-cups can be, which is why when I saw this product, I was excited.  I bought one.  The first time I tried it out, the coffee I got was a bit weak, but I figured I'd have some trial and error before I figured out the correct amount for my taste.  My problem was, I had trouble removing the EZ-Cup from the machine.  When it finally came out, I'd learned that the water temperature had caused the reusable pod to warp and crack.  This is after only one use.  So, I exchanged it for another, hoping it was just a flaw in the first one.  I managed to get two uses out of the second before it warped and cracked enough to render it unusable.  I'm sorry, but this product is a total waste of money.  I will have to find a better reusable pod to meet my needs.

review_title: Worked just fine in my Magic Chef oven
review_text: It was taking a long time for my oven to start and frequently I'd hear a puff puff and smell gas. The old glow plug was still glowing so I didn't think that was the problem. I researched the problem on the internet and read that even though the ignitor may glow if it didn't draw at least 3.1A it could cause problems like I was having. I measured mine at it drew only 2.7A. I had hoped for a ignitor with the correct end but the correct one was almost double this one. Since this one came with wire nuts I simply the end off mine and this one and wire nutted my end on this ignitor, worked like a charm! Now my oven starts very quickly and doesn't go out. I even ordered a spare for when it goes out again, apparently they only last ~5-8 years(depending on use) and mine was over 10 years so next time it happens I'll have a spare :) The two where still cheaper than 1 at most places, for sure locally.

We were having major problems with humidity getting into our dryer. The dryer was always wet as was the filter! After researching, we decide to purchase this product hoping that it would stop the moisture. IT DID!

After removing the old flap vent and cleaning the lent from the piping, I installed this vent onto the brick wall using Tapcon anchoring screws (drill and insert screws) instead of the traditional anchors. I also applied silicone caulking and waited 24 hours. With outdoor temperatures in the nineties, the dryer remains dry. It can be easily cleaned and I think that I can clean vent pipe as well. A great product!

review_title: Failed after 3 years. No one want to take the repair job.
review_text:
It was great for 3 years, could not be happier. Then it just stopped cooling. A tech told it is a dead compressor. No problem, the compressor is still under 7-years warranty, right? Called the LG support, they gave me a bunch of phones for "certified repair centers". Called all of them, got variety of dead phones, a single person contractor who is yet to get his license and tools, or a company that does not have a certified tech. (What kind of repair center is that?) The only company that does this type of jobs in my state first told me they are too backed up, so they cannot schedule my repair for 2 months. No problem I can wait, I have a backup fridge. Then after several calls when I got on the first name basis with their representative he told me outright they do not want to fix LG, because they keep failing left and right after repair. They do not want to take my money - BTW its parts that are covered, labor is $400-$600 extra - and then hear my mad call in few months because it breaks down again and now they are involved. So he suggested to cut my losses and get rid of the thing.
I googled it and found it is a very common attitude among the repair businesses : "LG? Sorry, we won't take the job."

review_text: I was hesitant to buy it since the Sears guy told me that I needed to use LG filter only, unfortunately it would get expensive buying it every 5 months (they say 6 months, but we drink lots of water in my house). So I went with this one because of the reviews, although, I almost didn't get it because of the few bad reviews, but I took a chance. SO GLAD I did. Water taste great, clean and I am saving money. Here is the key, once you put the filter in (super easy to do), and close the refrigerator doors, have a large pitcher and fill it up. You need to first get the air out, and then about 2 gallons of water before it comes out clear. The first gallon was greyish, but by the last gallon, it was clear. That's it. We have clear glasses, so we can see what we are drinking. The water is clear and taste great. Putting myself on auto shipping for this product.

So living in Portland, the beer brewing capital of the US. I went to an enormous beer supply store, only to find that the CO2 line that they didnt add, is a special hose. So I called Danby for the hose last week. I have HAPPY to tell you that after 6 days from that call, I received an email saying that they PLACED THE ORDER for the part today! Woo Hoo. So, if you're the type of guy that has time to run around town, looking for non existent parts, and like to wait 3 weeks to use a product that you paid for, and if the THOUGHT of beer is better than drinking the beer. review_text: Bought this to help maintain the humidity and temp in a 40-Gallon Breeder tank for my hatchling tegu (3 weeks-1 month old or so). After setting it up, I got the "E1" error message, and Customer Service said that it usually means the chip got wet, so they had me take it apart to see if it was corroded or if it somehow got wet (turns out my mister had caught it, oops). Dried it out with compressed air and it worked just fine. I have the temp  side hooked up to a small CPU fan which kicks on when the temp at the middle of the tank goes above 80 degrees, so the basking spot stays hot 24/7 but the cool side of the tank (where the fan pulls the air in) will be around 75 degrees. The humidity side is hooked up to a ExoTerra Monsoon mister, which kicks on for a few seconds when the humidity goes below 75%. I plan on getting a "second opinion" sensor to make sure it's reading correctly, because too low humidity can mean a bad shed, which is bad news for my tegu! But so far, so good!

review_title: Not 'Exactly' As Pictured - However Works Great
review_text:
This review could have went to a 3, or a 5 - depends on if rating the product, or the picture, so in the end I give it a 4. As others have noted the high limit does not match the picture and only time will tell how well it all holds up - I found the parts to be solidly made and had no issues with feeling cheap or breaking apart during installation.

Replacement is as easy as noted, just remove some sheet metal screws, pull the terminal wires off the old and replace onto the new parts, and button it all back up. Total time was less than 15 minutes, counting having to remove / replace the back panel and outlet vent hose. Started the dryer up and wooooosssshhhh! Just like new it was heating again.

I did this today, and we will see how long it all lasts, other reviews stated the parts worked for just a few months but I did not let that sway my decision before the purchase.

As of now, I recommend the kit but will update the review if and as necessary. Having all the parts needed in a single kit is a plus and the pricing is great - I am sure a repair service call would run $50 - $75 and the parts from a repair person would be a minimum of 3 times what the price through Amazon was.

review_text: If I could give this zero stars, I would. We bought a custom home 4.5 years ago; it had a FP double drawer dishwasher that we had to replace. Since the space for the double refrigerator set-up was custom, we got rid of one and spent at least $1600.00 at Lowe's to get one with an icemaker. Now, 4.5 years later, there is a water line leak in the icemaker and we have turned off the water supply while deciding what to do. A service call will be $90.00, and have no idea what the repair cost will be. Even before it broke, it was the slowest icemaker I have ever seen. In essence, we spent 1600 to get an icemaker, and it has ceased to function after 4.5 years. We should have kept the old unit, which was working fine, and just bought ice. review_title: Received the item damaged - But it works so far.
review_text: Received this item damaged. The outer carton had an impact mark that matched up to the dent. The inner carton was much better, but still had an impact mark on the affected corner. The actual damage to the unit appears to have putty applied to the wound. There didn't seem to be any other visible damage except to the upper back left corner of the unit. I followed the instruction manual to set up the unit to see if it would work... It seems to be operating normally with no coolant leaks or any signs of air leaks from the damage or anywhere else. When setting it up I noted the right front adjustable plastic foot knob is stripped and doesn't hold it level - so I had to put a small rock underneath there to level it. It's been running (quietly) for 24 hrs now and it has frozen a few water bottles. Temperature probe has it at -3.5 degrees F and is set at 4 (1-6). I have a month to decide if it's worth keeping or sending it back for replacement or refund. It's definately not a pretty "new" unit by any stretch - but so far it works. I'll edit this review when we've decided to keep or return and adjust rating accordingly. We were disappointed that we paid a "new" price for a damaged item - but it does work.

review_text:
Have used these for years in a Honeywell Models HCM-6009. Performance has up to now been on par with Honeywell's own version. Things have changed. Over the last 7 years the Honeywell filters have gone from a useful life of almost a month, to 14 days, and is now down to 10 days. ...and the cost has gone up out of proportion with their ability (not) to do the job.

Most current shipment of these clone filters is markedly different from those previously purchased. Not only do they appear to have changed in material content, but more to the point they no longer serve any purpose. Only lasted SIX DAYS and could not keep the humidity any higher than 30% (used to maintain 40 - 45% without difficulty). Cheaper materials, higher cost, poor performance.

This also means that the humidifier itself is running constantly because it is unable to reach the minimum acceptable reading of 40%, so poor filter performance also translates into more wear & tear on associated moving parts.

review_title: First Ice within 5 minutes - large size should fit under upper cabinets
review_text:
[[VIDEOID:18a3731b291de304af5afe8d8c2991ee]] The unit is large, heavy and will take up some counter space. It should fit under upper cabinets with couple inches to spare.

Per their instructions, after shipping , let it sit in its upright position for 24 hrs. After which, I plugged it in and put water in it. Turned it on and ice started to drop within 5 minutes. After about an hour there was a fair amount of ice, maybe 2/3s full. Hard to say exactly as ice was used during this time.

I like the small nuggets it makes. It is a little noisy but not too bad. When you push the dispense button, the auger turns and pushes Ice to the front opening. When you release the button, it reverses the auger for a partial turn which releases pressure on any ice that did not quite fall into your glass. This may also relieve any pressure that might cause a jam. I believe that it auto reverses if it senses a jam. The rate at which it drops the ice into a glass is a little slow, but again not bad. There is a drain hose on the back to empty the reservoir. It can be placed on its bracket to keep it out of the way. The ice box is not insulated so will melt slowly.

If you are going to get 40 lbs of ice out of this in a day, you will have to keep emptying the ice bin and toping off the water.

review_text:
These knobs aren‚Äôt really universal fit, but rather fit two standard sizes of D-shaped metal posts of the type typical of kitchen range controls. It would be helpful if the product description provided these two post diameter size measurements.

In my package were 4 knobs plus 4 small short adapter sleeves, 4 large short adapter sleeves, and 4 long adapter sleeves (for deeper-set / longer post applications) which have a large and a small sided opening (you can flip them around as needed). These adapter sleeves have the respective large or small D-shaped interior opening and a common grooved outer circumference that mates with the 4 included knobs. To install, you need to fit an adapter over the D-shaped metal post of your range or other application, then fit the included knob over the adapter.

I was able to fit a knob to an in-between size application by doing some drilling and filing to enlarge the inside diameter of the small adapter (it‚Äôs made of a hard plastic). It worked out fine, in the end, however I did not expect to have to do the customization work.

review_text: Our Samsung electric dryer suddenly stopped producing heat but showed no codes on the display. I figured it was most likely the heating element but didn't know how difficult it would be to replace. I found a YouTube video showing how easy it was to remove the lid, control panel and front door for access, so I ordered this part from Amazon and am thrilled I did! I used a multimeter to confirm the bad element and check the thermostats for conductance (they were good). Also, I was quite surprised to find so much dirt inside the dryer housing. It actually took more time to clean the inside of the dryer than to install the part.  In summary, don't be afraid to tackle this job. You only need a Phillips screwdriver and then a pair of pliers to bend a small tab and the two blades of the element wires, plus a vacuum and rag for cleaning. And for a tip, I taped the screws to their respective parts as I disassembled the dryer since each set of screws was different, making for a speedy reassembly. Go for it!

review_text: So to start off you maybe a bit confused why this product includes both the foils and the silicone disk and filters, basically there are 2 ways to brew and it‚Äôs kind of up to you to figure out what works for you, either the foils or the filter/silicone disk way. After testing this, here is my verdict. You don‚Äôt need the Filter/silicone disk as this method leaves more mess (inside the machine, no coffee grounds in the cup) it is a longer, more involved option. You want to use the aluminum foils! This is a much easier method since all you need is to fill up the pod with your coffee of choice and seal it with the foil, it works the same way as original, leaves no mess or coffee grounds in your cup and overall the better option since you can make a lot of them and just use them as you wish. The only downside is the foils after reusing them leave glue residue which shortens the life span you can use the pod. The reviews that say foils break and what not are either written by people with defective machine/foils or who simply don‚Äôt know how to use their hands. Overall don‚Äôt buy this product, instead go and buy my-cup 100q foils as it is cheaper and you will come to the same conclusion regardless.

review_title: Identical to GE WH17X10001 - Save Your $$$
review_text:
Perfect fit for my 15-year-old GE Spacemaker (WSXH208A1WW). The photo for these $20 Frigidaire shocks looks exactly the same as the $95 GE label shock (GE part number WH17X10001). I also found this instructional YouTube video for replacing shocks in a Frigidaire washer:

[...] Edit: Looks like Amazon won't allow a link to appear in a review. I suppose some idiot once posted a link to something rude, and now Amazon's lawyers... well, you know. So let's try this: Go to YouTube and paste the title of this video into the search box (without the quotation marks, of course): " washing machine shock absorber kit installation - frigidaire washer repair (part #5304485917) " The video is by Repair Clinic.com and the time is 3:44. The video convinced me that the part would work in my GE machine, and that I could handle the repair. If this doesn't get through Amazon's liability filter then you're on your own.

The Frigidaire machine in the video appears to be identical to my GE washer, inside and out. Even the screws and dimples on the sheet metal back panel are exactly the same. The video recommends using a deep-well socket to slip over the end of the mounting pin to depress the retaining tab (the tab prevents the pin from backing out). I found it quite easy to rotate the pin around with pliers, positioning the tab where I could reach it with my free hand, and then press the tab down with a finger. This saves removing the air separator as shown in the video. The pins are a tight fit -- took a firm pull to get the old ones out, and tapping with a wood block and hammer to get the new ones in. Still, it's an easy repair.

I've had these shocks in for about a week and the machine is running like new. Can't say how long they will last, but so far so good.

It exhausting having to run to the ice maker every few minutes to turn it off and on.  Now, after only 3.5 months of use, it is completely broken.  The motor doesn't work at all, and we are out $500!  I have a call in to Opal to see if we can get this fixed because we are now outside of our return window through Amazon.  The video above was taken less than two weeks after plugging it in.  We'll see how Opal decides to fix the issue.  If it's resolved appropriately and the fix works, I'll change the review.  But for now, I'd say that while the ice is amazing, it's not worth the effort or the price!

review_text:
This little flow meter saved me a lot of money that would've otherwise been spent on a service tech.
My washer is a Kenmore Elite HE3 Model 110.45862400
The washer was plagued with those F/H errors. The errors would occur at anytime when water was entering the washer. Sometimes the water would just keep coming in and the water would be 3/4 of the way up the door window before it would stop. (Normal water level as usually just below the bottom of the glass window). I thought at first it was the water fill sensor but in the end it was the flow meter.
Good luck to anyone dealing with those dreaded F/H errors.

review_title: I LOVE the performance of this machine but wish it didn't BREAK so soon.
review_text: I LOVE the performance of this machine. It is perfect for my small apartment. I don't give it 5 stars because this is the 3rd machine I have purchased in 2 years. BUY THE SERVICE PLAN! The first machine, the gears stripped, they are made of plastic so do no over wind the dials. The second one, the spinner quit working and I did not hear back from the manufacturer after asking if it could be fixed. I figure one month at the laundry mat costs me $80.00 so the machine pays for itself after only 2 months, but I do wish it were made a little better. You can't beat the performance though. My clothes get very clean, actually cleaner than a full sized machine. Clothes dry quickly as the spinner takes out most of the water. LOVE this machine but wish it would last for more than one year. Update 11/17 - My 3rd machine has stopped working, again the spinner is failing to move. The water pump still works. The washers water jets will not work enough to do a counter clock wise spin. I bought the service plan so a new machine is on the way.

review_text: We bought this to sit on our bar in our home to dispense ice whenever we wanted it instead of running back and forth to the kitchen for ice. There are several problems: 1) extremely noisy - the thing sounds like some one is building a Buick literally continuously. 2) the cubes are only barely frozen and melt VERY rapidly (although they are adorably small and cute) 3) the machine is not made to sit there continuously making and dispensing ice. We did not realize till we set it up (and threw away the boxes and packaging - shame on us) that it's meant to make ice and then be shut off. At the back of the instruction manual it says you shouldn't let it sit there turned on with ice in it and that it's meant to make some ice and then be shut off. This makes no sense whatsoever. If it's just going to make some ice that you then have to store in the freezer, then why wouldn't you just buy a bag of ice for $2 and store THAT in the freezer? We bought this so we had an ice maker in our bar area so we could get ice anytime we wanted, all the time. This is the dumbest product ever. I wouldn't mind so much if it was $10 but it was expensive and really a stupid design for a tabletop icemaker.

review_text: We purchased this Frigidaire 36" convection cooktop brand-new in August 2021, had it installed by an electrician, and didn't work. Called Frigidaire customer service on 9/28/21,  got a technician to come by within one day (good) to check it. He said that the main computer of the cooktop was defective, not working. He will order the part. I received a text message from the technician company on 10/11/21 that the part was on back order no ETA. I called Frigidaire customer service on 10/15/21, still waiting for the part to come, to call back in 10 business days. Today 10/29/21 I called Frigidaire customer service and they said they will call the technician service company to find out what part are they waiting for, after a few minutes the customer service rep gave me the part order number and said she just order the part and will be shipped to me on 11/17/21, that I will received it in 2-3 business days after that day, after receiving the part to call them back to set up an appointment with the technician to come and install it for us. So far, bought this brand new cooktop, it will be at least 3 months since we bought it and had not been able to use it!  No cooking in our brand new remodeled kitchen for all this time!! This part of the review (the purchase), I would say, do not buy this brand/model.... I will re-visit my review after I receive the part and the technician comes and try to make it work, we will see..... Well, as I expected, it si now 12/6/21, and no solution for us. No cooktop, no part, no replacement unit as I requested last time I called Customer Service on 11/24/21. On that day the Rep said it will take 5 business days to get an answer from the supervisor or next higher up in the chain.... toady I call back because I did not get a call or email from anybody about the request to get a replacement since its been over 2 months since we bought this mistake! Now I have to wait up tp 7 business days to get an answer if Frigidaire will send me a replacement or not.... I really don't know how to say this but DO NOT BUY this cooktop model. The model as far as me, its not good, and their Customer Service only take messages.... Today's rep said that there was no record of my 11/24/21 call about a replacement.... Its beyond comprehension, that means that we can't even trust a reputable brand name company to help their customers, in other words, the rep never wrote down in my file about this replacement request and lied about it, This is too much!! I'll continue my review after I receive the supervisor response, if ever...

review_text:
We purchased the Samsung RSG257AARS a week ago to replace our old Whirlpool (around 25 years old) that chugged along like a locomotive and sounded like one too.

It's still early, but thus far I have to give the Samsung a big thumbs up.

Pluses:
1) Very attractive design inside and out.
2) The interior theatre lighting is a nice touch.
3) Very effective cooling.
4) Exceptionally quiet.
5) Simple-to-use controls

Minuses:
1) The shelving has limited adjustment capability.
2) The crisper drawers pull out only half-way, so access is a little compromised.
3) The freezer should have a special slot for pizza boxes to be stored upright.

Side note: This model has a stainless steel finish and a great cleaner to use is Weiman's Stainless Steel Cleaner and Polish.

EDIT: (7/18/12) We've now owned this Samsung for nearly three years and are very happy with the purchase. The 5 stars rating remains accurate insofar as our experience is concerned. We've had zero problems with this product. It's super quiet. Keeps food consistently cold. And, for us at least, the ice maker works well.

EDIT (3/27/13) Still lovin' the fridge. Zero problems. Quiet. Nice.

Edit (2/9/14) Going on 5 years now, and absolutely no trouble. Sorry to read about some of the problems others have experienced. Maybe we just got lucky. Maybe Samsung has quality control problems. Maybe all refrigerators have their supporters and critics. All I can say is our Samsung has been trouble-free.
product_title: Samsung RSG257AARS 24.1 Cu. Ft. Stainless Steel Counter Depth Side-By-Side Refrigerator - Energy Star

review_text:
This range hood (shipped by Amazon--wrapped tightly in bubble wrap and in it's own box) worked great for my kitchen range hood exhaust project. The flap is effective in keeping birds out, and probably bugs too. Just in case, I installed a backdraft damper in line between the exhaust fan and this vent hood. Checkout Amazon item B000CDAFE6; Fantech RSK 4 Backdraft Damper 4" Duct. Also recommended.
It may be helpful to add that I used a foam sealant on both sides of the wall (similar to B0013IZSPU; which works like caulk, but expands a little to fill in cracks and gaps, and is supposed to be waterproof). Since this Vent Hood includes a collar for inside the wall, I used extra sealant (just let it seep out as I pushed the collar tight against the wall), and cleaned around the edges to have an air-tight, waterproof installation.

review_text:
The reason I feel compelled to comment on this filter is because of my own ignorance.

Let me explain. A couple of weeks ago, I noticed that the filter over our stove (which had been in place for at least 14 years) looked and felt like something you'd find on the beach after boat accident and a major oil spill. Thinking the filter was an irreplaceable component of the range hood, I began soaking and cleaning it and carefully scrubbing the muck off. I'd let it dry, realize it still felt like a gunky scratchy mess and go at it again. After a day or two of this a light bulb went off and it occurred to me that the dang thing might actually be REPLACEABLE! So I came to Amazon (of course) and (of course) found a replacement here. It arrived and fit perfectly. So this quantum leap in knowledge may be inflating my grade, but this item from Broan fits and it works and I was very happy to toss its predecessor. Could I have found one of these babies at a hardware store at a lower cost? Maybe so -- but probably wouldn't have remembered to go looking for one. I am once again thrilled with the selection and ease of purchasing that Amazon affords me.

No more yucky goooy plastic measuring cups.  This means that you CAN OPEN THE COVER while the tub is filling with water.  No LOCKING lid to aggravate you to no end.  Other washing machines at the big box stores are there only to fill up our land fills with more junk.  Most of the new machines have electronic circuit boards that will end up in our land fills and leach all kinds of lead and harmful chemicals into our ground.  I swear foreign manufacturers have no care about how we are going to dispose of all these pieces of junk they are sending over to our country.  Speed Queen is MADE IN THE USA with American labor and American parts.  The electric controls in this machine less of a hazard to our landfills than circuit boards do and since the SQ is designed to last, there will be less of them ending up in our landfills.  Think about this before you go buy a washing machine from China, Korea, or Mexico.  Enough said.

review_text:
I have an older FP double drawer dishwasher that was purchased when they were first introduced. Couldn't wait to get a double drawer dishwasher. Well, within 2 months I couldn't wait to get rid of it.

An hour and a half wash cycle? You've got to be kidding. And very limited room for glassware, not to mention NO cal rod coil to heat the water enough to sanitize or totally dry the dishware and glassware. The air dry these units have might save a few cents on the electric bill. But for my money I want clean, sanitized and heated DRIED dishes.

I ended up just purchasing two separate KA dishwashers, installed them side by side and they do a fantastic job and hold 1/2 again as much as the FP double drawer dishwasher held. Not to mention KA has a calrod coil (heating element) So everything gets sanitized and heat dried.

I received shipment of this dryer last week, and am very impressed. I'm not sure I would want to be drying family size loads in this dryer, but for 1 or 2 people it is perfect. I did dry my king size sheets in two loads (each took less than 30 minutes to dry). As recommended, I purchased the indoor vent. It works fine.

Awesome small dryer for an apartment. I highly recommend it.

review_text: I bought this motor after trouble-shooting a couple different areas of my dryer.  The dryer wouldn't turn on but the heating element would engage full blast whenever the timer was set to anything other than "off".  I thought the heating element might have been grounded out, but it was fine.  So was the thermal fuse.  I bought a new timer motor based on the recommendation of an electrician in the family, but that also didn't solve the problem.  Turns out the problem was a switch within the the drive motor.  I swapped out the motor with this replacement (slightly frustrating process, but not impossible) and everything was gravy.  I'm not an expert, but I think the problem was a little spring connecting two parts of the motor.  One of the two springs on the old motor had broken, and I'm thinking that they controlled the switch.  Don't take my word on it though, I'm an accountant.

review_title: Whirlpool dishwasher drain pump replacement solved issue.
review_text:
Arrived on time, was simple to install, I did it without pulling DW out and tilting. I have a whirlpool DW and the motor is in front, search youtube on how to install, there is a little clip you push down on and do a 1/4 turn and it pulls off easy. Remove wire clasp, then do reverse for new motor, but search for video to see where clip is that needs to be pressed.

Turn off Elec at breaker first!!! and put towel under the DW to catch excess water and remove drain hose with pliers. Try and get all as much as possible of the water out before removing the hose.

My DW would not drain when needed while in use, everything was hot and you could smell a faint elec smell of an overworked motor, but the motor would work if I turned the DW off and let the water and motor cool to room temp, then clicked cancel button till drain lit up, then closed door and it would drain. I though I had a clog somewhere at first. But replacing the motor fixed the problem and DW drains properly when called upon.
product_title: Whirlpool W10348269 Pump Drain

review_text: These are a factory match at over 40% less than OEM GE prices.  All knobs (factory or aftermarket) for my GE gas stove top are plastic.  So they will break in due time.  I got about 10 years out of 4 of the 6 OEM GE knobs.  Then they crack around the center stem on the underside of the knob which is to be expected eventually.  For longer life, ensure you push down firmly on the knob BEFORE you turn it.  Not pressing down hard enough puts pressure on the "barrel" portion and will lead to cracking.  When you do remove your present knobs, ensure the METAL INSERT installed in the middle of the "barrel hole" on the underside of the knob comes off with the knob.  But since 4 of my knobs had a crack in the "barrel" portion of the knob, the metal insert stayed on the gas control valve peg on the stove.  So when my wife first tried to install the new knobs, she said they would not go down on the peg.  But I noted the metal insert from the old knob was still on the peg (which it will do if the old knob's barrel portion is cracked).  So I merely lifted the old metal insert off the peg with my fingers, and installed the new knobs just fine.  Obviously the new knobs have the metal inserts preinstalled, and if the knob barrel does not crack, then the metal insert will stay attached inside that hole on the underside of the knob.  The new knobs when pushed down fit nice and tight and drop down just as far as the OEM GE knobs.  I have confidence these knobs will last a long time and for the price, would buy again and again.

review_title: DRAIN THE WATER INTO THE TOILET!
review_text:
Update June 19, 2021 - My machine came with a card promising to ship me the new version, free of charge, once it came out. I have been trying to get in touch with the company. They seemed to have no problems answering me when they wanted my review. Now, nothing. Generation Traders, the original seller, changed their name so they don't have to be responsible for my purchase. This is typical in various industries. Did anyone else get this card?

Update February 10, 2021 - I see the new photo of the "upgraded" machine. It seems the only change is in the lids of the wash and spin tubs and the knobs. Purely cosmetic. They did not add a water inlet hole into the spin dry side, like all of the other brands have at this comparable price. For that, I am reducing my star count to 3.

Review - January 11, 2021 -

I am very impressed with this washer. My clothes come out very clean. Since I never totally dry my clothes when using a traditional dryer, the spinner fits my needs. As someone who has worked in the textile industry for 40 years, I do have suggestions about using it -
1 - THE MOST IMPORTANT THING TO KNOW - Let it drain into the toilet, not the sink or shower. Detergent and fibers mix to become a gluey sludge and it WILL clog them.
2 - A water spout into the spinner would be nice to rinse the clothes more efficiently. I hope the company fixes that.
3 - I have never needed more than 6 minutes to wash or 2 minutes to spin. 15 minute washings could be too harsh on your clothes.
4 - The rotation can be hard on the clothes and get them quite tangled and pull on sleeves.
5 - I always use the SOFT setting but the only difference between that and the NORMAL is it delays an extra second or 2 between rotations. The rotations on SOFT should be about 50% slower than the NORMAL setting. That is another issue I hope the company fixes.
6 - Half loads work much better than full loads. It can throw off the balance of the machine and make it stall.
7 - When you hang your laundry to dry, put on a fan. It will dry much faster and smell fresher if the water is not left to sit in the clothes.
8 - The instructions packaged with this machine are CRAP! Please watch YouTube videos to learn. All of these machines work the same way.

I greatly thank all the ladies who published videos on YouTube to give me a heads up about how these machines work. It made it all so much easier.

review_title: No more nasty gearbox oil leaking underneth my Wash Machine. AND IT SPINS AGAIN!
review_text:
Our Whirlpool Roper wash machine would not spin during the rinse/spin cycle. Right away I suspected the clutch (again) which I just replaced about a year ago for the same problem. But after pulling the machine out and seeing all the nasty gear-oil all over the floor, I knew exactly what was causing the problem... the transmission input shaft seal has failed and (obviously) leaking.

What happens on these direct drive washers is when the transmission (or gearbox) input seal leaks, it will sling oil up and saturate the clutch-pack assembly causing it to slip. And when the clutch slips, this will prevent your wash tub from spinning (our it will spin real slow). Luckily I got to mine soon enough and was able to remove the clutch pack, clean the oil from the shoes and drum and reinstall it after replacing the input seal. I just rechecked the new seal install recently and the floor under my washer is dry and oil-free. And the machine spins normal again.
Happy with my purchase

review_title: It works just as great as it looks!
review_text:
I was renovating my kitchen and needed a new "island" range hood. The previous vent hood that I had was only good from one side. I saw this one and it looked perfect. Rest assured that what you see is what you get - only it looks even better in my kitchen (see picture).
Sadly, I cannot give you many installation tips, because I had an expert installer put it in for me, who was an expert in all of the "trades", but I did watch and help a little. The end result was more beautiful than I imagined. He did mention that the installation manual was vague, the picture on front didn't even match my model, and I think the instructions say to mount it to the sheetrock - which we didn't think was nearly sturdy enough. It's a heavy, steel piece, so we came up with a new plan. He built a wood box frame, with the thickness of three 2"x4"'s, and secured that in my attic, and attached my new range hood to it. I could practically swing from it, now (but don't try that at home). We also used almost all of our own screws - with the renovation going on, I had plenty of additional hardware and tools on hand.
Because my ceiling was lower (8ft) in the kitchen, our unit didn't need such a long "neck" - but the 2 steel rectangular sleeves that come with it are meant to be "nested", so we had to cut both pieces almost in half but, because my installer was an expert, he made it look great - as you can see by the picture!
If you must have something blocking your newly opened view (we tore down a wall, between the kitchen and living room), then it should be this beauty!
It has 4 well-placed lights, one on each corner, for "full food disclosure" - it really lights up my stove top!. As a personal preference, I've already replaced my little lights with the LED white light version of the bulbs, because I like more white light and less yellow light - purely my choice - but I wanted people to know that replacement bulbs are easy to find. I bought them right off the shelf at my local hardware store, in the specialty lighting area.
All 4 speed settings of the fan work great and, of course, the higher the setting, the noisier the fan - but the more vacuum power you'll get, for getting rid of the smoke (not that I ever burn anything)(maybe once or twice) (a month). The lower speeds are pretty quiet compared to my old "hoody".
My old vent hood had knobs and it had 3 speeds, 1). noisy, 2). super noisy, 3). noisiest...I SAID NOISIEST!
This one is a touchscreen and I really like it. It looks super clean and modern and it is everything I expected and more. I would highly recommend this!

review_text: Installed March 2014 and no problems with it. I was not the person who broke the original one that I was replacing, but I can see how this part can be stressed if you apply force in the wrong places or angles when opening the door. Complaints from other buyers about this replacement handle breaking are more likely due to the basic design of the part and/or the usage habits of the machine owners. There's nothing suspicious in my view about the quality of the manufacture of this part itself, it is what it is. I have seen elsewhere a metal replacement handle available for considerably more cost and less availability. If you're breaking this handle on a recurring basis, that extra expenditure and effort to acquire might be worth it. Otherwise, this part works as it is supposed to.

review_title: Frig water dispenser not working? Replace the Water Inlet Valve.
review_text: During our house remodel, I had to run copper to the new frig location. Unfortunately, I didn't know there was debris inside the line until I tried to run the in-door water dispenser. It was easy to pull the water inlet valve from our 20 year old Kenmore. Don't pay a service person to do this! I simply entered the part number found on the label, compared it visually to images on the www and found a replacement. The shroud was a little different from the original, but the water inlet and outlets and mounting holes were the same (extremely important). A ton of extra fittings were provided with the valve. I just used the new parts needed and tossed the rest. This valve was priced differently thru several web sites. Do your research and save some $. Shipping was prompt, the water dispenser works, the wife is happy, I'm happy.

review_text:
Independence at last!
I bought this beauty and I love it. It does what it's said it does, and it has saved me a lot of $ and a lot of trips to the laundry rooms of my building just for drying clothes. (I own a Haier portable washer where I wash all my clothes and it's also great)
Even though it takes quite a long time, (it is a 110-volts machine, what else can we expect?) it dries a good load of clothes very well, it fits perfectly in a small closet in my apartment, right on top of my portable washer, and it beats (at least for me) having to go to the other end of my building, take turns to dry and spend quite a bunch of bucks in order to dry 4 people's clothes.
The machine is very quiet, it runs smoothly, and it does the job it is meant to. The filters are very easy to clean, and if needed, replacements are easy to find. Last, but not least, it does not generate that awful lot of dust!
Awesome little perfect-for-apartments dryer!

review_text: I was seriously about ready to shop for a new dishwasher after the cleaning ability of my Kenmore Elite dishwasher had declined to the point that it wasn't really cleaning anymore. Then I read postings about other people who had experienced similar conditions and had discovered it was due to a worn out chopper blade. I found YouTube instructions for taking out the racks and other components necessary to get at the chopper blade and discovered that, indeed, the blade part was no longer attached and the little compartment where the blade fits was filled with stuff that had accumulated and could no longer be chopped up and flushed out. So for a relatively simple repair procedure to replace the chopper blade, I have a dishwasher that cleans like new again. Yay! The chopper blade was a perfect replacement for the original, says Whirlpool but fits a variety of dishwashers like Kenmore Elite that are probably made by Whirlpool.

review_title: Rebalancing the machine first might not be the best idea if your house has flaws
review_text:
You might not want to rebalance your washer first. We did and it was a big mistake. Why? Our vibration problem was characteristic of the house structure (wood frame on stilts) and the installers had done a much better job considering the challenges (it's gonna be less than balanced no matter what). However, after installing the anti-vibration pads, I've run a few washes in the problematic cycles and there has been much less vibration. My test: drink on floor in front of washer. Liquid surface & glass were not affected. Drink on top of washer merrily vibrated down to one corner.

My washer is a Maytag Bravos XL. I hate it because I want the ability to fine tune a wash - preset buttons suck - sometimes you NEED more water. However, a front loader wouldn't have any less vibration (researched that) and I can, at least, leave the lid up so I don't get stinky mildew odors.

review_title: Bearing didn't last for more than 2 months; might be a one-off (outlier)
review_text: [[VIDEOID:360fa5c3c1cba2a932bfb8c9b698e9f2]] I purchased this back in April of 2020 and installed it right away. I have to admit that when it was first installed that it was absolutely quiet and worked great. The price is reasonable and the items that comes within the kit is all you need to put it together. However, after 2 months of use, the washing machine sounds like the bearings are once again starting to fail.  Doing this repair  is relatively easy but it's very time-consuming. Note that there are alot of YouTube videos to help and if you clean the drum like I did, pretty messy. I recommend using a pressure washer in doing so. I happened to loan mine out to my brother in law at the time, but I digress. Now I'm pretty disappointed that it failed. Personally knowing how durable bearings are or should be I'm going to assume this is a one-off or like others refer to as an outlier and try this product again. I'm also trying this product again because it's also relatively inexpensive. I will follow up with my experiences to let you all know my opinion to whether it's really worth it or not to purchase this product. I added a , written and directed by me, so I'd like to warn you that I'm no Steven Spielberg.

review_text:
I'm using this for my clothes washing machine. I will be replacing it with a more modern one soon and I wanted additional protection. My home's electrical panel doesn't have any free circuit spaces for a whole home surge protector and this one mentions power-back surge protection. Not exactly sure how that works, but it sounds good and I have some thoughts as to how a device like this could help with that. Prior to using this, most of the time when I would start my clothes washer, an ev charger which is on it's own circuit, but of course shares the same grounding system, would have it's GFI protection kick in. That's the only time it would. The outlet and circuit for the clothes washer (and the ev charger) are wired correctly. The only down side is for this product is that it' blocks not only outlets above or below it, but next to it. Meaning I can't have the gas dryer which uses a normal 15/20A 110V outlet plugged in at the same time. I was thinking of adding a separate electrical gang box and outlet for the dryer anyway, so I will make it work, but others could run into this problem.

Update Jan 7 2019: The original intent of me purchasing this has been satisfied completely. With it in place, the EV charger no longer triggers a fault. In addition, there was an electric company issue in the neighborhood a week ago where we had a brownout - voltage dropped to 105 volts and sometimes down to 94 volts. This unit indicated undervoltage and stopped the electric supply to the washing machine - thus protecting it.
product_title: APPLIANCE SHIELD Surge Protector - Protects Appliances From Damaging & Costly Voltage Spikes/Dips, Works Great for Appliances, Refrigerators, Freezers, Dryers. Best In Class 20 Amp, 2200 Watts.

The coffee tastes great when used with the Chemex flask and the quality of this product is really top notch. The rubber ring is removable and you can wash the actual filter as much as you need to (I mainly handwash it). While I'm still trying to fine tune my coffee grind, it is currently between Medium and Coarse settings. I think I can grind it a little more towards the Medium and still be fine with it. The coffee brewed is strong as the hot water soaks through the grind so no issues with the filter letting too much water pass through it too, as the mesh is quite fine and porous enough without letting a flood of water through. Save the trees and get this. Well worth it. Will post a follow up in 6 months to see how it wears.

review_title: Ejecting is the only thing this does right
review_text:
I bought this pod and a similar one from another brand name. Both were identical so I'm assuming that they all come from the same place in China. The actual quality is impressive but that is a s far as it goes. Loading the pod is easy, Ieven bought a tamper to help. However the amount of actual liquid coffee that came out was just a dribble. I tried different grinds, different amounts of grounds, still all that came out was about a tablespoon of liquid. the actual stainless steel pod is about the size of the Alto (14 fl. oz) but what comes out is substantially less that the Nespresso Espresso pod (1.35 floz). I was lucky to get half that in many attempts. The machine gets the level from the codes on the rim of the pods. Both of these stainless pods (different venters) use the code for Mug (7.7 fl oz). The only thing I can think that could improve is the sharpness of the code lines. The Nespresso pod code is very distinct (and in black) whereas the stainless had some smudging along the code lines (and was in brown). I used lens cleaner to reduce the smudging and sharpen the lines and it worked a little bit. I was able to get roughly 1.7 fl oz from the stainless pods. With regular pods you can simply push the button and continue filling your cup. With the stainless the machine stopped after the button was pushed.
But as the title says, the ejection process was just as good with the stainless as with the pods.

review_title: Works better than just a fan.
review_text:
With temperatures hitting 100+ already we were looking for a way to cool down a little more. This has helped, but don't expect too much of it.

First thing you should know since we almost missed this: once the fan is turned on via the knob, you have to PRESS the knob to get the mist going. The documentation wasn't terribly helpful in this regard.

So let me tell you exactly what this is: this is a fan with an ultrasonic diffusing plate in front of it that turns the water into vapor. It's basically an essential oil diffuser put in front of a fan. (Though I would NOT try putting oil in it.) But that gives you an idea of how much mist we're talking about. I expected the pads in the louvers to get wet when using it (they don't) or at least the pad in the bottom to catch anything that drips. (This doesn't seem to get wet either.) The resulting effect is that it does cool off ever so slightly more than a fan does, but it's basically something you're going to just want to put on your desk right in front of you. In that regard it does OK.

We went the extra mile and used a spray bottle to wet down the louver pads a bit and that helped. (Make sure you take the louver/grill off before you do this so you don't spray water into the fan motor itself.)

Honestly, for the price one can't really expect too much from something this size. We found the fan speeds adequate, and the mister does help somewhat, so it fundamentally does what it's supposed to. It's not going to cool you off like a proper swamp cooler or A/C, but for something that sits on your desk and helps you stay a little cooler during this roasting months, it DOES help.

review_text:
GE made interesting choice for me when disabling their filter. Basically, I now am refusing to pay the inflated $$ for the rfid enabled OEM filter.

Just find (or buy) the filter bypass plug and gently remove the rfid. It should remove nicely with the sticker. Just stick it directly into the wall of the filter bay. Might take a try or two to get it just right. After that, install your replacement filter. Although the ‚ÄúI sit on a throne of lies‚Äù fridge will say. ‚ÄúNot Filtering‚Äù you can rest assured it is - because you just installed a new filter.

Take the money you saved and do something nice for yourself or someone you love.

review_text:
Seller: BUDORA DIRECT

Part seems genuine and price wasn't so cheap it makes me question whether or not it was a fake knock-off.

Samsung fridge model: RF18HFENBWW (this part probably fits other models as well)

The bad news is this is a SUPER common problem with Samsung fridges. It's most likely not IF but WHEN you'll encounter this issue (took about 5 years for us). The good news is it's cheap and easy to fix yourself if you're even remotely DIY inclined. One tech also told me that he almost never sees other issues (than this one) with Samsung fridges, so that's promising.

Our Samsung fridge was too warm and the freezer too cold. A professional tech came out and diagnosed our fridge and said this part would fix it (he was kind enough to just charge for the service call and gave me the part number). Our fridge was also icing up in the evaporator (which is behind the large plastic cover in the back, our cover says Twin Cooling on it). How he determined the problem was with the temp sensor and not some part of the defrost system, I dunno.

Ideally you will probably also want to replace the large plastic evaporator cover as well, part #DA97-11823A. I found it much cheaper elsewhere. It's an expensive part, so if you want to save a few bucks, you might try removing it first to inspect it. You want to make sure that the styrofoam is still all intact and doesn't have any mold/mildew growing on it. Ours had some mold growing on it (due to ice build-up), which is pretty much impossible to eradicate from styrofoam, because it's porous. You don't want funk being fan-circulated all over your food. And if the styrofoam has been damaged (either during the removal process or by ice build-up), then the cold air won't get circulated properly throughout your fridge.

The replacement is pretty easy. Search on youtube for a how-to video. Here's what I did:

1. turn off the breaker and empty fridge and freezer completely leave all doors open to defrost
2. wait 24 hours
3. remove all shelves and drawers in the fridge
4. use a phillips #2 to remove three screws: two are at the bottom of the evap cover and one is just above middle of the cover, you need to pry out the plastic cover to access the screw
5. use a butter knife or paint scraper to press in the tabs on the sides of the cover. Use your fingers to help pull the tabs free to loosen the cover. Most of the tabs have a tiny arrow pointing to them, but two of them are unmarked near the top. Ours had 8 tabs in all, 4 on each side.
6. At this point, the cover might fall free, so be sure to have firm grip on it and don't let it drop. There are some short wires connected in the back and you don't want to rip them out.
7. You might take a photo at this point of the wires connected in the back.
8. Squeeze the connectors to remove the wires that are connected to the cover.
9. the temp sensor is connected on the top left, the lower and smaller of the two connectors.
10. cut the 2 or 3 zip ties
11. Disconnect the temp sensor connector on the left. Ours had some plastic cover things over the wire connectors that had to be removed first. They don't seem essential, so if you break them when removing, probably not a big deal.
12. Remove the actual sensor from the plastic cage it's in that's attached to a refrigerator copper line.
13. Replace the old sensor with the new one.
14. Re-assemble in reverse order.
15. Turn breaker back on. Ours took several hours to get back down to temperature but works like a charm now.

review_title: Wii add years to the life of your front loading washer
review_text:
I installed the pads months ago, but held back on the review until I was certain they worked. These vibration pads are fantastic. They dampen and attenuate drum vibration as advertised. Before using them, washing a load of towels caused the drum of my washer to slam against the interior of the washer cabinet with the sound of sledge hammers. The washer would ‚Äúwalk‚Äù a few feet while this was happening, which is dangerous because it could pull against and damage the water supply hoses and produce flooding.

After installation, you can barely hear the washer operating. Drum vibration was greatly damped, and the pads have an additional benefit. Moving my heavy washer was a big ordeal without the pads, now I can easiLy slide the washer out of the way when I need access behind it, and no more washer crawling.
The level was very useful during pad installation, and the leveling feet of the washer were easy to adjust when they were sitting on top of the pads.

The pads are the best investment you could possibly make for your front loading washer. No banging of the drum means less wear and tear on the drum bearings. That alone will add years of life to your washer.

review_text:
After I diagnosed my 20 month old Whirlpool "freezer on the bottom" refrigerator-freezer as having "isn't defrosting" disease, I knew it most likely was one of two things; A bad control board or some type of obscure electrical connection problem in the defrost heater wiring.
Obscure electrical problems didn't seem the most likely failure and would require opening up the back of the box and poking around in the innards. Control board replacement is a fast repair. It won.

Amazon had an affiliate vendor with a good price and a good reputation, so I ordered the control board assembly (12868513) from them.

It arrived quickly and in good shape. It also included the information needed to program the computer chip on the board for my particular 'fridge. Whirlpool obviously uses the same board on many models.

I plugged in the board, turned on the fridge and programed the board according to the included instructions. It worked. Still works after 3 weeks.

That's as good as it gets!
product_title: GENUINE Whirlpool 12868513 Refrigerator Electronic Control Board

review_text:
I flashed the included ESP-01 module with esphome.
It did not boot at all unless it was plugged into the programming board.

ESP-01 modules need GPIO2 pulled to VCC to bootup normally.
This module had no resistor to pull GPIO2 up to VCC. So it was stuck in a non-boot limbo.

I soldered on a 220k resistor between GPIO2 and VCC, and now the ESP-01 boots when plugged into the temp sensor module.

The included soldered-on DHT11 temp module is far from great. It regularly reports a WAY out of range temperature and/or humidity that I have to filter out.
And the case for the DHT11 temp sensor looks... melted. I suspect it subjected to a temperature way outside of its boundaries when soldered on the module.

The voltage regulator built into the module seems fine, and the 8-pin female socket seems to make good contact with the pins.
I will probably desolder the ncluded DHT11 and add my own alternative temperature sensor to replace it (with the appropriate pull-up resistor so it will actually boot).
product_title: WINGONEER ESP8266 ESP-01S Serial Wireless Transceiver+DHT11 Temperature Humidity Monitor Shield Sensor WiFi Module Adapter Board

review_title: Performance drops sharply after a short time.  Disappointing.
review_text:
This filter unfortunately does not seem to perform as advertised. While there is a lot to like about it, it only offers trade-offs over current filters on the market. Ultimately it's more of a hassle over traditional filters.

Setup and activation of the filter is a process. There are a number of components that need to be washed and assembled. The filter needs to be soaked for some time, and due to the fact that the filter tends to float, I spent the time to hold it under the water to ensure a complete activation. It never actually stayed submerged during this process. The final step is shaking the filter.

Once assembled, it performed nicely for a few days. I could leave the pitcher in the sink to fill up under a moderate stream and it would only take a minute or so. The performance quickly dropped, however. Now it takes a few minutes to fill up under only a trickle. Any faster and the reservoir on top overflows and leaks into the filtered water. It seems like a step backward.

The other filters on the market that have a more thorough filter and a larger reservoir actually perform better. You can fill up your water bottle from the pitcher, then fill up the pitcher reservoir walk away. With this, you have to stand there waiting for it to fill. It's a step backward. And the fact that the filter on this product is only a fraction of the filtering capability of others doesn't really help.

I was puzzled that the throughput of the filter fell off so steeply after such a short time. They are supposed to last 3 months, but I only got a week or so before the throughput dropped. I thought maybe the filter had frozen so I left it out of the fridge for a while. That didn't help. I guess the water could be so loaded with particulates that it clogged up the filter really quickly, but that seems unlikely.

There are some other gimmicks to this product like being able to easily remove the filter to fill up a pot of water or a water bottle, but it performs so poorly that simply filling from the pitcher is the most efficient.

I do like the look of the pitcher and it is easy to hold and use. Unfortunately, the performance is just so bad that I can't really recommend this product.

review_text:
I always wondered as a kid why such a machine didn't exist. Then I learned Europeans have been using them since before I was born.

My husband and I moved cross country sight-unseen into what is surely the world's smallest studio apartment with the largest price tag, chosen blindly simply FOR the fact it had in-unit laundry, in some brand-new modern building with fancy countertops and pretty appliances and a polished concrete floor and all things not at all our style, and we survived over three years of living in approximately 120 usable square feet largely thanks to this machine's baby brother, which was small enough to fit under the kitchen counter and quiet enough to run while on teleconferences working from home which in that place meant sitting about four feet away from the machine. (This bigger model however is too tall to fit under a kitchen counter)

We're not picky about our laundry: you'd never find us separating our lights from darks, therefore we used the same setting nearly every time, so this machine serves an extra purpose still: it's the laundry hamper, too! More space saved in that tiny apartment!! (Space planning was a really big deal for my sanity. There were NO CLOSETS. My husband's clothes were folded and stored next to our dinner plates n bowls. My clothes were folded and stored in the bedside table's drawer, and that table doubled as the dinner table. We each owned four outfits.)

Then finally, precisely three years, two months and five days later, we'd scrimped and saved enough to trade one absolutely ridiculous living situation for an equally ridiculous but opposite one, and bought the biggest fixer of an old house you've ever seen (just look at that lean in my photo!: the washer-dryer combo machine is perfectly level). On moving day as I looked around that stupidly small now-empty apartment I realized I would miss absolutely nothing except for that washer-dryer combo machine (and the hot tub on the roof, fine.). So on our first night in our new-old junker of a gigantic house, I took our mattress out of the bag (pro tip from having moved sooooo many times: first make your bed --pillows, sheets, comforter and all-- THEN put it in the mattress bag, and use packing tape to wrap it twice super tight so your made bed stays intact, and then BOOM on the other end of your move all you need to do is rip it open), flopped down, got out my phone, immediately ordered this bigger brother from the amazon app, and there it was about two weeks later. It had shipped from Minnesota via a freight company, but then had to transfer from presumably a semi to a smaller truck once closer to the city because our ridiculous house is on a ridiculous hill, a 28.6% grade. (Do a Google image search for "San Francisco stuck truck" and you will understand - I witness this at least once a month) Still, the machine made it here and the beefy shipping guys somehow brought it in (it is HEAVY) and navigated it all the way back through twisty hallways and stairs in strange places to its final resting place at the very back of the house, and placed it on the platform I had built for it while in transit to keep it level in The House With No Level Surfaces, and on its rough voyage it only sustained one teeny scratch that was easily touched up (not that it was even necessary; the machine already stood out like a sore thumb as the only new thing).

Like its smaller version, this one works just the same and has a few modes I still haven't tried after two years and two days of ownership. The house already had enough plumbing backup issues so we made a quick greywater system to water a gorgeous Japanese maple in the backyard, and I think in doing so actually fixes the lone problem we'd had with our apartment's smaller machine; sometimes it would clog (that 0E error message another reviewer mentions) since the lint drains out with the water. Even though I'd run the former washer empty and clean the lint trap regularly that error message made a frequent appearance on the smaller machine. In our lazy greywater setup, I used an existing dryer vent hole through which I put the machine's hose, attaching it to a long garden hose & securing it with foil tape. Then the garden hose drops right off the deck and through some PVC pipe to direct it diagonally across the yard to the tree, where it lands a few feet above the ground, some 20' down. I wonder if the long drop has anything to do with lint not having a chance to build up anywhere. I find I don't have to clean the tub or lint trap nearly as often as with the other, too. I took the tape off a couple times the first year and checked then reapplied to make sure there was no mold building up, no strange smells, and all seems fine. I find with this machine I do have to level it after every few loads (I'd much rather clean the lint trap more instead; did I mention how HEAVY this machine is), but I'm sure most of that has to do with the jankiness of the house and is not the fault of the spin cycle. You can certainly feel the spin cycle from any point in the house -- again, I'm attributing this entirely to the house. And teleconferences are still OK from home because even though this machine's louder, my home office (twice the size of our entire former apartment) is on a different floor and farrrrrr away from the laundry room.

I think the smaller model served our purposes well in the small apartment with four outfits apiece, and I think the larger one serves us best in our situation now. While I think we still may only have four outfits each, we go through SO many work rags n towels from our remodel. I think any family larger than 1 might find the smaller model too small and would probably prefer this one. I hooked it up to a smart plug for a few weeks to see what it cost to run and while I can't remember the exact usage, I recall being shocked at how little energy it used. Oh, and before leaving a bad review for a cycle taking 6 hours, remember how big the tub was on your last washer, and how much larger the dryer tub was, and ask yourself if it could be user error. :) The clothes need room to fling about in order to dry! Don't crowd the machine! You'll know you're crowding the machine if things are more wrinkled than you'd expect right when a load finishes. Even loads with only towels (and I splurged on big white fluffy bath towels) doesn't take longer than two and a half hours or so and nothing ever comes out remotely damp. If 2.5 hours is still annoyingly long for you, then set the thing to start on a delay (which is a feature it has! and I love!) to start in a few hours, go to work, and come home just as it's finishing up to warm dry wrinkle-free clothes. In our house of neverending renovating work, this machine makes my life soooooo much sweeter. The only thing this washer-dryer combo machine could possibly do better is bring the clothes upstairs and put them on hangers in the CLOSETS we now have, and then pour me a glass of wine. :)
