review_title: Great for the first 3 or 4 weeks  ***UPDATE******UPDATE***PLEASE SEE COMMENTS FOR MY UPDATE**
review_text: I bought this Kegorator to replace my first kegorator which lasted 4 years without any problems whatsoever (I accidentally killed it trying to remove ice build up on its cooling system).  This kegorator arrived on January 26, 2015 very well packaged without any damage.  Setting up the kegorator for its first use was interesting to say the least, as the instructions really didn't explain that all washers and parts were already in place.  I  was left scratching my head a few times searching the packaging looking for the parts the instructions speak of when they were already in place.  I was extremely pleased with the temperature of the unit on the first day when I first plugged it in - 34 degrees.  By the end of the day the unit read between 38 degrees and 42 degrees and has maintained those reading up until about two weeks ago. During that period the beer pours were wonderful without any foam.  In the past week the digital thermometer has been reading between 45 degrees and 49 degrees and I'm getting nothing but a glass of foam.  Of course when I logged into amazon tonight about a possible return, I learned that the window for that closed on February 26th.  Hopefully I will have some success trying to contact the manufacturer.  I will update this review when I am successful in contacting the manufacturer.

review_text:
Coming up on the 1yr. mark, there is nothing I don't like about this fridge. I've had several over the yrs., including Kenmore, Frigidaire, GE, and others.
Except for the Kenmore which lasted about 18yrs., the others were crap.
I did experience the buzzing noise the first couple of days and called the service people, who very quickly realized I had the Ice Off power button ON,
when in fact the ice maker was not hooked up yet. He turned the power to it
off, and "voila" no buzzing!
I have not had a problem with this appliance in almost a year, and love it in my
smaller space.
It looks gorgeous and have received several compliments on it from others.
It has enough room for everything I need, and keeps the proper temp. consistently. The freezer holds loads of food, it's really quite large for the
size of the fridge, and I rarely have to put things in my basement freezer anymore.
Overall, I love my Samsung, and plan on buying the dishwasher now.

review_text:
This replacement W10531320 Dishwasher Drain Pump easily replaced the very noisy original pump in our KitchenAid dishwasher.
I was able to replace the pump without pulling the dishwasher out and tipping it on it's back. I first removed as much water as I could from the filtration system cavity with a small paper cup, then removed the access panel, placed a large towel under the dishwasher, removed the electrical connector from the pump, and removed the pump with a simple twist. Installed the new pump and put everything back in place. Took about 20 minutes.
Our dishwasher is almost silent again!

review_title: Low Profile and Unobtrusive. Look great
review_text:
I bought Samsung Black Stainless appliances and the corresponding hood but was unfortunately unable to install the hood because it was wall mounted and would have come up into the ceiling right under a floor joist. For this reason, I absolutely need a hood that would be unobtrusive and not class with my appliance.
I am extremely pleased at how low the profile of this hood is and how unobtrusive it is. It looks great and does not look out of place over my black stainless steel stove. I highly recommend this hood to anyone not willing to drop $1200 on the Samsung or LG black stainless hoods.
I have only had this installed for three days but Broan makes very good products and this unit seem to be very durable and well made. The noise level is very reasonable for the amount of air that it moves. The light works great and I have not had any issues with it. I‚Äôm very pleased with every aspect of this hood and highly recommend it.
As far as price goes, Amazon and Home Depot had the best pricing but with my Prime membership I could ship this 1 day delivery for about $25.00. This really bailed me out of a jam as the fiasco with the Samsung hood could have delayed my closing. Thanks Amazon and Broan!

review_title: I've never been more excited to do laundry
review_text:
I live in NYC, and my apartment building doesn't have laundry facilities. Until now, if I wanted to do laundry, I either had to wait until I had enough to justify a trip to the laundromat, hoard quarters, spend an afternoon there, and then lug everything back up, OR wash as much as I could in <a href="http://www.amazon.com/BRAND-NOT-SPECIFIED-Wonder-Washer/dp/B000BTDNEK/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1358208218&sr=8-1&keywords=wonder+washer">this</a>, a super small capacity machine with no spin cycle, which meant lots of time spend rinsing and wringing, and waiting for still dripping clothes to eventually dry on a rack. But that's all changed now thanks to this little machine, and I'M SO HAPPY ABOUT IT!

I received my Haier washer on January 7, and set it up January 12. It was pretty easy, taking all of about 10 minutes to get the bottom plate (which I believe is to dampen some of the sound) attached, and to swap the standard feet out for the included casters. I wheeled it over to the kitchen sink, and it only took a minute to determine how to do all the connections. I tested everything for leaks as I went along, and did notice some very slight water seepage at the connection to the washer, but nothing that a bit of Teflon tape won't fix, I'm sure, and I was able to keep it at bay by wrapping a piece of paper towel around it. My first load of laundry was a set of queen sized sheets (no pillow cases). I washed them on the medium water level (probably could've gotten away with low), and the normal cycle including wash, rinse, and spin. The machine took about as long a normal sized washer would, and I notice that it was a lot quieter than I was expecting. Even during the spin cycle, the machine really wasn't that loud - I'm on the 2nd floor, and I'm not concerned about the machine disturbing the neighbors downstairs. The spin cycle is impressive - when I took the sheets out, they were slightly damp. Definitely not dripping wet. I laid them on a wire drying rack in front of a fan, and they were bone dry in under an hour.

I've since done about 6 or 7 loads of wash in this machine, of varying sizes and types of clothing. The machine has handled them all perfectly. It did go out of balance one time (it beeps and pauses the cycle when that happens) but it was easy to rebalance and get started again. But I'm really impressed with this machine, and I'm so, so happy I got it!
product_title: Haier HLP21N Pulsator 1-Cubic-Foot Portable Washer

review_text:
I originally ordered the BV 900cfm model, I understood it to have the grease catcher and highest suction, also brighter LED lighting. When it got here i tested it and found no grease catcher. That was important to me, so I went back to Amazon. There I found the other model that did have the grease catcher, but lower suction (only 800 cfm)! What to do, what to do. Thankfully Amazon has a great return policy so I ordered this and figured I could compare them on my workbench. Yes, the first did have brighter lights and stronger fans but the second had a grease trap...testing the suction, I decided the second one sucked plenty of air and the lights were bright enough for me to see what I was cooking just fine. The first one went back and we set out to carefully install the new hood.
Installation happened after installing the new stick on metal tile backsplash. This is my new retirement home so I'm really enjoying doing things right, at my pace.
This hood is incredible. Beautiful, and it works like a champ. 3 speed fan that catches every odor coming from my searing and pan grilling steaks. My room mate was having breathing problems from my cooking. The old exhaust fan was a typical box store variety that on its best day probably sucked 200cfm. being willing to pay dearly to eliminate his breathing problems the box stores had nothing. Amazon however has many choices, and many people who take the time to evaluate, so us skeptics can feel more comfortable giving away our hard earned money.
Addressing some of the problems in the reviews I read: The packaging was top notch, tight and effective, no damage to this unit during shipping. The double fans are quite quiet, with no vibration. They have a delay shut off switch ability or immediate off. The LEDs have 2 levels. the first is like a night light in my kitchen and the high beams are plenty bright to watch what i'm sauteing. UPDATE (11/11/14). Not even two years old, and the handle for the freezer door just snapped in half. It's out of warranty of course!

This refrigerator makes more noise more often than any refrigerator I've ever had or that I've heard in my friends and family's homes. And not only is it noisy, but it runs more often than most refrigerators. The most annoying sound is a wheezing, like someone gasping for air, which can go on for 5 minutes or more, and starts up whenever you open the refrigerator door, as well as after periods of relative quiet. From reviews here and on Amazon, it seems that this is common to this model, but the only way to "fix" it is to exchange it for a more expensive model and pay the difference, and maybe a re-stocking fee (depending on where you bought it.).

Also, there is only one shelf in the freezer compartment, but I found a shelf for $5 at a hardware store that fit below the installed shelf, and it works just fine.

review_text:
We purchased this washer and matching dryer after our 9-year-old washer that was already bouncing all over for a couple of years had the sensor go and over-filled spilling water all over our floor (which it had ripped the vinyl previously, so water got under and had to have the floor replaced).

I read several reviews, but found it was just like when I wanted to purchase a new mattress. Nothing really got an awesome review. People either loved it or hated it, so I knew I couldn't go by reviews alone. There was a great sale on the items when we needed them, and we talked at length to the salesman. So glad we purchased them and didn't listen to the negative reviews!

It may be that the people who didn't like them are used to high efficiency washers and just want more bells and whistles. We were going from a 9-year-old machine that ruined our floor and bounced all over when it frequently became imbalanced, to this wonderful new machine. We love that it barely uses any water compared to the old machine. Love the different settings. It knows what is best for different loads and I don't have to think about it. It has a great capacity. What would've taken me two loads can now be done in one. Someone complained that it has longer wash cycles. The whites are a really long cycle, but it makes sense, since they usually need more sanitizing being your sensitive articles (underwear). I don't mind that some cycles are longer when I get the equivalent of two loads at one time.

To me, some people are just highly critical. I love these machines. They do the job well and I really don't need more bells and
whistles. Capacity is important to me, and they do a great job with that too. And another good thing that the salesman noted, they are made in the USA (I believe in Ohio). So if you do have trouble, it will be a lot easier than dealing with a manufacturer whose parts are out of the country.
product_title: Whirlpool WTW7300XW 27 5 cu. Ft Top-Load Washer - White

This is great. It cleans clothes just as good as a regular washer. And is easy to use after a couple of how-to YouTube videos.

The only downsides are that it can‚Äôt wash a lot at once and some fabrics dry very rough. Towels especially come out hard to the touch. I still have to go to the laundromat to wash certain fabrics. It‚Äôs still a great way to save money! Just be prepared to do some ironing.

Another downside is the length of the chord. I can‚Äôt use mine in the bathroom so I put it on the kitchen counter (and watch it while it dries so it doesn‚Äôt knock itself off!)

You also have to measure how much to dry or else it‚Äôll make a terrifying sound (and could possibly break).

Still, I don‚Äôt regret the purchase. It‚Äôs better than washing clothes by hand and absolutely $0.00 to use. My review is just a heads up.

review_title: Good for a fridge...but there is no support from Samsung.
review_text:
As for just the fridge part, it's a decent fridge. We've had it for about 3 years now, and not many issues to speak of. Worst issue we've had was the freezer's defrost drain getting frozen over once. Just emptied out the freezer, thawed out the drain, and good to go.

Now, for the "smart panel", which is the whole reason I bought this fridge. For a while, the Google Calendar app worked perfectly. And it was amazing, when it used to work. A live update in the kitchen of upcoming appointments...really convenient! Unfortunately, over the past year, the calendar app started becoming flaky, dropping its connection frequently. I had narrowed down part of that issue to clock skew (fridge clock too far off from Google's time causing authentication failures). But now, for the past 3 months, no service at all - apparently the current issue is that Google has updated their APIs and Samsung is not going to give us any updates to get things working again.

On the plus side, the lack of support narrows down my list of choices for new electronic toys in the future! I guess this will be my last Samsung toy.

review_text:
I've been wanting to get a portable washer for handwashing delicates in my small apartment, and have put it off because they all look atrociously cheap. I was on the lookout for one that seemed higher quality, built to last (the ones I could find that fit that criteria were too tall for where I'd need to store it in my apartment).

I erroneously thought the chrome on this was metal (an indicator of quality to me, because it will last longer bc it's less prone to breaking). Well, it's shiny plastic. That was disappointing. I was like, oh well, as long as it works! Certainly, someone put some thought into the looks of this‚ÄîI was very attracted to the cute green and blue colors.

Functionally, however, it is not great to use. The filling hose doesn't attach to your faucet; you have to like, hold it flush with the tap while trying to hold it steady to keep the water from spurting out everywhere. And I can't seem to find a better hose solution that is compatible with the device. I fill it up in my tub sometimes, but I have to hold it at an angle.

The wash cycles are just fine (though some speed control would be nice). the drying/spinning function seems particularly useless given the size of the basket you have to use AND just how little you can put in there compared to how much you can wash. I always end up having to hand-wring a bunch of stuff while slowly cycling small bits of clothes in the tiny basket. And you can't overfill it‚Äîor the machine will dance off the countertop.

Frankly, if I could return it, I would. Not loving it, and continue to wish for better home washing machines for small spaces.

review_text:
I bought this portable clothes washer seven months ago when I moved to a new apartment that didn't have connections for my stackable washer/dryer. I was concerned about ease of use and it does take a minor learning curve to remember the Three Things: drain, hookup to faucet, plug into electric outlet. Other than that, easy peasy. I have learned never to over fill it -- just loosely up to about 3/4 full -- and select the correct setting. I bought a nice-sized drying rack and a dolly to ease with rolling "Maggie" back and forth to her corner (I think it would be fairly easy without the dolly, but I'm not physically very strong and didn't want to take a chance).
So now I have laundry day like in olden days, roll her out, deploy the drying rack and get all my wash done in a day. Much nice than having to go to my apartment's laundry room and wait it out. (Though I do take one load of wash to the dryer so my wardrobe of black pants retain their shape.)

review_text:
This motor is slightly larger than the one that came in my LG dryer but fit perfectly and works like a charm. My wife bagged and labeled screws as I took the dryer apart, and the design of the dryer made it easy to disassemble and reassemble. My dryer has a built-in diagnostic to help determine what the problem is. It's described in the service manual, which can be found online at no cost for many models (Amazon wouldn't let me post a link). I found another site where a Canadian guy documented the process step-by-step, with great photos. Try searching for "Model: LG Tromm DLE6977W" "Parts: 4681EL1008A (supercedes 4681EL1002A)" "dz63" and you'll find a very helpful forum post.

You may want to stick your cell phone in under the drum and take photos of how the belt is routed before removing it.

Best of all, the price of this motor was about half the price dryer parts stores wanted for it. I'd guess we saved $300 or $400 by buying it from Amazon and installing it ourselves vs paying an appliance repair company to do it for us.

review_text:
** update, part quality has declined significantly. Changed and it broke same day, frustrating!! **
We purchased these replacement door hinge cables for our LG dishwasher, model LDF8812ST, in May last year and waited about a month to replace. It took my husband and me just shy of an hour and a quick view of an online video. Fix was easy enough. We went ahead and replaced both parts (only one side was broken at that time). Fast forward to mid August a year later one side broke and then the other a few days later. Because the price point was inexpensive and much cheeper than a new dishwasher we re ordered this part with the thought that replacing once a year was worth it until we need to replace the whole dishwasher. Good news was that second time around took half the time because we remembered what held us up last time... linning up the metal and getting the insulation tucked under before screwing the sides back on. Good luck!

Purchased from Lowe's 3 1/2 years ago, with the 4 year extended warranted. No problems up until now, while washing a load of threw blankets, heard what sounded like a bin of Lego's being dumped out. After a few seconds realized it was coming from the washing machine. Stopped the washer and noticed the inside glass had shattered, though we had it on cold wash cycle it was very warm when we opened the door, after taking the cloths out of the washer 10 minutes later the water temp was above 100F.

Called Lowe's to be frustrated by a automated call system that failed to recognize the information that they should have been able to access from the receipt number. When finally able to talk with a person, she said shattered door might not be covered, they will send out a repair person in 6 days time to determine if it is covered.

Now the PROBLEMS: Last month, it started continually making ice regardless of whether the bin is full. The auto-shut-off also stopped working so it tries to make ice even when the reservoir is empty (although those little "caps" of ice are pretty cute). A one-star review here from June(?) review_title: Easy to use, works, you won't be disappointed
review_text:
The old washing machine in the basement was looking like it was going to break any day so I needed an intermediate washing machine until I could find a good deal on a new larger machine. After using this little thing, everyone in the house wants to do their laundry in it instead of the (still working) old machine just because it's so fun to watch and easy to set up.

First off, if purchasing from Amazon, I believe you can rest easily about it arriving in good condition. For me, they used a lot of very thick, quality bubble wrap around the item box packed inside another shipping box.

I did have leaking issues where the hose connects to the spout (kitchen sink) others have had. I tried removing the rubber washer(s) in various combinations as recommended, but it still leaked squirting a little water sideways no matter what I tried so I had to settle for placing a small dish towel over the faucet spout while the water is turned on to catch the spray. At first I was annoyed, but I've learned to deal with it and the rest of the machine has worked flawlessly for several months that I've forgiven it for spraying at that one point now - it's clean water anyhow, just wring the towel out at the end, and you're done. There was another minor leak when I first started around the connection point where the in-hose connects to the machine, but I bought some two dollar thread seal tape from the hardware store, and that seemed to solve the problem. It might also help the not-leaking that I don't keep the water pressure on the whole time since I turn the faucet off right after it fills to wash the first time. I wait until I hear the first spin cycle starting, then go to the sink and turn it back on to let it fill for the rinse, then turn it off again. No leaks anywhere else.

Lint will come out the water drain hose and clog up your pipes if you don't catch it. What I do is buy some cheap knee high pantyhose from the drugstore when it's on sale and secure that over the end of the drain hose to catch the lint coming out. I just have it connected with a plastic cable tie that came with some other electronic purchase holding the cables together that I didn't use, but saved. I also use another plastic cable tie to hold the drain hose next to the in-hose at the sink so nothing moves around and water drains where I want it to.

It cleans the cat puke out and my socks smell fresh, so the machine seems to wash alright. Some loads I've done to give an idea of size: four regular bath towels; 40x60 throw, 1 pair jeans, 2 shirts, several socks; queen size sheet, a few kitchen towels; basically just start filling the machine with water and throw clothes in to where the dry clothes reach the top of the washer bin - don't force more in than that or your clothes won't have room to slosh around and get clean.

There is a good buffer zone from the top of where the water fills to (on high level) to the top of the washer bin, so you don't have to worry about water getting pulsed over the sides and can rest easily if you put in too much detergent and bubbles start to build up at the top (I did that) - it'll all still be contained.

Very happy with this purchase.

review_title: Cleans dishes like no other dishwasher I've ever owned
review_text:
This dishwasher is amazing. We are a family of 7 and it holds all of our dishes for an entire day. I used to have to run my last dishwasher twice a day. The increased load-ability of this dishwasher allows me to fit enough dishes to run it only once a day. I don't pre-rinse the dishes, I just scrape the food off and put them in. They come out spotless every time. Even dried egg residue and peanut butter disappears. I've never seen anything like it. It is truly a time saver! And it is whisper quiet. My refrigerator makes more noise than this dishwasher.

Update: I've now owned this dishwasher for 4 years and it hasn't given us one problem. It gets our dishes clean every time and there's no sign of wear on the racks or silverware baskets. The filter is really accessible and easy to clean, but honestly I probably only need to rinse the filter once every 6 months. I am still completely happy with this purchase!

review_text:

I am so thankful I will never have to buy another bottle of water again. I LOVE this product!

review_text: I bought this machine just over a year ago because I was looking for a small machine to wash my wife‚Äôs underwear and now my baby boy‚Äôs clothing. At first I thought this was a good machine because it has the gravity pump, but now I think it is not worth the money. Mine like others had gotten the same E1 error message just over a year after i bought the machine. It will not drain the water, so the machine stops running and you are left with a tank full of soapy, wet clothes and no way to rinse them or spin dry them. I‚Äôve tried contacting the seller, but it was useless as they just told me since it was 2-3 weeks outside of the 1yr warranty from purchase date, they could not help me. Since then, I‚Äôve tried replacing the water pump, checking all the electrical connections, but nothing works. I‚Äôve wasted about six hours trying to fix this myself and the company was not helpful at all with resolving the problem. If you try to look in the product manual to see how to fix it, it literally says ‚ÄúOpen top lid, according to before troubleshooting and settlement to settle it, then close the top lid and clear up the alarm.‚Äù I don‚Äôt know about anyone else, but I don‚Äôt expect to have to stand by a washing machine to clear an alarm every time it happens by opening and closing the lid. As they say, you get what you pay for. My opinion, don‚Äôt waste your money on this machine and spend a bit more to get a brand name that will stand by their product.

review_text: At the end of Thanksgiving Day, fortunately after all the cooking was done, when I went to warm up the pies, my oven wouldn't work! I had thought it was taking progressively longer to pre-heat and seemed to make a "whooshing" sound as it did so - as if it was igniting and re-igniting over and over. Thought that maybe I should look into it, but didn't do anything until it stopped working entirely. Anyway, burners worked, the fan inside the stove worked, it made a "clicking" noise when trying to pre-heat, so it seemed as if it wanted to start up - just no flames (or gas odor). Decided a cheap first step was to replace something that a Google search seemed to indicate was the "igniter." This certainly sounded like what I needed. Watched a YouTube video (so grateful that people make these, but who are they?) and decided it was within my skill set. Ordered it from Amazon, it came, I replaced it, and VOILA! it works! Woo hoo! Thanks internet and Amazon!

review_title: Great peice of machinery, well made, but use these modifications I advise below. Happy Washing!
review_text:
I am writing this review as my washer is running in the kitchen while I am watching TV and it's quiet enough that I dont even hear it while its running. If you are considering buying this product I have some advice for you. If you are going to run this off of a kitchen sink faucet you are going to want to order a Y splitter to hook to the back of the washer so the water from your sink can mix into both inputs on your washing machine. To find this product search Amazon for the following: "Y Washing Machine Mixer Hose". If you are planning on running this off of a kitchen sink it will not run properly, even if you select a hot or cold only wash, the machine will still a tempt to mix hot and cold water on certain cycles and if you don't have this splitter hooked up, the machine will attempt to pump water from both input spigots. To fix this issue, install this splitter, which will hook right up to the hose that comes with your washer that has a quick disconnect on it. To make set up easy you need to remove your old faucet head and replace it with the top half of the quick disconnect. When you install it MAKE SURE you wrap all threads all the way from the hot water inputs on the washer all the way to the disconnect installed on your faucet and all threads on the splitter. If every thread does not have Teflon Tape, you WILL get a leak as you are connecting metal to plastic threads. Some of you are curious about how much clothes this machine can run and I am very impressed with the capacity for thee 1.6 CF stainless steel barrel. I am able to fill the machine up with one normal sized basket of laundry. I have done 5 towels, 4 shirts, and roughly a dozen pairs of socks and a few undergarments in one load, just make sure that your clothes don't sit higher than the three agitator jets on the side of the barrel, or they wont be cleaned and set machine to highest water level. My third piece of advice for modifying this machine is that if you are going to be storing this machine in a different place then you will be using it is to purchase a set of 4 wheels. You can get these at your local harbor freight or home depot or lowes, then line them up on the bottom of the machine, drill your pilot holes for where the wheels will be and install your bolts from the bottom and install a nut on each bolt from the interior side of the machine. I would highly recommend this unless you want to have two people pick this big boy up to carry it around as the wheels that are on here stock do not work worth a darn. Overall I am completely satisfied with this machine and I would definitely recommend it to anyone lacking washer dryer inputs or space for a larger machine. Oh,....IT IS SO NICE NOT GOING TO THE LAUNDROMAT ANYMORE!!!!! Happy washing all. If anyone has any questions about installing these modifications post a question on here I will answer it.

UPDATE: I've been running the washer heavily for one year with no problems. The washer in the above review is the model with no dryer built in. This washer has been so great to me that I am now buying the washer dryer combo model(there are several model options) I have permanently plumbed my current washer into my water lines and drain lines under the sink just thought I'd throw that out there for anyone interested in a more permanent setup that this is possible to do... Will update again when I receive the combo unit.
product_title: Midea 1.6 CF Portable Washing Machine Washer

review_text:
Have owned this Bosch 300-Series Gas Range for two months. I ordered it directly from the Amazon-linked AJ Madison website. As for that store, the stove was delivered as arranged and the price was right, as it was on-sale for a few days. More on this later. Narrowed my list down to two: the Bosch and the Frigidaire FGGF3054K. The Frigidaire had a few advantages, these included a Convection oven feature, a better lower-drawer handle, a 17Kbtu front burner and a more advanced oven-rack arrangement. This Frigidaire is about $25 cheaper than the Bosch. I finally went with the Bosch because I had had good luck with their electrical components when doing repairs on my car in previous years. I also liked the heavier and more squared edges of the iron-grates covering the burners. Both stoves seem to be a good value for 8 bills. As mentioned, bought from AJ Madison. A few cautions are in order here. They will attempt to tag-on added charges after the delivery for a thing like delivering the stove up more than a certain number of steps (an arbitrary #). Before the stove is shipped, call their service rep, not sales, and tell them you will only allow delivery on condition there will be NO extra charges. I had to be a little forceful about this. And waiting for the sales department to answer the phone will require patience. These are New York-sharpies but they will be honest if you keep on top of them. I would purchase from them again, but only if the price was 25% lower than local dealers. Now some details on the Bosch stove: nice big lighted oven with a big window, fantastic non-slide full-coverage iron grating on top. The oven preheats quickly and since it is so roomy will not (my opinion) need a convection feature. All the design effort was on the burners, oven and electronics; the bottom warming/storage drawer is the typical cheapie type found on any $450 range. The working parts are fantastic, however. High-quality touchpad includes great timer functions for baking and general timing of cooking. The timers shut-off the oven as required and all timer functions beep every one-minute after timing-out, a great safety and convenience feature for me. Those not yet familiar with new gas ranges will have to get used to the electronic ignition for the top burners. Turn to lightning symbol till lit, then set to desired flame. The oven door will detent (pause) when closing but do not expect it to hold in open position solidly, as these ovens are meant to do all broiling with the door closed. On first use, you will probably notice a few things which seem like problems but are not: an error signal may pop-up on the display during first use. This immediately clears up once the stove has been plugged-in for a few minutes, clock set and the burners have been used. The other brief annoyance is that, due to the installer disturbing the gas lines, there will likely be some dust which blows up through the top burners, causing a snap sound. This clears up in a few days. Flame level adjustment is non-linear, an annoyance to some, but is compensated for by the ability to turn the flame down to an extremely low usable level.As for safety around children, the stove comes with the usual non-tip floor-bracket and has a nice electronic Lock feature for the oven door. It has the required push-to-light knobs for the 5 top burners. One caution with any of these full iron-grate stovetops is that a boy between 3-7 may get curious on seeing Mom cleaning the stove, and may lift off one of the 3 grate sections out of curiosity and drop it on his foot. Just train the little rodent. As for my 4-Star rating (see update below) of the range, I would give it a full 5 Stars but having owned the thing only a few months, I cannot comment on continued use or quality of Bosch customer service. So far, this gas range is great.

ONE-YEAR update: Oven and top-panel electronic controls are flawless. Four of the five burners light immediately with the electronic-ignition. The left-rear burner is balky, taking ~3seconds to light. One time, a pot of spaghetti boiled over a little on this burner. The flame went out and gas was issuing from the burner. With a second burner lit heating the sauce, there could have been a big problem if built-up gas had ignited. Luckily, I was in the kitchen at the time. I suspect these electronic-ignition stoves by various brands share this problem, since burner design has to be different to allow for lighting, as opposed to the old pilot-light jobs. The second problem arose when I called customer-service to report the safety issue. The woman to whom I spoke was rude and uninterested. Moreover, she was stupid. So, considering the ~minor safety issue and the non-existent customer support, a nice 5-star range will be given only three stars by this owner. All such stoves need a heat-sensor to shut off gas flow to water-snuffed burners. Wake-up Bosch. And while you're at it, take your entire customer-service staff for a company outing at sea in stormy weather.

review_text:
I live in a small apartment with no washer/dryer hookups. I hooked this washer up in my bathroom, with the drain going into the bathtub and I fill it from my shower head hose.

While admittedly this washer is a little small, it has the capacity to wash anything I put in it from my apartment and my queen size bed with the exception of blankets. Blankets now are the only thing I have to take to the laundromat which means I only have to go maybe once a month now. Yay!

Whoever engineered this washer should get a raise. At least two times, we have been filling the wash tub with water from the shower head and forgotten it. This washer is engineered so that overflow from the wash tub drains into the spin tub and when this spin tub gets too full, it automatically flows out through the drain hose ... and into my bathtub. I realized what I had done and raced back into the bathroom expecting to find a flood and instead found water draining into my tub harmlessly (except to waste water) and no mess.

Best $100 I've spent on washing laundry and has paid for itself already at least 5X over!

I replaced this at the same time as a bunch other parts to essentially refurbish my entire dishwasher to new condition (for $250 in parts rather than replacing the entire unit for $1,200!), and this was the easiest parts to replace. You simply disconnect the wires on the bottom, remove the mounting bracket, swap out the old thermostat for the new one, then put it back together. DONE! If you replace this and it still doesn't dry properly, then you may also need to replace the heating element which is about a $40 part and takes about 5 minutes to replace.

review_text:
We discovered our Whirlpool dishwasher had begun leaking. After doing some research on possible causes, we were pretty comfortable that the inlet valve was the culprit. It took a little while to figure out the correct part number but eventually figured out that it was this one. This is a very common part for many different makes and models of dishwashers.

Very easy to replace and leaking stopped as soon as we installed this one. This product was much less expensive here than other online stores. Having an appliance repair person do this would have been well over $100 , so win!
product_title: prime&swift W10158389 Dishwasher Water Inlet Valve,Replacement for 8563406,AP4369607

review_title: Not worth ruining your hardwood floors
review_text:
I don't usually write reviews of products even though I do rely on the reviews of others when purchasing an item from Amazon. In this case, I felt responsible to let others know about this product. It absolutely is not worth the saving since the item will leave water dripping from your Samsung refrigerator water dispenser. And since there is no drain on the small catch basin underneath the water/ice dispenser, you will end up with a puddle of water on your floor. If you have hardwood floors - this will cause damage.

I do admit that I read of others having leaks and I assumed they must be installing the filters improperly or they were doing something wrong as a user, but I can confirm this product will leak even when installed properly. I can not tell you exactly why it leaks but there is excessive pressure build up in the filter when removing and I have a feeling this added pressure is causing leakage through the dispenser shut-off valve internal to the refrigerator.

For anyone else contemplating this purchase, I have not tried the other brands of replacement filters but I would avoid this product as the possibilities for real damage in your home is not worth the small savings. Also, I did follow the tips I found on-line for running multiple gallons of water through the filter to remove any air pockets hoping this would stop the leaks but the filter continued to leak after multiple attempts to correct the problem.

Buyer beware . . . .

review_text:
Packaging: 5 stars. Box inside a box with styrofoam. Packed very well.
Setup: 5 stars. Remove tape from ice basket and plug it in.
Ice Making Speed: 5 stars. This unit pumps out 9 small ice cubes every 8 minutes or so. Good value for price.
Ice Quality: 4 stars. We made the ice in our home at 74 degrees. Cubes were a bit wet and a little soft despite being made in an optimal air conditioned setting.
What I wish it had: I wish they put a small hanger or magnet for the scooper. I rigged up a tiny command hook right above the product name.
1 month update: consistently drops 9 ice cubes every 8 minutes. Perfect for small parties if you start full. I really like this unit.

Great value for the money. Perfect for a small dinner party--say 4-6 adults. Fill it in the morning and run it. Empty into an ice bucket at party time and refill with water to run during party--you won't run out of ice! I paid full price and get/got zero for this review.

review_title: Literally saved me hundreds of dollars
review_text:
My old Kenmore washer fit all the symptoms of broken coupling, wouldn't spin, but water functions were fine. There are even audio clips you can listen to to help you diagnose the issue! I watched a video and it looked easy enough. This is the part where I tell you that I feel handy when I hang curtain rods or say, a picture. So this was a big challenge for me. I followed the video and verified that indeed, one of the brackets was completely cracked. I ordered the replacement via Prime, and two days later my washing machine was working again. It is definitely easier to remove the part then put it back in, but it still only took me about 30 minutes to carefully put it back together.

One note on putting it back together: I apparently didn't tighten something somewhere correctly, and the machine was jerking violently when it stopped spinning. I removed the casing and double checked all of my work, and it worked perfectly after I did so.

My washing machine is old and will need to be replaced at some point I am sure-- but I like that this very affordable part can keep it running for who knows how much longer (knock on wood).

review_title: Everything I needed and expected for the price!!!
review_text:
I bought this little washer over two months of tedious internet research. I needed a washing machine for my small two bedroom apartment and to do my sons' laundry and my own. There are many portable washing machines out there that are larger or smaller with varying functions and prices, however this machine seemed to fit my needs the best and it was the cheapest!. I just needed a small machine that would wash a reasonable amount of clothes with little to no hassle. I had read some of the other feedback about the machines noisyness, leakness, and hasslesome bottom plate, and extremely small basket and here is what I found....

I ordered the machine and had it within 7 days, I found that reasonable as i did not pay for shipping, it was also delivered with no damage to the machine or the box, I had it shipped fedex so i was able to track it daily.

The machine was very easy to put together out of the box, all I required was a phillips head screw driver. The bottom plate was hasslesome to install but I got it on, after that the rest was cake, I had it up and running within 22 minutes total.

I did a quick wash cycle and the machine ran smooth and strong, adding and draining water as nessacary. I didn't find the machine to be any noisier than any other washing appliance, the machine did rattle slightly durring the spin cycle but I have an area rug underneath it so it was neither noisy or disturbing to me. I experienced no leaks durring this cycle.

the clothes came out clean and wrung out, I was actually very impressed.

The basket size is actually larger than it may seem, I was able to fit into the machine about 3/4 of a standard wash!!!!!

All in all for the price and expectation I gave this machine 5 stars because it does what it say it will do, I have not experienced any hassles with it as of yet and actually I am more than pleased with the machine. I now look forward to never going to the laundry mat again or piled up laundry. I can see in the future having to go to the laundry mat once a month or two months for haevy blankets and rugs but all in all this little machine has handled my washes fine, to include sheets, light weight blankets, and jeans!!! Just distribute the loads carefully, remember one light weight blanket may mean one wash!!!

I am very pleased with this machine!!!! If you would like to see some pictures of it hooked up to the sink so you can get some perspective on it check out my face book page...jaime billiel in charlestown nh...............

UPDATE 2015

Hello all as of my last review I may have told you that I moved and gave my machine to my sister whom till this day FIVE YEARS LATER is still using the little machine :)...... Since then I moved to an apt and purchased a full size set, I met a man and we moved in together to a place with no hook ups so geuss what..... I PURCHASED ANOTHER ONE!!!!!!!!!!!!!! AND USED It for TWO MORE YEARS!!!!!!! Then I bought my very OWN HOUSE with a full size pair (still with my man). And I still HAVE that little machine! LOL

I have an elderly woman who wants to buy it but I dont know if she will follow through or not.

The point of my update, two machines, five years, no problems, still going strong. I may just keep the mini machine if the lady doesnt come to get it for back up, or sell it in a yard sale!!!!!!!!

review_text: My husband and I agree this K Cup rack is one of the best purchases we've made for our home - along with the Keurig itself. This is an awesome way for us to have "his" and "hers" displays that change with ease (the swivel design seems to be perfectly balanced...easy with one hand, but doesn't swivel on its own).  It's also very easy to clean.  The brushed-look silver parts are plastic but don't look too cheap next to stainless steel.  Ours is kept in a busy area of the kitchen and it's frequently splashed with coffee, grease, pancake batter, and the like, but everything just wipes right off.  I have several friends and family members who also own Keurig coffee makers and they have various OTHER types of holders and racks for their K cups.  They have ALL commented to me that they really like ours better and wish they had waited before going for the popular circular chrome carousel or the drawer-style one.  I really believe this is the best option for K cups.  I honestly love it!  In fact, this is one of very few times I've reviewed an item on Amazon that I purchased elsewhere. review_title: Great if you like wet clothes
review_text:
I've had many different driers over the years, and they've all dried clothes. The only differences were capacity, heat source, and features. It didn't matter the capacity, the heat source (gas or electric), or the features, they all had one thing in common, they dried your clothes. The permanent press cycles are nice, the cool down cycles are nice, infinite temperature settings are nice, but they are all worthless if it doesn't ultimately dry your clothes in a reasonable amount of time.

Then there's this drier. It is the absolute worst drier I have ever used. It will not dry a load of clothes on one dry cycle. Doesn't matter how many clothes are in the drier, how long the cycle is, the temperature of the cycle, items never come out dry. And I don't mean a little dampness or slight cool-to-the-touch around the waist line, I mean wet. It always takes at least 2 cycles, and often more, to get them dry. Especially towels. I will be up half the night restarting the drier every 75 minutes or so just to get one load dry! It must have 15 different drying cycle types, and it doesn't matter which one you use, everything is still is wet on completion.

This is the only computerized drier I've ever purchased, and it will be the last. Give me a good old mechanical dial for the amount of time and a 3-position switch for setting the temperature any day.

review_title: A little more work, but you get your favorite coffee and it's WAY more economical than purchasing the Kcups
review_text:
It was pointed out to me that purchasing the KCups that are prefilled is like spending $60 a pound on coffee that is already stale by the time you brew it! Whether it is actually $60/lb I don't know, but you are playing a premium for the convenience of coffee that is not as fresh as if you put your own freshly-ground coffee in.

So I purchased some coffee I like from a local roastery and have been using it. The coffee tastes WAY better than the prefilled KCups you buy - regardless of the brand, and I've tried them all. If you think about it, the tiny bit of coffee, already ground, has been sitting in these KCups for how long? and they aren't vacuum packed or anything, and there is usually a 1/4 inch of airspace in them as well which doesn't bode well for the coffee in terms of freshness.

You do have to clean the filter after each use, but it's really easy and you can compost the grounds.

In addition, if you drink one cup of coffee each day, you are saving our planet from 365 KCups per year!!

review_text:
I've always been very skeptical of anything bearing the "As Seen On TV" label, as the Wonder Washer did at one time. But when I moved into an apartment and started plunking down $1.50 for each load of clothes in a small coin-operated machine, I decided to give it a try, and I'm glad I did.

After a few tries I found that the Wonder Washer isn't up to handling jeans or sheets (the latter won't fit). Parts of it are a bit lightly constructed and I would be cautious about overloading it or expecting the plastic bucket and lid to put up with rough handling (to my knowledge, replacements are not available). I finally settled on using my machine strictly for bleach loads--a tablespoon of bleach does the job and as a one-person household, I average a "white load" a bit more often than once a week. In less than a year, the Wonder Washer has more than paid for itself in bleach and detergent savings along with avoided coin-op loads.

The only gripe I have with the Wonder Washer is that it has no spin cycle and does not drain itself so the bucket must be removed, emptied, and refilled for a rinse cycle (I've found that I get the best rinse if I fill and empty the bucket once before refilling it and putting it back on the base). Clothes come out of the machine saturated and must be squeezed out even before machine drying or, as I generally do, hanging on the shower rod (when the humidity is low, they'll dry overnight--when it's higher, they won't).

So....using the Wonder Washer is more of a hands-on process than using a fully-automatic machine. But you can't beat the price, and if you can accept its limitations, it will serve you well.

review_text:
Samsung Original at top of Photo, Replacement purchased at bottom.

Longevity: Only time will tell on this grading of the part, however that is dependent on many factors, many out of the manufactures control.

Quality: Original element wire diameter 0.042", Replacement element 0.042", Insulators different shape but provide adequate standoff and support, Mounting frame: Original has larger openings than Replacement. Original element reads 14 Ohm, Replacement element reads 10 Ohm, insignificant difference.

Ease of Installation: Totally dependent on installer preforming task. Took care to ensure skin oils did not touch Replacement element, not necessary just how I work. Verified all element parts did not touch any of the mounting bracket or heater housing components visually and with Ohm meter. During this install the dryer was completely disassembled from the front and all lint components vacuumed, wiped and blown clean, vent hoses cleaned or replaced, regular maintenance preformed every 12-18 months in this dryer.

Price: OEM from several locations ~ $80-120 This unit under $25.

Initial Use: Element will have an odor during the first use, even in a completely cleaned heater housing. This time it lasted about 15 minutes during a test phase with no clothes in dryer and element heat set to medium.

Shipment guarantee made by AMAZON - Not Met, Since shipping included in price with Prime, I have, nor desire any recourse.

Overall: Considering the large price difference from OEM to this replacement and reasonable visual similarity of components, if life of element turns out to 12-24 months in an already 8 year old machine and this is the first heat element exchange, my experience says that is a fair exchange of $$$'s to function.

review_text:
When you install this filter, does it not go on all the way, turn about a 1/4-turn then pop back off? Have you even tried other knock-off brand filters and the same thing happens?

I've got an update for you.

Mine did and I thought it was a problem with the filter. I ordered several extras, including knock-off brands and none of them would seat correctly.

Turrns out it was the receiving-end on the fridge itself, "Water Filter Assembly Head" not allowing the replacement filters to securely lock in place. I called LG and had an LG technician order the part and install the new one, now we are back up and running after countless attempts at trying different filters. He said this is a common issue with the LG Fridge.

Hope this helps!!!!

review_title: I ordered this part and then read some more reviews ...
review_text: I ordered this part and then read some more reviews on here and was convinced I was going to receive a cheap imitation. So I went to my local Whirlpool Authorized Dealer and got the part for $90 and installed it and got my dryer working again. I had planned to return this item after I received it. When the order came from Amazon, it was the EXACT same part I got at my authorized dealer for 3 times the cost. The box was the exact same, down to the sticker on the side that said "Made in Mexico". Even the "Authorized Dealer" box said that. The part itself is exactly the same, the same markings on the part, the wire looked exactly the same size as the original, everything. I am going to keep the part from Amazon to have on hand as a spare for the next time it goes out. Obviously I can't say I have tested it out but I am convinced it is the same exact part I got from the dealer so I would use it with confidence. I only wish I had waited for the Amazon part to come, I spent 3 times the amount of money at my local "Authorized Dealer". In the picture I have the boxes from my dealer and from Amazon. Already had the part itself installed so can't do a side by side of them, but they are exactly the same.

review_text:
This unit does fit my Kitchenaid (Whirlpool), but when comparing it to the original unit, I doubt this is an OEM product.

In short, if I needed to buy an ice maker again, I would either spend the big dollars to be sure to get an OEM unit or buy the cheaper units that do not claim to be OEM.

Here is a brief list of what's different between the original unit and this product...

Original: 3 watt motor.
This product: 1.5 watt motor. A less powerful motor may fail sooner.

Original: Teflon coated.
This product: Appears to be painted.

Original: Fins (heat sink)which helps it make ice faster.
This product: No fins, which does make it lighter and a little smaller

The original unit has a slightly larger heating element than this product.

It appears that all the parts are interchangeable. In my case, the original unit's heating element burned out. So I replaced it with this product's heating element without any problems.
product_title: Supco RIM597 Universal Icemaker

review_title: A great addition to any kitchen
review_text:
I ordered the NuWave mini when I ordered my NuWave Pro since it was free and only paid $30 shipping through the manufacturer site. Initially, I was thinking it would be a good gift for someone since I now have the Pro....but....I'm liking the Mini more when it's just me at home cooking a quick dinner.

First, I find the $90+ price to be way over the top. I'd find $39-$49 acceptable. Price isn't an indicator of quality, but an indicator of what you can/can't use it for. Funny enough you can buy the parts separately for ~$70.

Secondly, make sure you keep the recommended cooking chart handy. I'm finding on average to add ~2 minutes per side to the cooking instructions. My first frozen boneless skinless chicken thigh came out still pinkish in the middle. Adding 2 minutes more per side did the trick the next night. The chicken was moist, done, and tasty.

The electronic keypad seems durable and the timer is loud enough to be heard in another room. Good thing is, when the timer alerts, the NuWave turns off. No danger of overcooking this way.

The dome seems to be sturdy enough, but I'm hoping if my dome cracks, it does so while in the first year. If not, it's a measely $12 to replace.

The rack can be flipped to get food closer to the heating element or further away by a margin of about an inch. Not much difference.

The Mini is is ideal for 1-2 people. I can fit two chicken pieces or two medium steaks, or two fish fillets. On the cooking videos, Chef Jennifer fills in around the meat with veggies. I would eat more veggies than can fit on the rack with 2 pieces of meat. Thus, why it's a mini. But it cooks them well with a little adjustment on cooking times. I always start frozen and it cooks very well.

The variety of foods you can cook in the Mini is only limited by the size of the food. If it's just me cooking for me, I can fit a piece of meat and veggies in and have dinner in about 15 to 20 minutes. Cleanup for the NuWave mini is SO EASY. While it's dishwasher safe (top rack for dome), I'll only hand wash it in the hopes of the dome lasting longer. It's easy enough so why not?

Due to the Mini size, there aren't any official accessories to add to the NuWave mini but it does what it's designed to do very well. I think if the price dropped below $50 for this model, they would sell like hotcakes.

A final plus to the NuWave brand is their excellent website where you can find replacement parts for this model. With your purchase, you also get free access to the NuWave cooking club that has recipes, videos, and tips for how to use your NuWave. For a budding ManChef, this really helps give me ideas.

Enjoy! I have. :)
product_title: NuWave 20102 Oven, Mini

review_title: Confusion between model numbers led to me order the thing I didn't want.
review_text:
Update: Bumped the stars to 4. This is a nice product. I have been using the temp controller for a couple of days now, with my chick brooder heat lamp. Working great. I would only knock 1/2 a star off for the model # thing, but, of course, not an option. Happy with the item overall. Just wish it had the wifi I had originally been after.

Knocked off stars for the ambiguous model numbers. Will update stars accordingly, or not, based on actual usage once I have used it.

I bought this to use the temp controller with a brooder heat lamp, and an EcoGlow brooder, and was trying to get the model with wifi so I could monitor and adjust when away from home. I have a thing about not wanting to burn my house down.

The single wifi unit, with the SAME model number, would have take a MONTH to be delivered to me. Needed it ASAP. So I ordered this one, with the SAME model number, mistakenly thinking they were the same. Didn't really need the humidity monitor, but having the temp controller a full month earlier was a big deal. Alas, I could have had the non-wifi temp controller alone for $35, instead of $70, in the same couple of days time.

I'll blame myself for not catching that there is no mention of wifi capability in this item description. Both units having the ITC-308 model number is confusing.

So make sure you are getting what you think you are. It was a super easy mistake to make.

As for the meters themselves, I have just begun unboxing and will be setting it up for my chicks in the next day or two. Initial impression is that they appear to be well-made controllers and good quality. Not quite what I wanted for my chicks, but they will be living outdoors before I could get a wifi version in hand. So I will live with it. I have no doubt it will be fine for use with seed mats and the like, so it will see considerable usage one way or another.

review_title: Very similar performance to a paper filter
review_text: I got this because I wanted to use my Aeropress to strain loose tea that had been brewed and didn't want to waste more paper filters. It works great for that. I use the one with larger holes (you can look through the filters side by side at a light and see which has the bigger holes, but otherwise it is hard to tell them apart) for tea. Since the tea was brewed already, I didn't care how quickly it would drain, but it was still pretty slow and needed to use the plunger to get the tea through in a reasonable amount of time, with about the same resistance I was used to with paper filters. To see how it did with coffee, I tried that too and it is great, again almost the same as paper filters. Using the smaller holes for coffee, it is no problem pouring the water in and then setting the plunger and letting it steep (without doing inverted). Very easy to clean when you are cleaning the Aeropress anyway. The filters are non-magnetic, so probably actual stainless steel. For what these are, two perforated metal disks, it is a little expensive, but they work very well.

I tried to contact both seller and amazon customer service and they did nothing about it. I bought it at the begining of the summer but my kitchen was only done few weeks ago and I did not know how loud this thing is. I guess once you are pass your 30 day warranty you are dead for a seller and amazon customer service. There are items you are just not able to test within 30 days.
The hood is cute and I have no complaints for the looks. It came with a little dinge that I only saw after I installed it, and I still did not care. But because of this noise, I guess I have to go buy another one. Don't buy the hood unless your kitchen is ready to go.

review_title: Enjoy spending half a day tearing your drier apart every 6 months or so? definitely buy this kit!
review_text:
when it was about 12 years old our samsung drier started making horrible, terrifying screeching noises. At first I thought maybe it was just hitting puberty and its voice changing, but after consulting the great DIY repair oracle (youtube), I figured it must be one of the components included in this kit, and bought it, foolishly ignoring the negative reviews.

when I got the drier taken apart (no small feat in my 6x9 laundry room where it's stacked on top the washer and surrounded by an immobile shelving unit), it was apparent that only the front rollers were shot, so i just replaced those with the ones that came in this kit. And concluded my saturday afternoon putting everything back together while experimenting with some new expletives.

fast forward 6 months and the screeching started again. "It must be the rear ones this time!" I told myself, sure that there was NO WAY the 6 month old front rollers could be shot already.

after another expletive-filled disassembly process, I was quite dismayed to find that indeed, it was the 6-month old rollers that were shot. the others (OEM) were still perfect, and the drum belt was fine.

In the photos, the 6-month old parts are at the top, and the new ones at the bottom. As you can see, the bearings in these rollers literally just disintegrated--in 6 months! there were no bearings and no discernable metal pieces from the roller's axis. the axle itself was ok but the rest of the assembly literally turned to dust (which, btw, was all over the inside of the drier housing). Impressive!

I had bought another similarly-priced set to replace them, and didn't have the heart to put the whole thing on hold to order a set of OEM parts, so I used those. Check back in 6 months to see if they meet the same fate.

review_title: Danby Wine Coolers - Caveat Emptor - Planned Obsolescence?
review_text:
We purchased the Dancy 54 Bottle Wine Cooler in stainless steel and within 4 months of operation, the unit ceased to cool and one side overheated.

As Danby claims to have a one year warranty, we called Danby and found that since we had purchased the cooler at the beginning of our remodel and did not install the unit until the renovation was complete, the warranty would not be honored as we were a mere two weeks past our warranty expiration date.

We let Danby know that the unit had only been in use for under four months, whereupon we asked if Danby would not honor the warranty, would they at least sell us another unit at cost, at which point Danby stated that they would not. Too bad, so sad, you'll just have to fork up another $900.00 for another unit, sucker.

PLEASE NOTE that you cannot get Danby wine or beverage coolers serviced, states Danby customer service, as they are "contained units" which means the entire unit has to be replaced under warranty, not just the cooling elements. If it breaks during the first year, they will OSTENSIBLY send you a new unit. But who knows if they will even honor their one year warranty, based upon their reluctance to handle the simplest of customer service issues with us. It took days to get to a representative and even then they completely refused to stand behind their product.

After several tries with Danby customer service to no avail, we contacted the President of Danby, whom we were sure would make this situation right but were completely ignored. I'll bet he gets a lot of calls and mail about this very thing. Do yourself a favor and save on shipping - put $900 IN A PILE AND BURN IT rather than buy any Danby product. Better yet, buy another brand, as we did. Our new cooler works just fine and it can be repaired if it breaks, as it is 21st century technology. Our new unit was cheaper, too, and is better looking.

Come on! It's a little fridge, not rocket science, and they can't get a $900 wine cooler to work for more than four months without breaking down? I'd be interested to hear from any other Danby wine cooler purchasers as I have a suspicion that these units are manufactured to meet planned obsolescence of approximately one year as a means of bilking the consumer.

Yes, you heard me, Danby, if you read these reviews: Your customer service reps were too practiced in their denial of warranty coverage for us to believe that this is an uncommon occurrence. We'd also like to hear from you, Danby, since we've not received a reply to any of our communications for several months now.

CAVEAT EMPTOR!

review_title: Don't buy another cheap dishwasher!  A good one is worth every penny!
review_text:
I have to start by saying that we bought this because it matches the refrigerator and ended up getting the mid-level slate washer because the handle matches our fridge and for a couple hundred more you get the stainless steel case.

We have only had it for a few weeks now, but boy do our dishes look so much clearer and cleaner. I read some reviews that mentioned that it was difficult to hook up, but it was the same as any dishwasher I have ever installed. The only thing we needed was a hose adapter 90 degree elbow to install it and some wire nuts. You can buy a dishwasher install kit at Lowes or any other home improvement store that will include what you need.

The only thing that surprised me is how long the cycle takes. Almost a couple hours for the regular cycle. However, we run it at night and don't do more than one load per day so, no worries. In the past, I have bought a few cheap dishwashers and I am very happy that I didn't do it again. Think about it, this thing affects every meal and drink you have at your house. Spend some money on a good one so you don't waste your time and money washing dishes twice, or getting sick from the residue the washer leaves behind.

Not only does it clean the dishes very well, but the door springs work well, it makes almost no noise when running and the silverware basket comes out and goes back in easily which is nice. My old dishwashers made it difficult for whatever reason.

We are now only using the 3 in one cascade packets and it is much easier and again, the dishes look amazing. Even my 8 year old daughter mentioned how much cleaner our cups look after just two times through the wash. I definitely recommend this washer, it has been wonderful so far. Also, it shipped quickly and came in perfect condition.
product_title: GE GDT580SMFES 24" Slate Fully Integrated Dishwasher - Energy Star

review_title: BEWARE FALSE ADVERTISING: 2 pack only!  Claims its a 3 pack, but only 2 will be delivered.
review_text:
The product is decent. Its a good fit to the original filter cup and works well. However, it says this is a 3 pack. The label on the ziplock baggie says its a 3 pack. But the baggie is only big enough for the two. And that was the only 2 they sent.

I thought it could have been a shipping mistake, things happen. Amazon doesn't have a complaint item for "too few items shipped". So I simply returned it, hoping that it was simply a one time mistake.

I was wrong. I sent back the first two and the sent me a new package. Only 2 again the second shipment. This label also says 3 pack. There is no way 3 will fit the labeled baggie. These were the pictures of the entire contents of the second shipment of this "3 pack".

I would have been OK paying for a 2 pack. And to be honest, I want my coffee enough that I'm simply eating the loss. Its not worth the pain of fighting for a $4 piece of plastic.

However, they deserve the 1 star, and I will NOT be doing any more business with them even if my cup breaks. I'll find other means if need be. I'd be more likely to get rid of the Keurig than deal with this scammer again.

Feel free to buy them. Product does work as advertised, but know you will only get two.

review_text: Easy to install.  Check youtube. for examples.  My dryer access is from the back.  I recommend you turn off power at breaker box.  Remove the back of dryer. Take a picture so you know how the belt is routed through the idler. Compare your idler assembly to the one to be ordered.  (There are left and right versions, don't order the wrong one. )  At this point I oiled the old idler to finish a couple loads and wait for delivery.  New belt came in 2 days, I reopened back and replaced assembly as follows:  Slip the belt off the wheel.  Loosen the bolt holding the idler assembly  and replace with new assembly.  Note:  This bold is designed to be tight while allowing the assembly to move, so make sure it moves after the bolt is tight.  Replace belt, back and power.

review_text:
I purchased this dryer from abc warehouse, not amizon because of cost for shipping, but its the same dryer anyway. so I am going to cover 3 things about this dryer, First is size, second is venting and filters, and last, is it worth the money.

First, size. this dryer is close to 1/4 size of a regular dryer, and this means it is great for a small apartment like mine. the dryer is short and the controls are at the bottom of the dryer so to save my back I bought a wire 5 tier shelf and used 1/2 of it with a shelf on the bottom and one close to the top. bottom for clothes basket and detergent storage, and top for the dryer, being 40 lbs and heavier with wet clothes I chose a shelf with 80+ lbs per shelf. I used the adjustable feet of the dryer to screw in from under the shelf to hold it securely. Now the controls are within reach and the dryer is more accessible.

second, venting and filters. I attached the plastic vent to the back of the dryer and face this up toward the ceiling. after about 2 months of use, be sure to clean around the dryer. Dust and lint will accumulate. there is a noticeable amount of moisture in the air when in use but it only lasts from a few min after the dryer starts until about 20 min before the dryer stops. I have noticed no reason to vent this dryer outside, except for maybe in the hotter seasons where drying clothes conflicts with the efficiency of air-conditioners. For the filters they are basically felt. so after 7 to 8 months with the original filter material I bought a felt piece at the arts and crafts isle at walmart and one sheet made both the front and rear filters. On cleaning the filters, use a lint roller to remove the lint build up after about every second or third use.

last, is it worth the money, Yes. for drying clothes I load the dryer no more than 2/3 full and it takes 200 min (dial straight down) for a full load. for jeans and on hot days where I don't want to run a heat source and the air conditioning, I bought a wood hanging rack and I hang the clothes and jeans on these with a fan on them, making sure to flip the clothes after a few hours. Then after the clothes are dry, I run the dryer with no heat for 20 min to "soften" up the clothes and remove wrinkles. I have noticed very little in the cost of electricity for this dryer, about $7 to $10 a month. And that is the same cost as going to a laundry-mat.

This ends my review. No noises no problems, just a little maintenance and care.

I got this dishwasher to use in my RV, since I‚Äôll be living in RV 24/7 until I can find/buy a new home to replace the home I just sold. So since I was stuck living in the RV I wanted all the luxuries I had in my brick/mortar home, which included a dishwasher which my RV wasn‚Äôt equipped with. After reading all the reviews this dishwasher sounded the best.

It‚Äôs was so easy to install-just place on countertop-plug into electric outlet-pour water in top hole (or you can do the hose water hook up)-then push start. Yeah that easy!

And it cleans like anything. It has upper and lower spray arms that spray the heck out of everything. I use the express wash cuz the normal wash was way to much. It even has a dry cycle! But beware, unless you have small pots/pans, it‚Äôs doubtful those will fit inside washer, my 10‚Äô fry pan does not. But you can fit 4 place settings=dishes, bowls, cups, glasses & cutlery in it with no problem. An added bonus is the blue light it emits when starting & stopping is kind of cool!

I wholly recommend this dishwasher and very very happy & pleased with it.

review_title: Fixed GE GSS25QGTGWW Cooling & Water Dispenser!
review_text:
I used this evaporator fan motor to fix my GE refrigerator model GSS25QGTGWW.

The original fan completely failed after more than 10 years of use.

Replacing the fan fixed the cooling problem that developed over a weak ago and also fixed my water dispenser! For years I had problems with my water dispenser freezing up. This solved both issues. Apparently my previous fan was having issues for several years, but was still running, so I didn't know it needed replacement.

An early symptom of an evaporator fan that is not performing well is a frozen water dispenser line. This is especially the case with the GE refrigerator model GSS25QGTGWW.

A symptom of an evaporator fan that has completely died is that the refrigerator will be very icy near the bottom on both the refrigerator side and the freezer side, and not cold enough on the top of both sides.

A simple test to confirm the issue is caused by the fan not running at all is to leave the freezer open for 3 minutes. At that point GE says the fan should always turn on, and mine did not. This could also indicate a problem with the main controller board's fan control circuit, but that's rare, and for me that was not the case, fortunately, because the main controller board costs a lot more to replace.

The repair was easy but time consuming. There were a lot of parts to remove to get to the evaporator fan motor.

The new fan is VERY QUIET compared to the original and seems to be functioning better overall than the original did before it died. Prior to my original fan dying, it was very noisy for many years.

So far things are working great.

Definitely worth the money. My refrigerator is working like new again after installing the fan motor.

review_text: We purchased this refrigerator in June of 1014.  I debated between this model and the model that had four doors, but eventually got this one because it had more room inside. In retrospect, I might have done better with purchasing the four door model because in order to access the large pull out drawer it is necessary to open both the doors, which, in my mind, wastes electricity. But that is a choice I made that in no way affects the performance of the refrigerator.  We have not had any issues yet with the refrigerator and overall I am very pleased with it.  Yes, it will at times make noise, but to me that's not an annoyance.  It produces a lot of ice and is able to keep up with the needs of my large family, which is a big plus. I love all of the room inside the refrigerator and freezer and it is very easy to organize everything in all the compartments.  My 7-year-old grandson is able to access the freezer easily to get popsicles, which saves me time. He is also able to access everything in the refrigerator as we have put the items he likes down toward the bottom. The outside is easy to keep clean--I use furniture polish to clean it and it works like a charm. If something gets spilled, it only spills on the shelf and clean up is pretty easy.  The drawers open easily and seem to be pretty sturdy. I replaced a refrigerator that fell to pieces (drawers fell off tracks, pieces of plastic on shelves broke off, water and ice dispenser buttons broke off, etc,) with this one, and thus far is has held up quite well with my very rough family. Overall, I love this refrigerator and have no complaints whatsoever.

review_title: Awesome dual-fuel range!  Some things to consider.
review_text:
I went back and forth before finally deciding to purchase this range. I received a 10% discount off list, which means I paid North of $2,600. That is a LOT of money in my world.

Imagine my surprise, when the range was delivered and I discovered that it required a 220V outlet! Now this oversight was 100% my fault. I just want to prevent others from learning this the hard way (like I did). Furthermore, this GE Cafe dual-fuel range requires a 40 amp circuit! My electric dryer requires only 20 amps!

So $415 later (the cost of running a 50 amp circuit) I could cook!

Cooktop: You will want to buy "Simple Green" (degreaser) & a bunch of the fiber non-metalic scrubbers. Simple Green's instructions say that it can be used straight or diluted 1:10 with water. You'll want to use it full strength. This range has the most infuriating of all types of stainless steel - trust me. This range will work your butt off to get/keep clean. This range is such a pain to clean - it will change the way you cook. You will turn things down - so they don't spit. You will use lids - when you never used to use lids. On the positive side, I really like the oblong burner in the middle & the high output front right burner.

Griddle: Very good. The griddle grate is super dense & large. Grease flows away from your foods into a well designed catch. In fact, the tendency for grease to move away from foods and into the grease catch can be frustrating when trying to cook breakfast "Waffle House" style. However, I'll take on a George Foreman grill any day!

Oven: Superlative! The touch screen controls are elegant & intuitive! The oven has a digital temperature readout that tells you the temperature and shows you the elements in use via a picture! Very cool. The (2) oven lights & the crystal clear dual-pane window allow you to see everything that's going on. Anything you bake, convection bake, convection roast - will exceed your expectations!

That's it. It was a rocky road ($$$) to get here, but I love my GE Cafe.
