review_title: Overal does wash & dry but involves a lot of maintenance and has a lot of issues for the price.
review_text:
So I read a lot of reviews before purchasing this and will now contribute based on my experience so far.

I did not purchase this new from Amazon but used off of Craigslist (about 1/2 the price) - supposedly it was bought in June of this year so it is only about 6 months old and still under warranty. The owner was selling it because he is a landlord who bought it for his tenant and the tenant did not like how long the cycles took.

I bought it because we have an old house and very little room - it was kind of a compromise between myself and my partner as a better option might have been for us to purchase separate compact washer & dryer but he wanted a larger capacity.

This machine is large - going from a compact portable washer to this was a big difference - make sure you have measured your space before purchasing. The combo will help us preserve vertical space but it did not help at all in floor/hall space.

So here is what I have found so far...

PROS:

* does essentially what it is supposed to do - washes with very little water and definitely dries (I have not tried to overload this and have probably only filled it between 1/3 to 2/3's so far but clothes have come out more than enough dry (on "normal" setting).

* feels fancy and fun with the lights & noise

* takes up half the space of two full-size machines

* a good amount of options for different kinds of clothes - although initially seems kind of complicated it's pretty straightforward to set up - and because it's front load will be pretty gentle on your clothes

* clothes come out dry when they're done ( no need to be there to change them from washer to dryer )

* being able to set it on timer is nice - I am not comfortable letting this be on while not at home yet but it's nice to set it to go off an hour or two before I wake up

CONS

* this is a very expensive machine and for the cost I would expect it to work MUCH better out of the box than it does - it will require regular cleaning & maintenance to keep it in top working order - much more than a regular dryer would (I will go into details below)

* it is difficult to level; or I should say - I have leveled it pretty well based on my level but it still started shimmying away when I had a larger load in - we do have the challenge of very out of whack old house floors but this machine seems to have issues when it comes to getting it leveled correctly. I found a good post here on how to deal with this (and it's on my to-do list): [...]

* I was pleasantly surprised that the first load I put in estimated less than 2 hours time (it was not a large load but based on what I'd read I was expecting worse) - however (and I have read this an issue for others) - when it got down to 6 min left on the display it stopped at 6 min for about 15-20 min before finishing and moving on; I looked this up and found others having this issue - I am not sure if it's a maintenance issue of the dryer not working well enough or a sensor issue - some LG dryer reviews said you need to wipe the sensors off but on this machine I am not sure where this is; so far what I have done to try and alleviate this issue is 1) make sure to wipe the lint out of the door seal real well (not easy - more below on this); 2) do the drain pump maintenance (pretty easy); and just to make sure I have all my bases covered I am going to go ahead and take the machine apart to clean out where the lint supposedly gets stuck - since I haven't been the original owner - I'd like to see where it's at now before I have to do it again

* lint lint and more lint: you have probably already read this is an issue. it very much is an issue. you will need to wipe the rubber door seal after each use and it is not an easy simple & quick thing to do as the seal has a deep fold in it that is not easy to get your fingers into and also lint will get stuck under the edge of the seal so you kind of have to go around and pull this up. plan on this taking a good 5 min and not being a fun task - this is an issue that really makes me have to give the machine a lower review - LG REALLY SHOULD DO SOMETHING TO TAKE CARE OF THE LINT collection because there is essentially none and, as you have probably read, it leads to a larger issue of the dryer eventually not working and requiring you to take apart the machine in order to clean it out (unless you want to hire someone) but a great instructions on how to do this are here: [...]

* the door rattle on high spin cycle - this is another big deal breaker for me in regards to giving this a good review. I have read it as being an issue with other people too - as far as i'm concerned there's no excuse for this - it is loud and annoying. I may be able to get it to be less of an issue if I can get the machine better leveled - and I have also heard of people making their own dampener by stuffing some cardboard in between the door and machine - either way - not cool LG. basically there is not proper padding between the door and it has wiggle room (when shut you can kind of push on it yourself and hear how it will sound if it happened multiple times).

* another note on noise: as others have wrote - the pump is noisy. nothing to say except that yes, it is, and it will go on and off throughout the whole cycle; think of it as a loud humidifier or old loud fridge motor noise; when the pump is not going off it's very quiet; our bedroom is upstairs and the noise will not be loud enough to wake us up - and if you have well insulated walls it may not be an issue for you either - but don't go into it thinking that this thing is going to be quiet if you have thin walls or floors

* smell: it smells a bit moldy/musty; I am just running Tub Clean for the first time today - will update later to let you know if the smell is alleviated - I am going to assume that the previous owner may not have done this at all.

* other random issues which I can live with: the instructions say to hold the spinsense button down for 3 seconds to activate - this is not working for me ( I read somewhere that it won't work if you have the dryer set to cycle on - I will try again and see if that solves it ); when I went to use the Spin/Dry cycle the timer showed it as going to take 5+ hours even though I put in a very small load and there was no way it should have taken that long - for some reason the machine didn't run it's own sensor but just automatically goes to 5 hours - you can solve this by choosing the timed dry instead "normal" or "more"

Overall I would NOT recommend purchasing this machine at full price. There are too many maintenance and glitchy issues to spend this kind of money. But, if you can find it on sale or used - it might be what you need to deal with space issues. Just make sure you understand that you will have to spend time to maintain it correctly and yes, the overall cycle times on a full load are going to be much longer than they would be on a normal washer/dryer. There is a big learning curve on the tiny things you run into that won't really be covered in the manual and for which you'll have to consult other reviews, internet search, etc to solve on your own. If you're the kind of person who doesn't mind doing this - then this machine may work out for you. But if you're looking for a low-maintenance machine that you won't need to worry about - this isn't it.

review_text: 5 stars AFTER making modifications. This thing needs an internal fan-it varies 12 degrees from top to bottom without one. beer temp runs about 42 degrees (not cold enough for my taste). adding a tower cooler w fan and placing at back changed beer temp to 39 degrees. with inly 2 degree difference between top and bottom.  next-to get this thing to really get to 33 degree beer-the thermostat needs calibrated.  just inside the door i the thermostat-held on by three screws.  take it off and remove it from the cover.  there us an inset screw on one end of it.  turn it clockwise to make it colder.  i turned it as far as it would go and then put it back on. i can adjust it from 30 to 37 now.  also-do yourself a favor and get an indoor outdoor thermometer-put the outdoor sensor inside. you can the put the thermometer viewer wherever is cinvenient to monitor your kegorator temp. its perfec for me now.  hope this helps someone.

review_text: You know how home wine coolers have a compressor that usually dies in a few years?  Well, I have one that's over 7 years old and still working, but the seal on the door has turned to hard rubber - it's like plastic!  So after finding I could not get a replacement rubber door seal, I looked around and found these and ordered this item, using two of the right-angle pieces for two opposing of the four corners, and just making a 45-degree cut and sticking it all on with 3M 5200 marine adhesive/sealer.  Works like a champ....well, at least til the compressor gives up the ghost!  (I just threw the two unneeded pieces away.)

review_text:
Although I am not surprised that there are not reviews for this washing machine here, since it should be purchased from a local retailer who should install it, but I am really surprised that there are no reviews at all.
I replaced a 17 year old Maytag top loader with this machine and am not looking back. The old Maytag was still running, although was leaking and grinding. I looked at many machines that would fit into my small first story laundry room and this was the smallest.
I wanted a front loader to wash comforters, pillows, and cal king bedding and this is doing it wonderfully. It doesn't have all the fancy cycles that the others have and is not a big looker, but I wash tennis shoes, backpacks and rugs like everything. Best part if that I no longer make the semi annual trip to the laundromat with all the bulky items. My blacks that I wear to work, yes I work in a medical laboratory that wears black, are staying in better shape than everyone else's at work, also.
On another note the dryers that the company sells to match are huge also. I can wash four mens, two womens, and six teenagers jeans at once without wrinkles after drying. If you are looking for a excellent machine that washes extremely well that also will last 20+ years this is it.
If you want a steam cycle with seven other cycles in a red or blue machine that will last for 8 years there are plenty of them in most appliance stores and big box stores. If you want a machine that cleans well, is dependable and truthfully is built like a tank this brand is it. We needed to tie the floor joists together and add a floor jack below the machine but on a cement floor this would not be necessary.
I have no relationship to this company but I did stop in at the dealer yesterday to tell them how happy I was with this purchase, hence this review today.

review_title: Arrived undamaged and works wonderfully so far!
review_text:
Thankfully unlike many reviewers here I had a much more pleasant delivery experience. My refrigerator arrived completely undamaged and it's absolutely stunning! There is so much space that 3 or 4 people could easily share this fridge. I have this upstairs in my bedroom so for 1 person I'm more than happy with how spacious the interior is, I also enjoy how you have a lot of adjustability with the shelving as well.

I've always had top freezers but I don't think I could ever go back! Not having to consistently bend over to grab lower fridge items has been a convenience I never realized I needed! The freezer shelves have an amazing amount of space as well. And its also nice to have drawers instead of just open space, I enjoy not having to worry about falling items when I open my freezer.

While the fridge is still new so far I couldn't be happier with my purchase! My food is perfectly cooled and frozen and I haven't noticed anything odd about my drinks frozen due to wonky temperature controls. I'll be sure to update my review in a few months time with how it holds up!

review_title: POINTLESS - MORE WORK THAN HAND WASHING -- NOTHING LIKE REAL WASHING MACHINE
review_text:
I'm astonished that so many shoppers gave this thing a good review. I can't begin to express how disappointed I am. It comes with tiny instructions that really don't tell you much. I had to go to the Amazon Q&A to figure out how to use it.

This is exactly how you use it...

1. Put cold (or if you want push it warm) water in the left half of the unit. It is small to begin with, and all the users say to fill it up half way.Do not use hot water, as it will warp the plastic. It comes with a very cheap hose that does not widen on the end, so there is no way to attach it to a faucet. I filled mine by hand with a pot.

2. Put in your clothing. I was able to fit one pair of teenager's jeans and two t-shirts. That maxxed it out.

3. Add detergent.

4. Set timer and let it swish the clothes around. I will admit it does that pretty well. The first time I used it I thought "Hey, this is cool!"

5. When it is done swishing, you have to drain the water using a switch. Then you have to remove the wet clothes from the left side and move it to the right side, which is the Spin Cycle. The spin part is only half the size of the washing part. So I could only spin one pair of kids jeans. And then two t-shirts. (water got all over the place during the spin cycle)

THEN YOU HAVE TO DO IT AGAIN....

6. The clothing is still soapy, so you have to put water again in the left side (using my pot again) and wash it again on the left side. Then do the spin cycle again to get the water out.

9. Then you have to hang it somewhere to dry.

This is so much more work than just using Woolite or something and doing it a sink.

Some other CONS -
It is kind of noisy, and I can not use it in my apartment. It must drive the people downstairs nuts.

I moves around as it functions. (there's a reason real washing machines are heavy)

CONCLUSION
It is nothing like a true washing machine. I hope it would help us while we are trapped in our NYC apartment during the pandemic, but it was useless.

I am returning it at some point. (when it is safe to go to the UPS store)

review_title: Nice Price & Working Fine... But May Require Modifications to Back Panel on SOME Model Refrigerators
review_text:
Just wanted to give a heads up for others. This valve is working well & it's nice to have a less expensive alternative to the factory part, but installation was not that simple in my Whirlpool Gold refrigerator.

From other reviews, it appears that this valve was a drop-in replacement for a lot of folks. But in my Whirlpool Gold refrigerator, (model GX2FHDXVQ02) the cover/access panel had to be modified to fit. The body of the valve is too large to fit thru the existing cut-out in the panel. I had to enlarge the cut-out with a pair of tin snips (Be careful not to cut away the mount point for the screws) & drill an additional hole for a 2nd mounting screw. This was simple enough to do for someone who is handy & has tools, but might be problematic for some.

Pros:
- Price
- Works well (full sized cubes again..)

Cons:
- Necessary to modify access panel to mount this (larger) valve
- Plenty of extra hardware included in the package to accomodate any water lines & connectors
- Valve is is noisier than the old was (At least in my case. Others have said that their replacement valve was quiet, so this may vary..)

review_title: So much quieter than the old bearing
review_text:
These new bearings are so much quieter than the OEM bearing that were going out on our washer. There is no way for me to be sure, but I think it spins faster now, too. In all fairness, our washer is going on ten years old, so the old ones did last a while. I expect these to last at least that long or until we replace this machine. The order arrived quickly and all the contents were very well packaged.

I watched a few vids on UToob to see how to take the machine apart. I really liked the one from Yellow Van Handyman. He disassembled the exact model we have and offered a some great tips and tricks for taking the machine apart and removing the tub and drum assembly.

That being said, Make sure you watch the Front Load Bearing(sellers) videos. There are some great tips and trick on the actual bearing removal and installation. On my first attempt, I did not get my seal seated all the way and when I reassembled the drum and tub, the drum did not spin freely. This was my fault and if I had watched the sellers videos first, I would have avoided this mistake. No harm done, just extra time and a few laughs at my expense.

HINT -- When you are driving you bearings out, I found that a standard 5 gallon bucket ( like the one the sheetrock compound comes in), works very well as a cradle and support. There are some tabs on the joining edge of the the rear section of the tub you must not damage. The 5 gallon bucket is wide enough and tall enough to hold the tub when working on both the inner and outer bearings.

Overall the process was easy for the average DIY person. You may want to get some help with removing the tub and drum, it is pretty heavy and bulky. Get a jar to put all the screws in, there are alot. I think the only tools I needed were a 7mm socket and driver, small flat head screwdriver, large crescent wrench or socket set, large screwdriver or bar (to lock pulley in place) and a rubber mallet( although you can use a regular hammer), a piece of 2x4 and some white lithium grease.

Just take your time and pause the videos as you work.

BTW have a few beer cold for when you finish, because you should reward yourself for a job well done.

review_text: Like most I was disappointed when the reusable pod didn't unlock the additional sizes.  But not to be deterred I took a hack used to fool the keurig into unlocking the additional sizes and applied it to this guy and voil√†! My 14 oz is back.  Basically just take a used or unwanted carafe pod, cut off the green dot, and tape it to the red dot on the pod. Not sure if a green sticker will work as well as I didn't have one, but based on the pictures, this for sure works and it brews 14 oz just fine.  Although the size will be available with this hack, the pod is not able to hold enough grounds to brew a carafe.  4 stars because yes it works like it's supposed to, but it's something that should have been included with the unit in the first place.

review_title: How to fix the smelly washing machine for good (replace hose and buy a Fan for the vent - permanent fix )
review_text: For the smelly washing machine:  The hose is great quality btw  - replace the hose first and then you will need to buy a 115 VAC 120mmX120MMX25MM fan (eg AC Infinity AXIAL 1225, Cooling Fan, Low Speed) and buy an 120mmX92mmX80MM fan mounting adapter kit.  (eg. Akust Aluminum 80mm & 92mm to 120mm Case Fan Adapter Blue). both are available on Amazon. to add the fan:  Remove the top washing machine  cover (3 bolts on back and slide it fwd and lift off). Mount the smaller 80mm side of the adapter around the vent on back so it enclosed it.  There will be a small gap on one side and you can add a piece of rubber 3/4" weather stripping ($4 dollars at lowes/Home D). After you add your weather stripping, line the holes up so you can catch metal on the washing machine.  pre drill the back of the washing machine (using slighter smaller holes thatn you mounting screws) by drilling through the 4 holes on the adapter.  Use some zinc hex screws and screw it in. Now mount the 120mm fan to the other end of the adapter.  It is a vent so you mount the motor so it exhausts and creates airflow out of the wash machine.  check arrow on fan for flow direction. (or plug it in before mounting to confirm flow direction).  Note - removal of the cover is so you can see where you are drilling so you do not drill into something you shouldn't.  This is the low speed fan that uses 8watts and they have a higher speed one with twice the CFM that use 18W and is an overkill in my opinion (too much energy usage).  Plug it into the wall and leave it on for years (do not unplug) you are leaving it on to dry out the passages to prevent mold from reoccurring. (so you want it to run 24/7).  The "Washer Fan" company has a patented magnet mount version that will be available in late 2016 for a $100 if you are not mechanically inclined and want to wait....  Additionally, some folks say washing with Borax with Tri Sodium Phosphate (TSP) in the HE front loaders will fix problem given the Phosphate's reaction properties with iron, sulfur,  etc

We'll try to get them at the local store and see if they're different (same brand, but different packaging).  Also - have you ever tried to mail a water-logged fridge filter back to Amazon? review_title: Worst Washing Machine  I've Ever Owned!
review_text: I own a Maytag Bravos but different model# (MVW600XW). This washing machine is horrible!  The water level is so low that it doesn't even begin to cover the clothes....even when the load only has a few pieces of clothing!  The lock is very annoying and doesn't allow you to rinse the detergent cup (which causes a big mess unless you take the cup to a sink and rinse it out) and trying to add a forgotten clothing item to the wash turns into a major, time consuming ordeal.  Since there is not an agitator clothes basically just sit in the machine,  barely moving, in a very small amount of water so the clothes are never truly clean.  The instructions reccomended that you wash your Maytag washing machine every month to prevent the machine from having an odor...odd, I never had to wash my traditional washing machine to prevent it from having a bad odor....perhaps this is due to the fact that my traditional washing machine actually added water to wash my clothes!  The cycles seem to run much longer than my former washing machine (traditional, not HE) and the clothes are still not clean.  My husband and I have both had enough of this machine and made the decision to just take a loss on the money we spent on this Maytag and buy another washer...Yesterday, I ordered a traditional washing machine -that actually uses enough water to cover the clothes and an agitator that will actually move the clothes around while they wash....what a novel idea!  I am VERY dissapointed with this Maytag washer and expected a much better product from a company that has been in business for so many years!

review_text:
I was initially drawn to this machine by it's looks, but bought it for ease of use. Samsung and LG consistently get high marks but in everyday use they drive me nuts. For those not familiar with the Asian design aesthetic, it basically goes like this: More buttons + more blinking lights + more beeping noises = more better. Well, in the words of Stan Marsh, "I thought this was America!" It is, Stan, and this one is actually made in America too.

The controls are simple, just go from left to right. Set auto or timed mode, modify the default settings if you want, throw in some bonuses (like delay time), and press play. I did not really need to read the instructions to figure it out, and the silly noises can be turned off. This is also the first dryer I have ever used with an automatic dry mode that actually works. Although the modes are a bit goofy, "more dry" equals dry, I'm not sure how you can be more dry than dry but whatever. "Normal dry" equals barely damp, perfect for ironing, and "damp" equals damp for hang drying. It is really nice that the steamer has an actual water line, not just a tray you fill with water like many others.

This is easily the best performing dryer I have ever used. The first time I turned it on it blew decades of old dryer lint out of my 30' long exhaust vent, and it blows out so much steam you could build a sauna around it. This thing dries quickly, usually in 40 mins. And evenly, even fitted sheets are no match. It is also very quiet. The only noise that can be heard is the burner lighting, and that is when standing right next to it.

One final note is a weird warning on page one of the installation manual: "Place dryer at least 18 inches above the floor for a garage installation. Failure to do so can result in death, explosion, or fire." Now we all know garage floors are no more explosive than regular floors and I am not going to build a stand for it that is 18 inches taller than my washer, but since this little gem is not mentioned in any of the sales info I thought I'd pass it along.

If you are buying this as a set like I did, the features of the washer and dryer to not really match up. The 6000 dryer DOES have a steam cycle and interior light, if you also want that on your washer you will need to step up to the 7000. Also, unlike the washer this dryer DOES NOT come with all of the required connectors. It only comes with the water line, you will need a gas line and exhaust vent. Please don't use a cheap-o flexible vent tube, they reduce efficiency and can create a fire hazard.

review_title: not a beginner project but not difficult
review_text: had all the parts to bring your drive mechanism back to new.  to do this you pretty much have to completely dismantle the dryer so you can pull the drum out.  I used a cart lift because  some if the work is at the bottom and it makes it easy to adjust the height ad I dismantled  and rebuilt the unit.  youtube video will help if you have never done this.  it's a rewarding project that's not too difficult but take a lot of time.  plan on 4 hours if you have never done it before.  take pictures as you disassemble it so you can remember everything you took apart.  I also bought new weather stripping and replaced all the workout seals while I worked on it.  I also spent a good deal of time just vacuuming the lent and fuzz in the machine.  I'll bet there are 50 screws you pull out to disassemble this.  in the end I figure I saved close to $300 doing it myself.

review_text:
This came from Costway in 3 days...box was in perfect shape....with writing on top starting if it needs to be returned you have to pay for it....hum...I had alot of other choices from Amazon....well let's hope it's ok....well I was orginally thinking to use this in the tub...but...there are open slots underneath....so I wasnt thrilled about the tub idea...so..it fits on my kitchen sink counter....the provided intake hose is a joke....so I am able to fill it using sink sprayer.... THE DRAIN HOSE....seriously I paid 72 bucks for this and get a 2ft drain hose ...come on... The hose barely reaches the sink to discharge.....and once this baby starts dropping water...lol dont plan on being able to lift it up in the again to stop it to drain a little bit at a time because once that flow of water starts....its not going to stop....here's some additional advice....the plastic cowling below the drain tube is very sharp....it could puncture the drain hose....run some duct tape or pad that area some how to keep the hose from running over the sharpness...easy fix...

Ok...enough about hoses...I PUT IN 3...4XL Mens T shirts....might have been able to do 4...and this was my trial load....the machine is smooth....very quite motor....wiggles some while just washing...but it has rubber feet...not going anywhere....the tub drains in les than a minute...whoosh... have not used the spinner...think it's pretty small...good for underwear and socks.....I HAVE A DRYING RACK and a shower bar that runs the full length of my bath tub in my 2nd bathroom for a drying area...

I consider this a good buy even though the manufacturer didnt give much thought to THE HOSES...

review_text:
Whirlpool bought Maytag. I think my particular model is as old as the hills... but the belt finally gave out.
This one slipped on with few problems. Pro tip: Hang the drum by the belt as they show in the YouTube videos, then put it into the machine. Drop the belt. OPEN THE ACCESS PANEL ON THE BACK! Take a pic of the video that clearly shows the way the belt feeds around the loop with your cell phone camera. Use the pic to make sure you thread it correctly. It takes about 30 seconds to install, pushing the tensioner pulley to the side and then slipping the belt over the idler. Also, be sure that it does -not- fall into the groove in the drum. There will be a worn area just outside that groove that indicates the correct belt position.

Now, if only the glides didn't use pop-rivets!

review_title: Drive block was machined slightly off-center- hopefully a rare issue
review_text: Had an unexpected surprise; the part was correct for my washer and installed OK, but I noticed that the spin basket seemed to wobble more than it had, causing an imbalance & minor cabinet shaking. I had an all-new drive system otherwise (center support, basket drive, clutch, etc). The machined hole in the cast drive block was basically about 30 thousands off-center, which caused the wobble. I could see this with the spin basket removed and just the drive block spinning by itself. I went to a local store and bought another block (grrr, 3x Amazon price) and it was fine. We micrometer'd both of them, with one mic jaw flat against the small conical taper at the bottom. The empty basket should have none to a bit of imbalance when spinning, but not as much as I saw. Both blocks were sealed in Whirlpool factory service parts (FSP) bags - I noted that the new one's bag said made in USA, which surprised both me and the counterman. I'd tossed the old bag. Each block had slightly different mold stampings so they were made at different locations. No blame on Amazon; the part was genuine and it was more than 30 days before I could get to it. So, if you've had a mystery imbalance since new or after a repair, check this part. A symptom is that the holes in the bottom of the spin basket won't be tracking in a neat circle but will sort of blur out as the wobble sets in.

review_title: Is there a button on side to release ice bucket?- RF30HBEDBSR/AA
review_text: fyi I have a SAMSUNG RF30HBEDBSR/AA and the replacement ice bucket part is DA97-14474C.  If your ice bucket has a button on the side to release it then you need the separate latch part that accommodates this ice bucket. This bucket does not have the button on the side. It releases by lifting it to unlatch it. The separate part replaces the existing latch part that screws into the underside of the top of the refrigerator. It is a simple replacement. However if this ice bucket has the "C" at the end of the model number and you are replacing a side button ice bucket (i.e. the model with an "A" at the end), then you need to replace the latch part as well.

review_title: TERRIBLE! DO NOT BUY IT EVER!!
review_text: After having an ancient Maytag work-horse finally die after more than 30 years of loyal trouble-free service, I assumed that a new eco-friendly Maytag would be fantastic.  How wrong I was! This is the worst washing machine I have ever experienced.  It is a piece of junk!  I can't imagine that Maytag is not ashamed to put its name on a machine that is so bad.  It is unbelievably noisy, downright scary, making very loud sawing, creaking, metallic grinding, clicking, alien noises when it is "sensing" and "locking the lid" and for every other cycle. Although the bin is very large, you can't put much laundry in it since it has to be evenly "placed" around the imaginary non-existent agitator in the center.  It supposedly is eco-friendly and does not need much water, but it sadly does not get the clothes clean. It tangles and can rip the clothes.  It does not spin at all if it has a normal size load as the clothes get wet and become too heavy for it to spin at all. Then you can try to use a special "drain and spin" cycle, but that also does not work and it still does not spin. If you put in anything like a quilt, dog beds, small cushion, etc. it does not spin at all or starts banging the tub inside against the sides of the washing machine making the loudest, scariest sounds you have ever heard. I am returning it immediately and now will never buy a Maytag again, since they obviously do not care what garbage they are making and selling. This is truly a sad story of a formerly quality brand name of appliances that is "Made in America", but is now just awful quality. Calling it a "WASHING MACHINE" is not accurate, since it does not wash or spin clothes. Is it really so hard to design a product that actually works?  PLEASE DO NOT BUY THIS TERRIBLE PRODUCT!  I was duped by the brand name.....don't make the same mistake.

review_text:
My refrigerator is not near a water line so making ice must be done with ice cube trays or an ice making machine. This ice machine reliably cranks out ice for home use. By no means is this made for commercial use but to fill several glasses of ice for a meal, with more left over, it's great. I have only used the small setting which seems to fit glasses well. Of course, you can always bag ice ahead of time and keep it in your freezer for occassions where you'll need a several bags. The chamber where the ice is kept is insulated but not refrigerated so the ice will eventually melt. However the water reservoir is below the vented ice basket so the water simply refreezes into more ice. It comes with a perfectly usable white plastic scoop but I bought a metal scoop because I liked the design.

Pros:
Preforms as advertised.
Quiet except for the occasional sound of ice dropping in the basket.

Cons:
This unit is fairly big and takes up a good bit of kitchen counter real-estate.
While fine for my use, and I would guess most households, it may not produce enough ice for some.
I wish the price were a little lower.

review_title: Don't walk. RUN away from this piece of GARBAGE
review_text: We had an agitator washer for a long time. The Dog Agits wore out and I replaced them so it worked ok. However my wife wanted a new one. We did some research and bought a WTW7300X about 2 1/2 years ago. BIG mistake. It's been SO frustrating that if there was such a thing as a time machine, we'd use it to go back in time and buy something else. Two weeks after we got it, the computer board failed. The first tech blamed it on the water feed hoses being clogged. He had NO clue what was wrong and left. Second tech replaced the computer board which solved the problem. We've had CONTINUAL "unbalanced load" issues so we can't run it at night because you never know if it's going to complete a cycle. I estimate 30% of the time we get a "UL" regardless of how it's loaded or what's in it. 30 days short of two years the tub bearing failed. Fortunately we'd bought it with a CC that extended the warranty for a year so the repair was ok'd by the warranty company. The repair tech said that bearing failure was a common problem but was supposed to have been fixed. Guess not. Shortly after that when we lifted the lid there was a loud "clunking" noise near the lid hinge. I determined that the lid spring assembly had come loose and had to retighten it on both sides. When I opened it up to fix the springs, the underside of the top was filled with rust. Water splashes up under the top and stays there, eventually rusting the top. Now clothes are coming out with dark stains on them. It looks like oil and I suspect that the bearing is failing again. And it's also torn some of our son's clothes. So PLEASE save yourselves a LOT of pain and frustration. Don't buy a Cabrio. April 10, 2014 Update. Last night there was rusty water on the floor under the washer. The problem I mentioned about water splashing up under the top at the bleach dispenser apparently happens continuously. There's another review here that addresses the same problem. You just don‚Äôt notice it until enough water runs down the inside of the washer over time and then overflows from the frame at the bottom. Now the top left side is rusted almost all the way from front to back. There should ba a gasket on the top of the tub funnel tp prevent this from happening. Now, the paint‚Äôs bubbling and all the hose clamps are rusty. So you have this to look forward to if you have one of these. Whoever designed it should be FIRED. What a piece of crap.
product_title: Whirlpool WTW8800YW Cabrio 4.6 Cu. Ft. White Top Load Washer - Energy Star

review_title: Good, but here's what you also need to buy.
review_text:
Works pretty well and is lightweight. Great for small spaces and single living. Do this in your bathtub!

You should buy:

1) A Rinsearoo (as stated by another user). This way you can use your shower head for water quickly and easily. Also great for pet bathing and quick rinse offs without getting your whole body wet. Lastly, I suggest rinsing items twice.

2) Three prong extension cord.

3) Waterproof tape. Use this to attach the longer hose to the short drain hose so that water is going more directly into the drain.

4) Liquid detergent, do not use pods!

5) Foldable drying rack for clothes or more hangers. Clothes come out lightly damp to almost dry.

Cat hair:
Does not get any off. I suggest buying a hair grabber in the wash cycle.

review_title: Get this tool and be proactive to clean your vent annually....don't wait for a huge build up!
review_text: Great product and a "must have" for homeowners who have a long vent that goes up to the roof. We bought a new dryer which has a flow sensor that said we had 80% blockage.  Our home is 15 years old and I bought this kit to see if any lint had built up over time.  I first when up from the bottom, going about 3 feet up then back down (to clear lint) then up to 6 feet and back down...then 9 feet, etc...up to the full 12 feet.  I then went on the roof and went down and then back up.  After that I used an electric blower from the bottom to blow out any remaining lint (onto the roof). Check out the pictures of what I pulled out!!  After the above procedure I did the flow sensor test again and it said 0% blockage.  I'm going to run this same test annually from now on.  This is a GREAT TOOL and it worked perfectly.

review_text:
Perfect, except listed measurements. It's actually

H x W x D

This is the only one we found that actually had an upper spray head for the top drawer that holds utensils and such.
We use it on average once sometimes twice a day. We must always use the standard cycle with a dry feature. The dishes always come out dry except for the food container lids which sometimes have a little water left inside but that is normal for any dryer. Once you get to know how to load it it takes a few days things come out clean almost every single time. We use Cascade complete plus oxy and slightly overfill the very small detergent container. We found them by slightly overfilling it so that the detergent kind of mounds up it always cleans the dishes perfectly. We tried using all the brand dish detergent and it did not do near as well. I found you can stack cooking utensils and things on top of certain items just make sure that there is some sort of flow from the lower spray head. One word of warning is to always watch when it first starts to make sure the upper and lower spray head are spinning and are not blocked from moving. We always fill the dishwasher from the top because the faucet hook up must stay connected through the entire 69 minute cycle because it refills multiple times for rinsing but you only have to fill it once if you use the included jug.
We have had the washer for 11 months now without issue or leakage.

I will try to remember to update this review when it stops working.

review_text:
I had ordered the official Samsung part over a month ago and Samsung didn't have it in stock and missed the estimated date 3 times. So I took a chance and ordered this part because it looked similar and came up with a search of my model number even though that model number is not listed in the product description. There's a bigger flange on this part but the part that makes contact fits in the opening. The original part was only held in with one screw so I just kinda wiggled it in and fastened the one screw, plugged the oven back in and it fired right up. Put the oven back together and have baked two batches of muffins and roasted a pan of veggies. Works great. Will never use the stupid self clean feature again. Also, Youtube is the only thing that made this repair possible. God bless those people that post their repairs.
UPDATE: Worked perfectly for a few months, but now it doesn't regulate the oven heat at all. Discovered when I tried to bake a cake at 350 and it jumped up to 500. Been using a digital thermometer to test and the oven is always at least 150 degrees over what it reads. Will have to replace it again, but I'll be ordering the part elsewhere.

review_title: STK Reusable K-Cups - Study In Progress
review_text:
As an engineer, I liked the overall design of the STK Reusable K-Cups based on what one could gather online. An o-ring on the lid prevents the grounds from escaping the cup while brewing. The lid takes some effort close but the cup is sturdy enough to withstand the force needed to close it. The cut-outs n the sidewalls certainly allow the brewed coffee to escape the cup more freely than the single hole a standard K-Cup provides. In theory I agree with the mfg. that this could provide a more robust cup of coffee.

My wife and I's experience is limited to about 3 weeks of occasional use at this point. The brewed coffee turns out well. Clean up is minimal after dumping out the wet grounds and allowing the remainder in the cup dry before trying to remove them.

We purchased our first Keurig coffee maker (model 145) 3 weeks ago so we are relative neophytes to the Keurig world. Our first machine died after 12 days - will write more about this experience in a review of that machine - it could no longer force water through even a standard K-Cup to brew coffee. However, without a cup the water flowed through the machine. I am not yet familiar with the mechanism(s) and process the Keurig machine uses to regulate the force of the hot water through the K-Cup while brewing. Until I am I have reservations about what caused our first machine to fail. I have not ruled out the use of the STK K-Cup for causing the failure. Until I can be sure that the plastic strainer in the lid of the STK does not restrict the water flow during brewing, thus possibly requiring more water force than the Keurig was designed to handle my rating will remain at 3 stars.

My background as an electrical engineer means that I need to perform additional research on the mechanical design and properties involved before I will be able to deliver an accurate verdict on this product and the Keurig machine design. I will update this review after I am satisfied with my research and conclusions... I welcome inputs from those who have had similar or dissimilar experiences with their Keurig and the STK K-Cups, please include data that includes: Model Keurig used, average use and age of the machine; how frequently you use the STK cups and how many weeks/months/years you have done so; any other observations you may think are relevant.
product_title: STK Keurig Reusable K Cups- 3Pack for Classic and 2.0 Brewers Universal Fit for K55, K575, K15, K250, K-Elite, K155, K-Select, K475

review_title: A little more detail is needed here
review_text:
Pros:
The repair went well enough to get my agitator agitating again. The old agits (probably original) had disintegrated into bits.

Neutral:
- Getting the agits in upside down in my fitment (a Kenmore 110.92283100 washer) was agitating, but that's not Blue Stars fault.

Cons:
- One of the items wasn't of the proper dimension, so I wound up using the old one.
- In addition to the agits, I did use the supplied agitator because mine looked was developing small cracks.
- I question the durability of these parts because materials are not of comparable quality to my 30 year old parts.
- I was frustrated to discover that the necessary agitator grease (which is mentioned as necessary in the instructions) is omitted. That grease alone is a $28 FSP part (350849).. I've read where waterproof grease can be used (e.g., marine grease), so that's what I got instead.

Final word:
- I should have just bought the agits and saved myself a couple bucks. The old cam would have lived on, I suppose.
- For what should be a 15-30 minute repair job, when not all the needed parts are correct or supplied it takes much longer. It's also a hassle stopping in the middle of a repair to run to the local hardware store if you don't own a boat and have marine grease on hand.

I have an ~10 year old LG Direct Drive washer which has had the ‚Äòall plastic rotor hub‚Äô (4413ER) replaced many times. I assume that‚Äôs due to an engineering mishap on LG‚Äôs behalf since they upgraded the dampening ‚Äòall plastic hub‚Äô with a metal insert one that hasn‚Äôt failed yet. Only problem with that is it puts pulsation from the Direct Drive VFD‚Äôs magnetic forces directly on the bearings. I think this causes seal fatigue and the bearings to fail prematurely. I have to give TOMOON / wsh supplier credit as they did stand behind their "5 YEARS WARRANTY". They shipped a whole rebuild kit under warranty very quickly. review_text:
Well designed capsule and it does make a great espresso. Those who say that it won‚Äôt make espresso do not put the right amount in it. I used the small scoop this came with. One capsule takes two slightly mounded of this small scoop size. You need to tap it down (no need to press it hard) and the top will fit on tight but just right. Great design, high quality, double walled and seals well. My machine makes the same high pressure sound when I put this amount of coffee in it as if I used the illy iperpresso capsule. I do get a good creama. Makes a great espresso.
Two more tips: if the water rushes through too easily without the high bar pressure sound that means either your coffee is ground too large or you need a little more coffee in the capsule to fill air gaps.
I highly recommend this capsule. You are free to use your own coffee this way, decaff or half caf, cost less than iperpresso, and no more trashing empty capsules if you are environment conscious like I am.

review_text:
I bought the eco-egg mini washing machine about two weeks ago and have it used 3 times. It clean as expected but there a few things that could be better, so I gave it 3 stars and I will explain why.

I took 1 start from it due to the following: After washing the clothes, the machine throw the water out, but after removing the clothes from inside of it, I always have some residual water inside. Since it does not have a button that I can press to activate its mechanism to throw that residual water away, I need to remove the water by hand (If you close you eco-egg with water inside, the next time you open it it will be with a bad smell inside). I cannot assure that the residual water inside the machine is due to not effective draining system or due to the water that came out the clothes when I remove them from inside. Yes, when the machine finishes the cleaning cycle, your clothes you will be full of water since the machine does not have a spin dryer mechanism (as a normal washing machine). That spin dryer function is something that I really miss.

The other star that I took is to its installation mechanism. When I bought it, I though that I would simply plug the water in hose in my water tap, but you actually have to remove a piece that is inside the water tap (at least, the majority of water tap has that piece installed). So, every time that I would use, I need to remove that piece from my water tap and insert a specific piece (that comes with the machine) in the tap.

In sum, if you are looking for a mini washing machine to clean your clothes and you mainly don't mind having to squeeze your clothes after the cleaning, this machine will work for you.

review_text: I have ordered these "Anpro 24K Gold K Cup Reusable Coffee Filter for use on all Keurig 2.0 Brewer Models, use on K200, K300, K400 and, K500 Series brewers(Black, 3)" twice from seller 'Anpro US' for two different prices in the range of $5 to $7. They were "Sold by Anpro US and Fulfilled by Amazon" and arrived with the rest of the things I had ordered both times, as one would expect from something that is "Fulfilled by Amazon". I have been happy with them so far, enough that I ordered that second box of them. They seem to work as well as the other refillable k-cups that I have used and these have the advantage of being larger and thus holding more coffee grounds so that I can brew a 16oz travel mug of coffee. The construction is very similar to the 'cheap' generic re-usable k-cups, but they look and feel like the materials are better -- the black plastic seems a bit more rigid and the gold filter material is less flexible and slightly more restrictive than the gray screens on the others reusable k-cups I have but so far this has only been noticable when washing them out. I haven't used them enough yet to comment on their durability. The box came with a tiny scoop which might be useful for measuring grounds for a consistent brew (since there are 3 different sized cups), a tiny brush I haven't needed, and there was a nicely printed product information card and a customer service card with the company's email address. The product looks good and professional, not like cheap junk; I'd feel comfortable giving a box of these as a gift. For the price I paid ($5-7 for a box of 3 cups) these seem to be a good bargain when compared to the pricey official Keurig version and even when compared to the 'cheap' generic re-usable k-cups which seem to cost about $1-1.50 each when bought in quantity.

review_text:
UPDATE: 1/3/2017 -

The lint filter in my dryer started falling off while the dryer was running. I called the number in the product book and was asked to give my email. They did contact me via my email address and ended up sending me a replacement filter. The new one still fell off. I contacted them again via email reply to the original email conversation and they sent me the plastic part that the filter goes on; still didn't work. In the meantime while waiting for the part, the dryer started making a crunching noise behind the filter. Each time I used the dryer it got louder. I contacted the company via email with a video of the dryer running so they could hear the noise.

They sent me an email that I would receive a new dryer, I just needed to cut the power cord on the original dryer and send a picture, which I did. I investigated the noise in the broken dryer before sending it to recycling and the metal on the inside of the dryer, right behind the plastic part that holds the lint filter, is completely shredded.

I was happy to receive the email that I would be receiving a new dryer, unfortunately, the replacement dryer doesn't work. It runs but the drum does not turn. There were two dents in the new dryer as well. I assume this was damaged due to shipping.

I am now awaiting a response from emails that I have sent regarding getting a replacement for the replacement.

I received the dryer on Saturday (1/30/2016) and I really like it. I tried to register the product, as stated on the ownership registration but the link provided does not work. I called the company and was told that it is not necessary to register the product but to keep the information if I need to use the warranty. The customer service rep that I just spoke to barely spoke English and literally told me there is no need to register this product? Why would they put a registration card in if you don't register it? How will I know if there is a recall or other safety concerns?

I am 50/50 happy on this. The dryer is very cute and works great so far! I am worried that if this breaks, I am out the money I paid for it.

review_title: Made washer spin cycle significantly worse
review_text:
These are high-quality pads, so I don't regret getting them. Previously, my washer and dryer were on an old linoleum floor over concrete. I didn't have walking problems unless my top-loading washer became seriously imbalanced while washing a comforter or load of towels.

I installed a new vinyl floor and purchased these pads mostly to protect the new floor and raise the machines a bit. They work great with my dryer but have made the washer almost unusable because even slight imbalances become greatly amplified during the spin cycle.

Previously, I think the washer would slide a bit across the linoleum to help compensate for imbalances while spinning. These rubber pads do not allow any compensatory sliding, so even small imbalances grow out of control.

I may need to find another use for them.

review_text:
I replaced my cogs, motor coupling, and clutch assembly. Below is my review for that, just in case it's helpful. If you're lucky enough to be doing the cogs only, it's really easy to do. Go watch a video or two on YouTube and you'll be all set. I noticed a substantial improvement in the agitator when I replaced my cogs, even though they weren't broken or completely worn out yet. It's a cheap and really easy way to get better performance from your washer.

There are great YouTube videos online showing you how to do this and you absolutely must watch a few of them before you try this. My washer made a grinding noise and didn't spin the drum or agitate. I've had this washer for about 13 years and this is the first repair I've had to make, other than the time a sock somehow got into the pump. It has had very heavy use for all of its life so I'm not surprised it broke. I believe the root cause of my failure was the direct drive motor coupling but I'm not sure because it may also have been something in the clutch assembly because I did see some significant wear. Also, my agitator cogs were quite worn and I noticed a substantial improvement in the vigor of the agitator after I swapped them out.

I decided to replace the clutch assembly, direct drive motor shaft coupling, and the agitator dogs/cogs. I bought all the items on Amazon and once I had them together, I began my adventure. I didn't remove the metal shell around the washer tub like I see in the videos, I just tipped it back, drained the water out, and did all the work from the bottom and inside the drum.

Again, watch videos on YouTube. I pity the fool who tries this without looking at videos and hopefully you're more adept with appliances than I am. Aside from my pictures, these are my tips to others:

Picture 1-3) The motor couplings I purchased were very tight fitting. I think they were likely machined to the same size and they don't, in any way, just slip on. I used a short spark plug socket end from my toolset and a hammer to get both motor couple ends on and it was vigorous hammering. The old one popped off fairly easily from the motor end, which I could see where the metal ring inside the coupling splintered or did something bad. Aligning the two couplings with the black rubber intermediary worked better for me when I put it on the motor end and then slid it onto the transmission. Also, older models may not have a metal reinforced piece inside the white nylon portion but mine did so be aware it might look different than the picture.

Picture 4-5) Replacing the clutch assembly requires dropping the transmission and the drive shaft out the bottom of the washer and you have to remove some pieces inside the drum. Keep track of what piece goes where because I managed to get my pieces out of order, only to realize the locking ring I thought went in the drum was actually in the clutch assembly. I got to redo the entire replacement process and I wasn't happy about it. I was a lot faster the second time though.

Final thoughts - be prepared to get dirty. Lots of grease, pet hair, and nastiness accumulates. This translated to me not being able to watch the YouTube videos as I went along. I wore gloves for some of it because of the sharp edges of the sheet metal but needed more dexterity so took them off and got nasty. Slot about an hour or two for this work max.

review_title: it works, for a while, then same problem
review_text:
This is the classic issue with these control boards. You'll probably see it scattered around if you search. When you press start it does a double beep 3 times in a row and flashes the front light orange and fails to start. It will do this incessantly until you press and hold the start button to cancel. Sometimes when the dishwasher enters this state you can turn it off at the breaker for a few hours and then turn it on and it will work again, but eventually it stops working completely.

I got this one as a replacement and it worked flawlessly for a few months, and then the problem started showing up again. No click on start, beep beep beep. Now it's failed within the 1 year limited warranty and I need to get a new board. Luckily, they aren't that expensive and it takes an hour or two to replace with basic tools. It's cheaper than getting a whole new dishwasher.

About the 1 year limited warranty. Don't even bother trying. You'll just go in circles. You can't return it through GE (even though the link says that's how you're supposed to) because you didn't buy it through GE parts center or their 1 authorized parts seller. You can't return it through Amazon, because it directs you back to GE, so you end up going in circles. The 1 year limited warranty is a bit of a scam and has no affect. You *might* be able to force credit return through your credit card, and that's the approach I'm going to try, even though there's nowhere conceivable that I can mail the board and it'll probably cost me $15 in shipping. Is it worth the hassle for $100? *shrug*

Anyway, part works, but it'll likely fail again in a year or less and you'll have to do it again. If you are not the handy type, you might pay extra to get it through an authorized repair center with a warranty.

review_text: I LOVE this refrigerator.  The space is great and for an organizational girl like myself - it has lots of areas to compartmentalize things and easy access to drawers.  HOWEVER . . . I HATE that I've only had it 2 years and it's now the 2nd time my compressor has gone out on it . . . in the last 8 months.  If you look for reviews online - you will see that this is a VERY COMMON issue with LG refrigerators.  Our repair technician said they receive calls all the time for this problem.  The compressors regularly go out due to the poor way they are made to work.  If you purchase an LG refrigerator - BE SURE to buy the longest warranty you can get - and plan on the frustration of losing food and living out of a mini fridge or coolers for at least 2 weeks (speaking from our 2x's of experience now.)  It's a big bummer - cause I LOVE this style of fridge.

review_title: Or better yet, make a cooktop that doesn't turn off ...
review_text:
Don't...
buy a Bosch induction cooktop until Bosch explains the conditions that cause the cooktop to automatically shut off at some arbitrary time during use. This applies to the 500-series, 800-series and Flexinduction models. I discovered this can happen while reading manuals during my web research on induction cooktops.

Here are the respective web pages and page numbers advising of this stipulation in each model's "Use and Care" manual:

500-series:
http://i.sears.com/s/d/pdf/mp-tc/spinpdf/spin_prod_975580612
(page 14)

800-series:
http://i.sears.com/s/d/pdf/mp-tc/spinpdf/spin_prod_975587312
(page 16)

Flexinduction:
http://www.goedekers.com/assets/PDF/Bosch/bosch-nitp666suc-use-and-care-manual.pdf
(page 15)

I called Bosch Customer Support 5 times over a two-week period and each time talked to a different rep including a Support Supervisor on my last call. I asked for an explanation about the specific circumstances under which the cooktop would shut off. I cited several examples of cooking situations where one would not want the cooktop to "just turn off" on its own. On my last 4 conversations with Bosch support reps, I was told they would research the issue and "get back to me with an answer".

Well, they didn't get back to me, and I still don't have an answer. The support people don't know and further, they told me they don't communicate with Bosch engineering (who certainly would know the answer). How strange is that? But I was copied on an email from a Bosch Senior Support Representative to "an unknown at Bosch". The email contained the following exact wording from one of the manuals:
"Automatic time limitation
If the element is used for prolonged periods of time without changes in the settings being made, the automatic time limitation function is triggered. The element stops heating. "F8" and the residual heat indicator "H/h" flash alternately in the display. The indicator goes out when any symbol is pressed. The element can now be reset. When the automatic time limitation is activated depends on the selected heat level (from 1 to 10 hours)."

The email also briefly revealed that "a customer" (me) wanted to know the conditions that can cause the cooktop to shut off, but didn't offer any relevant explanations. Whatsoever! I was told by a couple of support reps that the cooktop turns off for "safety reasons" but no other details were offered. Safety reasons? Really? Does that mean the cooktops are nearing a dangerous state? Are these Bosch cooktops the only cooktops ever made that turn off "for safety reasons" Maybe, but if so, I'm not aware of any others.

I hope I am not alone in thinking Bosch needs to inform prospective customers exactly what conditions can trigger these (expensive) cooktops to shut off? Or better yet, just make a cooktop that doesn't arbitrarily turn off.

Bottom line is, buy one of these Bosch cooktops only if you are willing to risk it automatically turning off sometime between "1 and 10 hours". Or, if you'd be content to just stand watch over it to be sure it stays on while you're cooking a corned-beef for 4-5 hours.

Bosch engineers take notice!

review_title: Product may be good but I'll never know because Price Pros stuck me with a broken item
review_text: I purchased this vent hood due to the good price and apparent good feedback.  We are renovating our kitchen and received the vent hood 32 days ago.  To keep it safe we left it in the box until we were ready to install it.  When we opened the box the glass was completely shattered.  After contacting the company the only response they gave was this... "Thank you for contacting The Price Pros.  We received your request for return, however we are unable to process your request at this time.  Per our return policy, we will accept a return of a defective or non-defective item, for credit or replacement, if notified within 30 days from receiving the item. Since it is past our 30 days return policy time frame, you may contact the manufacture of the item for further assistance.  Please do not hesitate to contact us with any concerns or questions you may have."  Trying to call them I sat on hold for 30 minutes before giving up and subsequent e-mails received the exact same canned message.  Granted I was 2 days past the warranty period but this unit was delivered damaged.  A call to the manufacturer Broan-Nutone got the response "We never heard of  Price Pros ... it could have been bought and transferred many times before being sent to you".  A call to American Express got the response "since it was delivered to you already damaged we don't cover it under the buyer protection coverage".  So at this point my only recourse is with the shipper and if they say I broke it somehow then back to American Express.  All in all I wanted to share this experience - an expensive $900 lesson not to purchase from Price Pros and to reconsider buying expensive items from Amazon.  Amazon.com was no help at all.  Boo Hoo on Price Pros - it is apparent they are one of those companies that I try to avoid with my due diligence of checking feedback etc but in the end somehow got sucked in by the price.  The true strength and reliability of a company is to come through when things go wrong not when they go right.  An expensive lesson - please do yourself a favor and buy elsewhere and not from Price Pros.  I saved $50 and lost $900 going with them.

review_text: In this picture, it's very easy to see the brand name on the bottom had alot more carbon in it. Now These filters will work, they just won't last half as long.  The brand name came with these stickers that turned red when it was time to replace. These filters don't have that, just replace regularly. Given this is so much cheaper than brand name, only 6 months or more could I say if replacing them twice as often is cheaper or not. For those of you who don't know what this thing does, you know how your fruits and vegetables are going bad quicker? That's probably not lower quality produce, it's most likely the carbon filter needs to be replaced. I've noticed good carbon, blueberries and strawberries will last 2-3 weeks. review_title: the price is great, it looks expensive but it is not
review_text:
First, I will tell you the Pros:. This is an outstanding hood, the price is great, it looks expensive but it is not, the stainless is magnetic, It has three fan speeds with an 8 inch exhaust discharge, It replaced a microwave that did a poor job of exhausting fumes and smoke from the range, The hood arrived promptly in perfect condition. It has grates that can be washed in the dish washer and also has a grease drip bar in the back. Operation of the light and three different fan speed are fairly simple. The fan is programmed whereby you can turn it off immediately or let it continue for one minute and then turn off.

Cons: I would have given this hood a five star rating except for the operation of the clock! Setting the normal clock time is complicated and I had to call the business that sold the hood for instructions and they even had a little difficulty explaining things. The clock reads all time in 24 hour stages which I call Military time, for example 11 PM is 2300 hours. There is no way the set the mode of the clock to 12 am and 12 pm.
I don't use the clock anyway because I have a clock on the coffee maker, a clock on the microwave, a clock on the range, and a clock on the wall of the kitche. I don't have one on the fridge, but when I replace that, I probably will have one alreadyh installed.

review_title: Sludgy Coffee, Low filter area, lots of plastic, but Beautiful Dolphins to look at.
review_text: I ordered these because they fit into my MR Coffee Keurig maker. For my main Keurig maker, I use another product with a gold filter, so I had something to compare to. The coffee made with this filter came out sludgy with poor taste. Also, in order to fit the maker, the bottom portion is indented, and it makes it very hard to clean the coffee out. You have to used your finger or the edge of a spoon to stir up the coffee. My other filter just washes right out with the faucet. My biggest concern is this design. Instead of the filters being full filter around the sides of the cup, there is intervening plastic. I do not understand this design, and when looking for a replacement I noted many other ones for sale also have this design. With this design boiling hot coffee filters and then runs over plastic before exiting the unit. After a little while, I noticed that the plastic is placed in such a way to create a design out of the filter -  2 dolphins swimming!!!  Do we really need a dolphin design to make a cup of coffee, how about maximizing the filtering area to produce a better cup of coffee. I have had to return and will try another design with a full filter. I do not recommend this product.

review_title: Perfect solution for my baby clothes washing needs
review_text:
As a new mom the thought of washing babies little clothes in the gross old apartment washing machine in my building horrified me. I didn't know if this washer would work out but I was willing to take the risk. Turns out it is perfect. It works well for my needs... Baby clothes need to be washed often so I throw in a load usually every other day and the size capacity of this washer accommodates that perfectly. It's super easy to use and unlike portable washers my friends have bad in the past, it doesn't short circuit my apartment. Some things to keep in mind: this thing sucks at collecting lint; I am currently in search for solutions to this and I am confident I will find something. Also, the washer isn't super loud but it isn't quiet and it takes about 45 mins per load including the spin cycle (taking into account how long it takes water to fill up and drain and the cycles).
I would def recommend this machine for anyone with a baby or small kids; perfect for their laundry.

review_title: Not a 38/400 thread pattern like real growlers!
review_text:
Update: The seller contacted my and went above and beyond to correct the error, changing the listing and shipping me a replacement product for free. If you are okay with the thread pattern this growler will work well for you. Hopefully someone will build a carbonating cap for it in the near future. If they do I'll buy this again because honestly the thread pattern would be better for carbonating than the standard 38/400.

Here is my previous review: It is a single walled stainless bottle, so no insulation to keep the contents cold. While it does look small it holds 64 oz, but with no head space. It has one critical flaw for people interested in using it as a growler though: the thread size of the cap is non-standard! The standard growler thread pattern is 38/400 while this one has some metric thread I've never come across. The lid diameter is indeed 38 mm but a standard growler cap won't fit as the thread pattern is much too fine. I had planned to carbonate in this growler using a 38/400 carbonation cap and Das Beer clearly answers a customer question posted above about the cap size saying it is 38 mm. Either they are deliberately trying to mislead customers (unlikely) or they just don't know much about home brewing beer in America. The manufacturer is likely a Chinese company that just received an order for bottles with a 38 mm cap and they just used their normal metric thread pitch rather than considering the end user. The growler seems to be constructed well and if you are just going to use it as a water bottle you should be fine, just don't lose the cap!

review_title: Adequate but More Thought and Better Customer Service would Help
review_text:
Ovens are supposed to heat‚Ä¶pretty prosaic. But there are high-end ovens that throw in bells and whistles and you pay a premium for them. So, how‚Äôs a consumer to know if an oven is worth its premium price? Hopefully a review like this helps.

Some of this may seem like nit-picking, but if you are paying for an oven to do more than just be hot, it could be helpful for you to know the goods and the not-so-goods.

This is about the Miele H4890. Yes, it does heat. But what else would you want from a high-end oven? Reliability? Good customer service? A rotisserie? Easy to clean?

First, customer service: Customer service eventually answers you, but it‚Äôs difficult and frustrating. I waited more than a month to write this review because I wanted to make sure I was not writing only out of annoyance. My attempts to reach customer service were answered by giving me an email address that bounces emails and a customer service group that told me on more than one occasion they did not get my request. The Miele website for this oven offers no information (it results in a blank page). Just for the heck of it, I checked again and it is still that way‚Ä¶more than a month after I told Miele that it appears that something wasn't working.

The rotisserie is unusual in this oven. There are two within the oven cavity and they are both mounted so that you place the spit in the same direction as the depth of the oven instead of from side-to-side, along its width. This may be a good idea but because there are two of them and because the depth of the oven is less than its width, you are limited to what you can put on the rotisserie. The spits are so close to the sides that anything larger than a very large chicken might not fit.

The way the spits are inserted into the interior motor creates a minor inconvenience. The spits mount so that drippings go into the drip pan (good) but the grill racks are needed to mount the spits properly. This means that drippings from the roast not only go into the drip pan but they also go onto the grill racks creating just one more thing to clean. More about that later.

Also, you cannot use the rotisserie at less than 400ÔÇ∞ F. Why? I don‚Äôt know.

The drip pans and the grill racks use what Miele calls a proprietary ‚ÄúPerfect Clean‚Äù technology. It‚Äôs supposed to be easy to clean. I haven‚Äôt found this to be the case. After using the rotisserie and the broiler, the edges of the drip pan became encrusted with hard-to-clean material. I didn't see any advantage to what Miele is offering here. As with other ovens, you cannot leave the grill racks, nor the drip pan, in the oven when using self-cleaning. Now, that's a feature I would pay for!

The heating elements are very close to the front of the oven. This may help create even heating but I found it a little dangerous‚Ä¶particularly on the lower over. If you reach your hand in you may touch the heating element: I did‚Ä¶be careful!

The ovens have a ‚Äúdehydrating‚Äù feature. It‚Äôs hard to know what that is because it‚Äôs not described well in the manual. Does dehydrating automatically turn off when the item is desiccated? Is there a recommended time that should be set? I do know that it does not turn off automatically.

The ovens have a surround heating feature. This is supposed to provide even more uniform cooking than convection cooking. I found the surround feature to work well.

In short, these are adequate high-end ovens that could have used a little more thought and better customer service. I'm pretty sure they're not worth the premium price but I have not compared them with other high-end expensive ovens.

review_title: When I opened the brown envelope package I was disappointed at first glance focusing my attention to the hose ...
review_text: Okay I just received this two pack of stainless steel washing machine filler hoses in the extremely fast Amazon delivery fashion . I did not have time to read all the customer reviews but I did base my purchase on the high star rating as I did not want to spend hours or days researching and reading products reviews. When I opened the brown envelope package I was disappointed at first glance focusing my attention to the hose ends. Me, not being a physics major, I do understand the principles of water flow, albeit, gravity, pressurized, pumped or sucked mechanically, hydro or electric. Having said that let me point out that on standard rubber washing machine filler hoses the hose opening is anywhere from 3/8" to half inch generally which allows a speedy fill of the washer tub for washing and rinse cycles. This hose opening is 3/16" which is pretty small to say the least. So people on a municipality water system which pumps water to your house the water delivery pressure is somewhere in the area of 35 to 8o psi max or if pressure is higher than 80 PSI a regulator has to be installed to reduce it under 8o. These hoses most probably work and are okay for the new styles of washing machines that use way less water than the old style machines, using almost quarts of water compared to several gallons of water for the older machines. This small hose opening  under pressure will deliver water similar to when your garden hose nozzle is set to the jet setting, a small fast stream of water under volume and pressure. If any of you have ever witnessed a small pin hole in a copper water  pipe or PEX tubing it spits out a lot of water in a narrow stream. The bottom line is this. These hose will work, but it will just take longer to fill the washer tub. I suspect if I searched longer I would find hoses that are identical to these, being PVC wrapped in stainless steel that have larger openings in the ends. If you are looking to buy new hoses and have the older style and models of washers that use several gallons of water for wash and rinse cycles these are probably not for you, unless you have a lot of idol time or patience. But if you have the newest  models such as the front load or agitator-less styles this hose will work. Good Luck

review_title: Good for emergency repairs, but don't expect long term operation
review_text:
After 12 years of being a happy GE fridge owner, the original defrost heater module broke.
So I bought the Antoble defrost heater regardless of the negative comments about the smell. It turned out that the initial smell was negligible and after the replacement, the fridge worked great for months. Then today, I noticed the temperature in the fridge was creeping up again. So I removed the cover from the evap coils only to find that the coils were covered in thick ice again (this is an obvious sign of a failure of the defrost heater, thermistor or defrost control board). Since the diagnostic checks confirmed correct thermistor and control board operation, I ended up manually defrosting the coils then testing the heater element. As suspected, the Antoble heater was broke. What I didn't expect is the extreme damage of the gasket between the glass tube and the receptacle. On the GE defrost heater, the gasket was in great shape even after 12 years, on the Antoble, it melted away in 2 months. I give it 2 stars because the heater wire held up for 2 months, but I won't buy from this vendor until they fix the design flaws (gasket and heater wire issues).
product_title: Antoble Refrigerator Defrost Heater for Hotpoint, Kenmore, WR51X10055 GE General Electric RCA Freezer Refrigerators
