review_title: The jury is still out, but... UPDATE: the jury is out! Pass.
review_text:
UPDATE
I've used this cap twice a day, every day, since I got it. This cap makes one (and only one) improvement over the standard cap--it eliminates leakage while steeping.

Here's the kicker...if you are using your Aeropress correctly, leakage is not an issue. Just slightly insert the plunger after adding water, and the naturally-formed vacuum will stop any errant drips. Or, use the inverted method for no drips at all.

Mesh filter? Been there, done that. Yes, I prefer paper, but I have a mesh filter, and it works just fine with the standard cap.

Oh, and don't even think about using only a paper filter with this cap (that is, without the mesh filter also in place). It will be impossible to press. It's hard enough to press normally!!!

Also, the cap is so large, you absolutely cannot use the Aeropress funnel to dispense coffee into a smaller/narrower cup, so forget that.

I don't know what real problem this cap solves, and I do not see where it offers any improvement. I've given up using it. I can honestly say I do not like using it and absolutely cannot recommend it.

ORIGINAL REVIEW
I'm not seeing how this is an improvement over the original cap.

Here's the thing...the Aeropress was designed to work as constructed. Every time you try to "improve" on the design with some gadget, you are likely to be disappointed. Do I follow my own advice? Of course not! That's just the rogue in me, I suppose.

Anyway...

It seems like this device is solving a problem that doesn't really exist. If you use your Aeropress properly, leakage is minimal. If you use your Aeropress in the inverted fashion, leakage is non existent. Go watch YouTube videos if you're having issues. I guarantee you, someone out there solved the problem and made a video of it.

The claim "...this creates more pressure in order to brew coffee closer to espresso" is patently false. Is the plunger a lot harder to press? Yes. Does that create the 12-15 bar of pressure necessary to an espresso (or even close)? Not at all. 15 bar is pretty close to 15 ATM (atmospheres) or 220 psi. That's 15 times the pressure of air at sea level, nearly 7 times the pressure in your car tires. You could not possible generate that kind of pressure manually, and certainly not in an Aeropress.

Side note: with all of the extra pressing you have to do to get your coffee out, it is ridiculously easy for your cup and the Aeropress to get away from you, making a huge mess, and likely breaking your cup. Be very, very careful to keep everything lined up and apply pressure straight down. If you get off kilter, you will have a disaster.

Some people claim this device creates crema. Also untrue. Crema is the off-gassing of carbon dioxide trapped in the beans during roasting. High temperature water (boiling) will cause some off-gassing. The release of high pressure in an espresso machine will create copious quantities of crema. What this device does is mix air in with the coffee, giving you a foam of large air bubbles instead of small carbon dioxide bubbles. Put your coffee in a blender and you get the same effect. Sorry kids, no crema.

The stainless steel filter does allow oils to get through, which is good if you like that. It also allows fine particulate matter to get through as well--something a paper filter does not allow. Other steel filters work just as well. In fact, I have a stainless steel filter disc, and the performance is exactly the same. You can use a paper filter instead of the mesh, but I don't think it works as well as using a paper filter with the stock cap.

The device is very hard to install, especially on an older Aeropress. I bought mine in 2012--it's still ticking! Getting this thing installed required a lot of effort, though that seemed to improve slightly the more I used it. It will be interesting to note whether the gasket gets deformed.

The device does take up more space in your cup, so be prepared to use a larger cup. Or, use the funnel that comes with the Aeropress. Did you ever wonder why the funnel has a hexagonal shape? It's that way for a reason. Fit your Aeropress into the funnel and see for yourself.

Clean up is no different than using the stock cap with a stainless steel mesh filter. Just remember to remove the mesh filter before ejecting the puck. (No need to worry about that with paper filters.)

SUMMARY

Let me start with this...you will never, ever pull an espresso shot (or anything remotely close to it) from an Aeropress. It is simply physically impossible to do so. Anything that claims otherwise is completely untrue.

This is probably not better than the stock cap. You can use a mesh filter with a stock cap and get the same results. The "added pressure" is nonsense. The "crema" is nonsense. For the price you pay, you get a mesh filter (which is around ten bucks anyway) and you get to push a lot harder to get your coffee out. Beyond that, it's a wash.

I'm going to keep using it for a while to see if my opinion changes. It cost ten bucks, so it's not like I'm breaking the bank here. If ten bucks is a stretch for you (as it is for a lot of people in these times), save yourself the money and the headache of returning it. Stick with the stock cap and paper filters.

review_title: Frigidaire LEQ1442ES1?  Youtube videos are NOT ENOUGH!
review_text:
For the money, I rate this product 5 stars as of the first day... this might change if the blue (plastic??) part does not last as long as the original nylon part. The spindle itself is better than the ones you see on YouTube, because the hub is prethreaded, and the kit DOES include the ball bearing, grease, screws and instructions for "standard" machines. However, if you own one of the newer model Frigidaire dryers, you need more info than the vids offer. It's not that simple!

There is one video on YouTube that does show disassembly for THIS 1442ES dryer properly. If you've seen it already, you might not need to read all of the stuff below, but the videos always make things seem simple and they edit out their mistakes. I am just trying to point out that there are dozens of YouTube videos, but they are not for this unit, even though the parts are the same... so watch this one before you begin so you have a good overview at least: [on YouTube, SEARCH "Frigidaire Dryer Diagnostic - Making a Vibrating Sound When Running"] (This repairman does not really fix anything at all, but at least you get to see the job of removing the panels and the drum).

I would also like to say that if your bearing is shot, more than likely the front drum glides and felt are about to need replacing as well, so you might consider purchasing them at the same time and doing the whole job at once.

1. Open the top panel (NOT as shown on YouTube with a putty knife... you will damage the control panel and possibly ruin it). Instead, just remove the two screws at the top rear of the machine and slide the top BACKWARD and off. [Shown nicely in the above video]
2. The bottom panel under the door is removed next so that the upper part can be removed without damage to the blower's foam gasket. It's held by two screws at the very bottom, and you'll need to tilt the machine back a little to get under there. Next just pop the panel downward and the pegs pull out from the center panel. [Shown nicely in the above video]
3. Now, looking down onto the machine, at the front edge you will see two to four screws that hold the front panel in place. Mine had only two and the other two holes were not threaded, so the factory skipped them. You will have the extra chrome screws after installation (new ones furnished) so save those for this purpose. I noticed in the video, there are NO screws in the top... decide for yourself if you want them there.
4. From the top, look down the sides about 8 inches and you will see another screw on each side just above the alignment pegs. Remove those. [Shown nicely in the above video]
5. At the bottom front of the center panel there should be two more screws on little tabs at each side. Remove those.
6. Remove the little nylon drum catcher from the center of the top... this will make things easier to remove and replace the drum. [Shown nicely in the above video]
7. At the top right side of the frame there is a wiring harness. You will need to cut the zip-tie an squeeze the connectors to disconnect them. [Shown nicely in the above video]
8. As you remove the front, support the drum so that it doesn't fall hard on the blower. Set the panel aside carefully, the top two panels still connected to each other. It's fine to let the drum rest on top of the blower while you do this.
9. Remove the rear hatch behind the motor and rotate the belt off... it won't be tight because you lowered the drum a little. I first did this like the videos show, but you can't see what you're doing... better to remove the little rear access panel.
10. Now lift the drum straight up and back gently to lift it off and out of the old bearing... you can look at the new one if you don't understand, it's just a cradle.
11. One of the YouTube videos shows a "trick" he says makes changing the bearing easy, by re-using the old bracket, but I actually found it easier (since the top is fully removed from the dryer) to change the whole thing... just put a good dob of grease in the ball bearing socket and it will hold in place.
12. Install the new bearing and bracket as per the written instructions, no problem unless you lose the ball bearing... I guess then it's ok to use the old ball bearing. Be sure to fill the grooves on the bottom of the plastic bearing with grease. Use it all and spread a little on the rest of the inside of the plastic.
13. Remove the old spindle ball from the back of the drum and put in the new one. It's a little bit of a stretch for short-armed guys like me, but I did the first screw by poking the screw through the hole and holding it in place with a long screwdriver. Snug it slightly to allow the other holes to line up and hand start the other two screws, rotating the drum so you can reach both sides. If you can't get your arms all the way around it, you might try holding the new spindle in place with tape after lining up the holes. [Not shown in video]
14. Put the drive belt back on the drum and carefully lift it through the opening to near where it was sitting before. Be careful not to pinch or snarl the belt on something below the drum.
15. Replace the drum and lift it high in the back to put it into the new bearing cradle. Carefully rotate the drum a little to make sure it seated properly, because you cannot see it at all.
16. Re-install the front panel, being careful to thread the wiring harness back so it does not get pinched. Re-installation is not as easy as removal, but just hang it from the top brackets and put the screws into the top loosely until you've put in the bottom screws, then replace the side screws and tighten the 8 screws. Be sure to make sure the drum threads over and around the felt on the front panel opening. [Shown nicely in the above video]
17. Putting the belt back on will be a little tougher with the drum supported, but it does go on. Make sure you put it around the idler pulley the right way so that the belt is very tight, and the ridged side is making contact with the motor pulley and the drum, backward would probably slip.
18. Snap the wiring harness connectors back together and put in a new tie to hold it away from the rotating drum.
19. Spin the drum with your hands to make sure it is turning freely and not hitting anything... it's easy to fool yourself into thinking you got the spindle into the bearing correctly. Once you are satisfied all is well, plug in the machine (KEEPING YOUR HANDS AWAY FROM ANY MOVING PARTS OR WIRING) and turn the machine on for a second to see if all is working properly. If so, turn the machine off and unplug it again until you've replaced the top panel, the small hatch at the back where you access the belt and motor pulley, and lastly the bottom panel at the front, after checking that the blower input duct is snug in place and the foam preventing leaks.
20. Clean up your mess, put the tools away, wipe the grease off the machine and shout "Honey, it's fixed."

review_title: Not at fault for making clothes stink like an ashtray.
review_text: My original dryer belt snapped.  It was all chewed up and no part number could be observed.  Kenmore recommended this '341241' part number as the replacement for my model 110.86574100 dryer.  This belt was about 1/4" wide, whereas the original was more like 3/8" wide. It is one of two belts that I purchased from Amazon in an attempt to get one that wouldn't stink.  The mismatch in size muddied the waters for understanding what the true problem was with the dryer. [minus 2 stars for not matching original width and confusing the issue] Nonetheless, it was not the root cause of the clothes that kept coming out smelling like an ashtray (seriously it was nasty).  The smell was from the belt, but only because the bearing at the motor (which takes all the side force from the belt tension) was bad, which caused the spindle to heat up and transfer that heat to the belt (causing the belt to outgas).  Both belts (purchased from different sources) looked about the same and lined up with the groves on the spindle perfectly (as observed through an endoscope camera).  The thermal camera revealed the excessive heat of the bearing (root cause of failure), which likely explains the destruction of the original belt.  Weighing the cost of repairing the bearing issue plus additional items which also needed replacement due to wear, warranted the purchase of a new dryer (which happens to be remarkably more efficient than this dinosaur anyhow).

review_title: Great replacement, prob will need some DIY adjustments
review_text:
First, it's seems all old fan motors have approximately the same dimensions and the replacements are very similar, with helpful additions to make them "universal". Extra spacers, grommets, and such.
All you need to check: will the fan fit in your opening? check the width of the fan blade against the dimensions of your hole.
Second, even tho the products attempt to be universal, they aren't. In my case, the old fan mounted on the rear wall with slots to attach the back shell of the freezer compartment. The replacements won't do that.
Third, as most everyone else has commented, you need to be a bit handy to make adjustments. Drill a couple extra holes, using some spare small bolts you have around, etc.
The product itself is solid. It's quiet, relatively well made (I have to say "relatively" bec what you do expect for $20), and will do the trick if you're handy. My wife is peeved, but our 42-year-old fridge, used as a spare, is back in business!

review_text: My Samsung gas oven suddenly quit heating. The broiler still worked though. A couple YouTube videos later and I nailed down what I thought was the problem. $34 and 10 minutes of my time sure beats the bill for a service call. I will say before buying any igniter, make sure yours is dead. Only 1 video showed me the easy way. Take all the heat shields off all the way down to the gas tube and igniter. Try to heat your oven. If the igniter glows bright red you probably have a different problem. If it doesn't glow at all or just barely, this is the bit for you. Make sure you get one with the right connection. It's worth the extra few bucks for the connector. Once installed and tested as above, everything went back in place. Whoa and behold heat like it hasn't seen in days.y socks will dry in no time now.

review_text: Had this dishwasher for about five years which was 4.5 years too long. I HATE this cheaply-made absolutely inferior pile of garbage. It is abundantly clear the many ways the manufacturer cut corners with crappy fragile plastic parts to maximize profits. Within 6 months the first plastic roller on the top rack disintegrated. Would‚Äôve been $200 to replace the whole rack. I Gerry-rigged a repair and a few months later the other side went. The plastic door for the dishwasher detergent bows and deforms due to the heat so it catches on the edge of its running track half way open. I‚Äôll open the dishwasher to see a waterlogged, bloated dishwasher tab sitting in the bottom of the dishwasher and the dishes are still dirty alone with a coating of dried soap film. Switched to a purely liquid detergent and still no better. The grease trap constantly needs cleaning (weekly or more) and the inside of the dishwasher always has a thick soap film. Typical American manufacturing, charge as much as possible for the lowest quality garbage. If you want any product of any quality, buy German or Japanese manufactured equipment.

review_text:
I used a YouTube video to repair my dryer because I like my dryer, don't want a new one, and don't want to pay $200+ to a repair person to fix it. This part was so inexpensive and works great! It fit perfectly in the heater element. It did take me 2 1/2 hours to fix the dryer because it needed fully disassembled as that is how it is made. It was easy enough and I took lots of pictures while disassembling to make sure everything was put back the same way. I did need a little help from my husband to put the tub back in place and hand me the right tools to me, but other than that, I completed it all by myself! I highly recommended purchasing this product over paying full price for an OEM (over $100) and I suggest searching for YouTube videos to find your dryer and fix it yourself!

Additional info--if your dryer has a sensor, make sure both are replaced at the same time. Don't just buy the heating element or you will end up repairing again soon after the first repair.

review_title: Junk - Threw away after 16 months and 3 repairs
review_text:
I purchased mine as part of a set from Lowe's in October 2012. We had been happy with our Maytag Neptune set for 11 years but our new home required stackable units so we purchased this set. We were excited b/c of the features and it being a newer and prettier set than our 11 year old Neptunes. We had them delivered and installed by Lowe's.

We were initially happy b/c the sensor functions worked better than our Neptune set and the capacity was slightly better. The washer worked ok although this dryer does take longer than our old Neptune.

We started having issues in June 2013 when we opened the dryer and a 3 inch wide by 6 inch long gash appeared in the drum. It was very sharp and very dangerous. It completely shredded a pair of my basketball shorts. Fortunately, it did not damage other clothes. The dryer was completely unusable. This is where the fun began. We contacted Samsung and could not secure an appointment for TWO WEEKs. We had already had a service appointment once on the washer (less serious issue but still a warranty issue) that had taken nearly a month to resolve with 4 different trips. Samsung, the global conglomerate that makes mobile phones, many makes of video monitors / televisions, countless other consumer electronics, hundreds of consumer electronics such as watches-phones-music devices-etc used a sub contractor to work on their appliances that was nearly 4 hours away from our home despite us living within 1 hour of two 800K person cities and 45 minutes from a 250K person city. They would send a tech from Columbia, SC to Beaufort, SC but not from Charleston, SC or Savannah, GA, or Hilton Head, SC....this led to many long lead times and trips back and forth when the techs could not figure out what to do. To add insult to injury, there was a 1 month back order on the drum (they had to replace the entire drum to address this). After 68 days, they finally addressed this with a new drum and we were able to dry clothes again.

Now (February 2014), only 17 months later, we have a dryer that shuts off after about 2-3 minutes running. No matter what setting we use; it just turns off after about 2-3 minutes. If we stand there long enough re-starting it it may run 10 minutes. Drying one load can take 5-6 hours and require you to start and re-start over and over. We contacted Samsung and were told we would wait about two weeks to see a tech, again from Columbia, SC; and we would have to pay for this honor.

So long Samsung; your equipment was picked up by our recycling folks in Beaufort. We have learned our lesson...no more Samsung equipment period. We even wrote letters to your office of the president and to customer care people who helped us before and got NO RESPONSE after two weeks. We called both 800 numbers and got nothing but "we are sorry" and run arounds. So, we bought new electrolux equipment and we will never ever buy Samsung anything again. Shame on you for building junk and then not supporting it...and finally for not even acknowledging our communications with you.

Buyer beware. I would not buy Samsung unless you buy some type of long term warranty or have the energy and time to do your own work on their equipment. They clearly do not care enough to support their products in market by having anyone able to respond to emails or letters and dispatching sub contractors from 200 miles away. Unbelievable.

review_title: Open at Back.  Gray Color is Very Attractive
review_text: I purchased two (2) of these Sunbeam Washing Machine Covers.  I purchased the gray color and I purchased one for my washer and one for my dryer.  Both fit perfectly because these cover are "open" in the back.  If you can imagine putting on your jacket backwards, that is how these cover fit.  The top, front, and sides are totally, and completely covered (including the raised "control panel."  The open back is NOT noticeable at all.  This design is perfect since the washer and dryer I am using them for are still in use, so they are still connected to water hoses, gas lines, exhaust vents, etc.  The sizing is perfect.  I have them covering "old school" appliances, a full size washer and full size dryer, both of which have the "control panel" on top at the rear of the machines.  These covers are patterned after these type of older appliances.  The gray color is very neutral, a light colored gray.  I originally wanted to buy the beige color since my laundry room (basement) is painted tan and white.  But the price difference between gray and brown was significant, so I purchased the gray and it is perfect since the water heater and furnace all have gray tones.  The material is a little thin but these are just covers, they are not meant to withstand any significant wear and tear.  Again, this is another reason to consider the gray color, which was a lot cheaper than any other color.  These covers are a great purchase.

Dear Mr. Hunt:

Thank you for visiting the Whirlpool web site. We appreciate hearing from you concerning your Whirlpool washer. We apologize for the letters rubbing off; however, we recommend using only mild soap and warm water in cleaning the appliances. Unfortunately, we do not have a stencil to provide to you; therefore, we recommend obtaining a use and care manual for assistance.

review_text:
I purchased this washer a year ago (not at Amazon, but posting a review so others can learn some of my issues before making a purchasing decision).

The Good:
(1) It's quiet.
(2) It doesn't take a walk across the laundry room when spinning, as my old machine did.
(3) It has an agitator, which cleans clothes well. (Old washer did NOT clean clothes).

The Bad:
(1) The ONLY setting that allows water to fill to completely cover clothes is the "Heavy" setting.
(2) Lid lock. What's the point?
(3) While it cleans clothes very well, it also destroys them. I had eight towels shredded, new bed sheets get holes in them, and a few nice blouses ripped beyond repair. And that was just in the first month of owning this washer.
(4) It eats clothes. So many, in fact, that I've named this machine "Jaws." I have lost six pair of underwear, four socks, two bathrobe belts and a few hair ties that are now underneath the agitator. You cannot get that agitator off to remove/retrieve the eaten items. There is a lug nut waaaay down at the bottom of the agitator that can only be reached with a socket wrench extension (which I purchased but, alas, the freakin' screw was on too tight). Called a repairman, who told me that the agitator cannot be removed. (Huh?! WTF?!) Told me I would just have to leave the "eaten" clothing under the agitator. (Great. Now mold can develop!)
(5) Be prepared to see your gas or electricity bill (depending upon what type of dryer you have) DOUBLE with this washing machine. Clothes come out sopping wet. I have to dry most clothes TWICE and some loads (like towels and bedsheets) THREE times to get them dry.

This washer's price may be cheap, but you'll spend far more replacing ripped and lost clothing items--as well as increased costs from multiple drying cycles--than what you'll save with the lower initial machine price.

My advice: Take a pass.

If you product get too dry during cure add a green leaf to bring rh up in the jars. If it‚Äôs too dry after cure add the Integra packs. When your product is mostly cured 2-3 weeks and the jar rh is steady at 62% rh. Then add pack to jar for storage in cool dark place. If you have loud dank and want to put a cut carrot or green leaf in jar. Top shelf Skunk, Haze or Kush should never see a pack in with it unless it‚Äôs already dry and/or has lost its smell.

review_title: Use wash bags to avoid damage to your clothes
review_text:
Since we don't have hookups and our home is small, this is our next best option. I'd rather have a full size machine since this one requires your attention to move to each step, but it's doable until we get hookups installed. It cleans really well, and it can do really small loads, which I like. The agitator is incredibly strong though, and will easily damage clothes if they are not placed in a wash bag, which reduces the usefulness of the machine somewhat. Fortunately, I'm mostly using it to wash cloth diaper prefolds which can take a beating.

If you use wash bags, get ones that keep the zipper from opening in the wash, otherwise they WILL open. Also be sure to get bags with good stitching as this machine has ripped the zippers out of several of my wash bags.

Mine arrived missing a small piece (the lid that goes inside the spinner), but customer service was very responsive and sent me a replacement quickly.

UPDATE: Forgot to add, it does the equivalent of about a 1/3 load in a regular machine. And it does little for lint. We ended up getting a dryer partly because line drying takes too long when you have an infant to take care of, and it removes most of the lint.

review_title: worked on my Kenmore Series 70 model 110.20712 991
review_text: The other day i was washing a load of laundry and right before it was ready to drain the water i noticed my machine seem to quit working. So i messed around with it awhile and come to find out everything worked expect it would not drain nor would the spin cycle work. So i had the fun job of scooping all the water out by hand. I then did some research and found out that the lid switch was one of the common things to cause this issue i was having. So i borrowed a multimeter tester from my dad and then i pulled my washer apart and found the switch and unhooked it to test it and from what i could tell was it was shot. When i decided that was the issue i came to my favorite place to look for a replacement and it was here on amazon. I was surprised i could find it for about 8-10 dollar including any shipping charges. However i decided to buy one from a seller that offered 2 day prime shipping and paid about 30 dollars for 1 day shipping instead. I know i overpaid and it was worth the extra 20 dollars to get it in a day. I just did not want to wait a week or so to fix the issue. I also looked around to make sure this would work with my exact washer and found that sears was selling the same one for 45 dollars on their website so in the end i still saved some money. If you need to replace the switch save money and do it yourself. It is so easy to find videos online to teach you and after you do it once it will be that much easier the next time. I would say it would take about 20-30 minutes to replace it yourself. It took me less that 10 because i already had the washing machine apart and i pretty much knew what to do before hand so i wasn't fighting with it today when i switched it for the new one. Overall i am happy and i was happy to get a load of clothes washed. I am really happy and was happy to find it here on amazon.

review_title: Easy Fix to Cure Oven Which Won't Light Up Broiler
review_text: This worked Perfect to replace a bad Igniter.  My old one would light up red hot, but not draw enough amps/current to turn open the gas valve.  It looked like it was working fine too, that's the problem.  It glowed red hot. But the gas valve would not open.  The old Igniter was Weak. So this New Igniter solved the problem for a very low price.  It is not too hard to install.  You may need to use the wire nuts which are included with this new igniter.  The attachment screws (to the burner bar) came out/went back in okay, but you will need to pull out your oven to connect the wires up in back.  You Do Not need to Solder the wires, as you tighten high temp wire nuts on them or use the connector if it matches up.  You need to pull racks out and the bottom oven pan and possibly pull off the whole oven door, that's about it.  Will take about an hour, including pulling oven out, attaching wires, attaching unit to burner bar, etc.  Be sure the wire nuts are tight and be sure the Insulated wires don't rub against the stove metal cutout in the back of the oven.  I put electrical tape on that area, so the wires would touch that tape and not metal over time.

review_text:
I have a ball python and i already had three [[ASIN:B000NZZG3S Hydrofarm MTPRTC Digital Thermostat For Heat Mats]] thermostats to keep three heat mats at their correct temperatures.

i also have two [[ASIN:B000634980 Tropicaire Humidifier & Air Exchanger]] connected to a fish tank pump to keep the tank's humidity high. the problem is that the humidifiers work too well, and the humidity sometimes goes too high. i needed a controller to turn off the air bubbler to help regulate the right level.

i also have a heat lamp to keep the ambient air in the tank high, as well as a UVB bulb for "day light"

up until this point there was no easy control of everything.

now using this controller coupled with a [[ASIN:B0057OC5WK SainSmart 8-Channel 5V Relay Module for Arduino DSP AVR PIC ARM]] i have programed the controller to replace the three temperature controller, a light timer and to control the humidity and ambient temperatures.

the programing of the board is extremely similar to assembly language. it is not difficult to program even if you are not familiar with assembly. the companies website contains user manuals that explain in good detail how to perform different functions in code.

the web interface of the board is how everything is controlled and configured, no need for a hardware programmer.

if you make a mistake with your program syntax the web page will tell you the code line that has the issue so you can look for your mistake.

my only complaint is that the board does not support floating point calculations and does not allow more than 1000 lines of code. i was originally hoping to attach an LCD display to the controller but between limited code space and I/O ports that was not possible.

when using the thermal sensors over the 1-wire bus, make sure to do some research on how to properly implement the network and reduce any hassles you may otherwise encounter.

over all i am very pleased.

EDIT 5/22/2012:

my board had been experiencing some technical issues and after contacting CAI Networks support they immediately sent me a new board while i mailed back my current board. The technical support was fantastic and overall customer support is great.

my new board appears to be working 100% perfectly. highly recommend this product and the company itself.
product_title: Webcontrol Universal Network Enabled Timer Temperature Humidity I/o Controller

review_title: And on the third day, the refrigerator was alive!
review_text:
On Wednesday, the refrigerator let the family down. Less than 9 years old and the Whirlpoool Gold model GI5FSAXVY03 gave up the ghost. On that very same day, the Independence day appliance sales were ending. So what is a family of 4 to do? We ordered a new, but on back order refrigerator. So starts the race! Can I fix it before the new fridge ships? Trusty Amazon has the correct part at half the cost of the OEM site and delivers 42 hours later. 5 minutes after the part hits the porch, the reefer is humming along. Hooray for the service!!! We "saved" $2800. For the technical folks out there:
- The refrigerator would not cool, no compressor action or noise
- The interior lights would come on when the door opened
- The front water dispenser/ice maker would emit a "beeeeeeeeep" for as long as the lever to dispense was pushed
- Any front panel button push on the dispenser would perform what was essentially a "light check" on the front dispenser where every light and LED segment would light up
- When unplugged and plugged back in, the only thing that would happen is the water/ice dispenser would make a noise like the ice chute was being closed. Nothing else.
So, we bought the HV control module, part number W10310240. Swap was a piece of cake. Once the new panel was installed, I just had to google "programming Whirlpool refrigerator" and follow the directions to enter the correct program code. The programming instructions should have shipped with the HV control board, but they did not. The review would have been 5 stars if the programming instructions were included.
I hope this review guides you to a good outcome if you are ever in the same situation!
product_title: Whirlpool W10310240 Control Board, HV

review_title: Samsung products need to be discontinued.
review_text:
Quick update to this: I did get the oven control panel repaired after a lovely woman at Lowe's contacted Samsung for me to prove it was in warranty. However now a little over a year later, the oven doesn't ignite. If you search for "Samsung oven doesn't heat", there are 18 pages on the Samsung forums of customers with 1 to 2 year old Samsung ovens that don't ignite.

Original review: This doesn't even deserve 1 star. As every other negative review states, it works great for a couple of months, then breaks. I bought this last August. Control panel buttons stopped working in May. After fighting with Samsung to get it repaired under the 1-year warranty, the buttons have stopped working again. Samsung claims I'm not in warranty. According to the representative I spoke to, the receipt I uploaded when I registered the product last August doesn't transfer to the service department so I need to upload the receipt again. Lowe's prints their receipts on tissue thin paper that is no longer legible so Samsung won't accept it. Since my Samsung refrigerator has also been repaired four times in three years (which I didn't actually buy but Best Buy lost my LG refrigerator and gave me the Samsung instead - long story), I not only refuse to buy any Samsung product ever again, I now make sure to warn anyone considering their products.

Durably constructed of stainless steel with a flip open plastic top and a large top port for hot water. Fits most machines although you can't just insert willy nilly. That could be a problem if you toss in without that fitting and slam the lid shut, you may damage your machine or the pod. review_text: Between the internet for information and Amazon for providing an amazing array of products, the solution for my malfunctioning fridge was identified in minutes and resolved in just a couple of days. This little gadget runs the defrost cycle of the freezer - absolutely critical to the operation of the fridge! If the freezer coils can't defrost, they will soon ice over and will not exchange cool air properly with the non-freezer section of the refrigerator. Eventually, the fridge box gets warmer and warmer, unable to exchange the heat over the freezer coils. The little unit was easy to access under a cover in the top of the fridge. The device plugs in - one way - can't go wrong. Just match the cycle times printed on your original with the new one. This one works perfectly in my little Haier shop fridge. Back in business!

review_text: Unfortunately I had nothing but problems with this from day one.  After spending $600 I expected to make a great machine that would last a long time. There was no way to get the hair out because it was inside of the air gap on the front and had obviously made its way inside there during the molding process.  The only way to see it was with the contrast of the white ice in the tray.  Do incredibly disgusted and sending it back to Amazon.

review_title: Ordered this filter back in May and it worked great. Now it's September and the water from my ...
review_text:
Ordered this filter back in May and it worked great. Now it's September and the water from my fridge is already back to tasting "dirty." The regular tap water where I live really isn't that bad to begin with. In fact, I'm the only one in my household who notices a difference between the tap and filtered (I'm a water snob, apparently). Since water is pretty much all I drink, it's easy for me to detect variations.

I think this filter should have lasted longer than 4 months, but in that 4 months it did a decent job. I can't say how well it would hold up in a place with especially gross or chlorinated water.

Despite only lasting 4 months, I'll probably continue ordering this filter. For $12 a piece, replacing it 3 times a year still costs less than name-brand filters that (theoretically) need to be replaced twice a year.

review_text: Factory replacement (updated part number and design) for Samsung dishwasher door lock. Our seven year old dishwasher lock stopped setting itself to ‚Äúopen‚Äù when door was pulled (automatic lock only) so when you went to close it would not do so properly. After a week of manually setting the lock I ordered this which is not the same part as the original but is the updated (current part) for my model. 30 minutes after delivery washer was back in service and have not had a problem since. Make sure it is the right part especially if your dishwasher original part can also be found for sale on Amazon by checking more specialized information sites. review_title: Fixed ice dispenser door in 10 minutes.
review_text:
Issues it fixed:
1.ice would not dispense well or at all, often blocked by flap door and filled chute to overflowing.
2. Ice/frost build-up at top of chute because the flap door was stuck open.

When dispensing ice, push the lever, watch and listen for the little flap door to open and close. It should open fully to dispense ice and then snap shut about 2 seconds after releasing the lever. If the door never opens or stays open, a faulty solenoid is most likely the culprit.
I was able to remove and replace this item with a Phillips head screwdriver in less than 10 minutes.
Watch a couple of YouTube videos for helpful tips for installing.

Worth every penny to have my ice on demand working like new!

review_text:
I have had a "SpaceMaker" washer/dryer combination where the washer just gave out one day after 15 years of use. I decided then and there I would not buy a single combination unit again and went for separate washer and dryer, that way you replace one part and not the whole unit. I bought this dryer as it fit my need and was within my price range.

I have had the unit for a month and think the dryer is very good. People complain about the small amount of clothes you can dry but after having the SpaceMaker I am used to doing more smaller loads. I have also been combining this dryer with a drying rack. I take the wet clothes out of the washer, let them air dry for up to 8 hours then put them in the dryer. This process has greatly reduced the time I need to use the dryer and what I have done in the past with my SpaceMaker unit. So far, so good. I have no complaints. I also don't think it is that loud compared to my old dryer, even though Haier dryer has a slight larger capacity than the SpaceMaker. I am single and can fit all my clothes in the dryer, including a Queen size sheet, without problems. For towels I only put two at a time, but I pre-dry them as it saves time and energy.

I have also decided not to mount it on the wall. It weighs about 50 lbs but I am afraid it could come crashing down on my washer. Maybe some others are brave but not me. I don't trust my walls to hold it. I am using a simple cart that I bought on Amazon.com that fits the bill.

All in all I replaced a SpaceMaker unit with a washer, dryer and cart for less money so I can't complain.

review_title: The refrigerator looks nice but always seemed to make a lot of noise ...
review_text:
I have had the refrigerator for just over 5 years. The first 3 or so years were ok. The refrigerator looks nice but always seemed to make a lot of noise and sounded noisy then lower models I have owned even while being a renter. After 3 1/2 years, everything started happening. First the compressor and cooling line needed to be replaced, luckily that was under full warranty. Then 6 months after that, the main computer board that regulates the refrigerator's temperatures went bad, and that was not under warranty! Several hundreds of $$ later, issue resolved. Then six months later, guess what? Leak in the cooling line and compressor started going bad again. Parts for this repair would have been covered under manufacturer warranty, but labor was not so the estimated repair was around $700. At this point I am going to get a new refrigerator, not a Kitchen Aid this time just in case.

AS FYI, alll three times the refrigerator had problems, the symptoms were always the same. The freezer temperature would increase to 8, 9, 10 up to 14 degrees, then go back to 0 only to happen again numerous times throughout the day/week. Eventually it stop returning back to 0 degrees and the refrigerator portion also increased in temperature until both sections no longer cooled.

review_title: SDoes not work properly for range 4-prong to 3-prong
review_text:
This adapter does not work for me.

I bought a new stove that came with a 4-prong plug. I have a 3-prong receptacle. I bought this adapter. It does not work properly in my case. Here is why.

After the 1996 code change, appliances were sold with the case ground separated from neutral. This configuration requires a 4-conductor power cord with a separate ground wire that connects street ground (from your junction box) to the ground screw on the appliance.

The NEC still allows the use of existing 3-prong receptacles, if you are replacing a range and have a 3-slot receptacle present. However, you must connect the ground screw on the appliance (the chassis ground) to the neutral terminal.

This adapter does not connect the chassis ground to neutral. If I use the adapter, my stove will work, but the adapter does not make the connection properly. What I did instead was to add a grounding strap from the appliance's ground screw to the appliance's neutral connection and then use a 3-prong cable.

Please look at the accompanying figure for details.

review_title: Bad Compressors and Poor Phone Support
review_text:
My LG refrigerator is less than 2 years old. The compressor failed on October 30. When I called LG, I was told that there was only a 1-year warrantee, so the repair would be at my expense. She told me to open and close the freezer doors, but this didn‚Äôt work.
I decided to contact a local service repairman and after he looked at the fridge (and a $75 fee), he told me the compressor was bad and that he was seeing a lot of these bad compressors on LG refrigerators. The product looks nice and has some great features, but it does me no good if they install bad compressors. After some research, we found that there is a class action lawsuit for this problem before 2018. Shame on LG for continuing to sell cheap, unreliable products.
After more research on my own, I found out that these compressors have a 5-year warrantee, so I had new hope. Too bad LG did not volunteer this information on the phone.
So I decided to call LG directly once again. On November 10, I called LG to inform them about the diagnosis of a compressor problem. The man I spoke to in service was incompetent and unable to speak in an understandable manner. He assured me that I had an appointment on November 12 between 8-12 AM. So I stayed home that day waiting for the repair visit.
At noon that day there was no phone call and no visit. So I called LG once again to report this issue. The lady who handled the call said she had no record of the appointment. Also, she had no record of my problem, no model number, no address, etc. This was my third time talking to LG! She proceeded to reschedule the appointment, but there was another delay of 5 days. She mentioned it would be fixed free of charge for my inconvenience.
On Monday, November 16, I was contacted by LG the day before my new assigned appointment. This was much appreciated! And on November 17 a competent repairman changed out my compressor. So after 2 ¬Ω weeks I finally had a working refrigerator.
In the end it only cost me $75 for an initial diagnosis. However, the phone help line at LG is very poor and this weakness should be corrected by the company.
product_title: LG LMXS28626S 28 cu.ft. 4-Door French Door Refrigerator - Stainless Steel

review_title: Fixed the "OE" error and loud running drain pump on our LG model WM3070HWA
review_text: Do yourself a favor and attack this from the bottom. Much easier and much faster. Someone on this forum suggested that and I'm glad they did. (There's a YouTube showing how to put machine into a diagnostic mode and step it through the various cycles.) After watching multiple how to videos where they disassembled entire washer, this was better. Flip it on it's right side (facing washer), remove plastic bottom, and you're basically looking at the pump. Remove screws holding the filter/drain tube assembly and you've got pump in hand. Took about an hour because I really took my time. Next one would be 20 minutes. Washer is now working and pump is much quieter. Time will tell how long this pump works. review_title: City living, now with the luxuries of the suburbs
review_text:
I'm your average 30 year old living in NYC in a modest sized apartment, of course, with no dishwasher and no ability to install one based on my lease contract. My roomate and I had a dishwasher in our old apartment and have really been terrible about doing the dishes, but since neither of us like looking at a sink full of dirty cups, I took matters into my own hands and bought this baby. So far I've had it about a week and here are my initial thoughts:

1. This is perfect for your normal city dweller running mugs/cups/utensils from food delivery and maybe a plate or two. If you have a big family or a lot of dishes it'll still get the job done, but its not really tailor made for that.
2. I've been using those Cascade three-in-one dishwasher tablets and they work really well, all the dishes come out clean and sparkly just like at my parent's house!
3. It was super easy to set up, although it is a big large on my countertop. However, its a price I'm willing to pay for having a dishwasher and it is nice looking alongside my stainless steel appliances. Not exactly stainless steel itself, but close enough.
4. Its rather quiet and doesn't move around or anything.

Once or twice I've gotten an E1 error part was through doing the wash, which it seems like just meant I didn't have my water turned on high enough. Since making that change it has completed each was perfectly (I've done about one a day just because its so exciting, I can't use up my cups fast enough!)

I will update if I have any issues, and for the first time ever I bought the 3 year warantee because there was no way I was going to try and mail this beast somewhere if something happened. I hope I won't need it since the quality really is quite good, but for $30 its worth the peace of mind, even though its usually a sucker move.

So if you're looking for a little dishwasher to make your urban life feel more suburban, this little guy really does the trick!

review_title: Perfect part for my Maytag. Also fits other brands too!
review_text:
I have a Maytag Model MEP5775BAF Oven that needed a new Bake Element (this is the lower element) and this fit perfect and took less than 3 minutes to replace. Even though I have a Maytag this Whirlpool part is made for several models. Here is the different part numbers this Heating Element is knows as: W10310274 (AP4567080) replaces 74010883, 1863288, AH3407743, EA3407743, PS3407743. Whirlpool brands include Maytag, KitchenAid, Jenn-Air, Amana, Magic Chef, Admiral, Norge, Roper, and others.
Before you start make sure you shut off the power to the Stove/Oven from the Service (Breaker) Panel - just flip the switch to ‚Äúoff‚Äù. You'll need a Philips screwdriver to remove the 2 each screws on the back oven wall. Once the screws are removed slowly pull the heating element out from the wall to disconnect the 2 wire connections.
Note: The hardest part of this whole task is getting the old element out from the backside of the oven without the electric terminals coming loose and stuck behind the oven wall. If that happens you‚Äôll have to remove the stove back panel to get to this area, which means you‚Äôll have to remove the stove away from the kitchen wall to get to it. A big pain!
I find moving the heating element side to side will allow the interior wall insulation to unwrap itself from the terminal leads at the tips of the elements. If everything goes right you should have about 3 or 4 inches of wire exposed though the cavity. Now just disconnect the electrical lead on each end of the heating element and swap them out to the new heating element. Reinstall the 2 screws and wipe off the new heating element with a damp towel to remove fingers prints, debris, etc. Oils from your hands could cause a ‚Äúhot‚Äù spot and burn the new element at that area. Now turn the Breaker back on and turn the oven to bake. Wait 3 - 5 seconds and you should sense heat. Good luck!
product_title: Whirlpool W10310274 Bake, Black

review_title: Easy to install, perfect replacement, hope it's more durable than the original (fit a Maytag)
review_text: Although this is a Whirpool-branded part, it perfectly fit my Maytag model MDB7600AWS. This was a perfect replacement and online videos helped prepare me for the easy, quick installation.  A few pointers on that:  TURN OFF THE ELECTRICAL POWER TO THE DISHWASHER (at the fuse or breaker box) BEFORE THE INSTALLATION, since this job puts you directly in contact with electrical parts inside. It is easy to crack or strip delicate plastic parts by overtightening the screws during installation, so I recommend you avoid using an electric screwdriver for this job.  I needed a Torx T20 hand screwdriver, and needle nose pliers (used to gently pry the wiring harness connector away from the metal electrical contacts on the latch assembly).  There were two different types of screws holding the inside of my washing machine door: shorter sheet metal screws (with pointy tips), and longer machine screws (with a flat leading tip). The longer screws are for the "top" row--the part of the inside of the dishwasher door that the latch sits under. Those longer screws connect to molded plastic threads inside the door, so BE VERY CAREFUL TO AVOID OVERTIGHTENING, so you do not strip the fragile plastic threads, or even crack the plastic door parts.  The shorter sheet metal screws fit along the sides of the inside of the dishwasher door. Those connect into metal, but you still need to avoid overtightening those, to prevent cracking the inside of the dishwasher door.

review_title: Removal problems associated with dryer motor
review_text:
Once installed, this motor works just fine. Unfortunately, removal of the old motor was not as simple as the online video would suggest. The key is the separation of the blower fan from the rear of the motor. The fan is made from resin or plastic and has a raised square journal surrounding the threaded hole that allows the fan to thread onto the rear of the motor shaft. Using an appropriate size wrench, hold the square journal on the fan to prevent it from turning while using another wrench to turn the pulley retaining nut on the front of the shaft. As you turn the motor shaft, the fan is suppose to unthread from the motor shaft, The fan end of the shaft is left-handed thread so that the fan tends to remain tightly fixed to the shaft during operation.
Unfortunately, due to the type of material the fan is made from, when drying multiple loads of laundry, the fan becomes pliable and can actually get tighter on the shaft. When the unit cools, you'll find that the fan has become frozen to the shaft. Attempting to apply excessive force to rotate the shaft only serves to round-off the square journal on the fan making it impossible to remove. This happened to me causing me to have to remove the back of the machine, the blower duct & use a saws-all to cut the motor shaft so the motor could be removed. Truly a nuisance and a lot more work.
This, of course, is not the fault of the motor since the blower fan is not a part of the motor and when you order a new motor, you do not receive a new fan with it. The fan, if required, must be ordered separately. I believe this is the dryer manufacturer's design flaw. If the blower fan were made of aluminum or some other light-weight metal, rounding off the square journal would be far less likely.

review_title: Worked perfectly on an unlisted compactor model
review_text:
Even though my weird model trash compactor wasn't in the manufacturer or model list for this repair kit, I could tell by the pictures it was awfully close and took a chance.

The gears are a perfect match and just what I needed. Installing the new gears was a chore - not the fault of the kit but the fault of a 30+ year old compactor that had never been serviced. Getting the big gear off was fairly easy, but I did it in an unconventional way - instead of loosening the motor I loosened one of the corner gears.

Getting the shaft gear off was pure hell, I finally had to heat the shaft and then the pin could be hammered out using a pin-punch. Putting the new gear on was straight-forward as I could apply some grease first.

Then I started sorting through all the other parts in the kit and discovered they do not fit inside my weird compactor, but then again nothing was malfunctioning other than the broken gear so I didn't care. So the parts for the two rods that pull the compactor top down were not used.

I used this opportunity to thoroughly clean the chain and screw rods, and put heavy duty grease back on them - hopefully I will get years of additional service for the old compactor. I checked the compactor to make sure it was not compressing too hard - this breaks the gear I had to replace. If you have your original manuals then you will find a section that describes how to set the compaction pressure correctly. Too little and you use more bags, too much and you start damaging the compactor components.

review_title: works well but slightly bad design by whirlpool....
review_text: So my washer is a whirlpool GHW9200LW, and 2 out of 3 of these baffles were missing. Don‚Äôt know how it got that way - washer came used with a house. Without the baffles, the clothes get torn up. There are sharp metal clip/latches built into the drum. The baffles latch into the drum clips pretty tightly. But obviously not tight enough - if they fell off! Anyway, the first trick is to clip the baffles in carefully testing the alignment to make sure all clips have engaged. The next step involves a bit of tricky repair work: 1) take off the washer top. 2) Locate a small corrugated rubber water feed around the 11 o'clock position. 3) Carefully wiggle this loose - don't break it! Use your fingers - not a screwdriver. 4) With the water tube off the drum exterior can, you will see the stainless steel can inside. you are actually looking at the outside of the stainless steel can. Rotate the drum until you see the screw hole for the baffles. NOTE: you might want to locate this hole before actually installing the baffles. 5) Using a magnetic screwdriver, mount the screw, and then carefully start seating into the baffle through the water tube hole! Using this method avoids a boat-load of repair work. Without this trick, it‚Äôs probably not worth trying to install new baffles. Anyway, the whirlpool company should have design these baffles with a better screw/locking mechanism so they don't actually fall out! The washer is pretty nice though. Good luck!
product_title: Whirlpool 285976 Baffle for Washer Pack of 3

review_title: Makes ice quickly...in very small amounts.
review_text: This ice maker has a pretty quick cycle time.  It will make Ice cubes in about 8-15 minutes depending on the size you request.  However it only makes 10 cubes at a time.  So about enough for 2 glasses of cold drink.  If you keep the reservoir full of water and the ice catch basket empty it will keep making ice all day.  The problem is the catch basket is full in about an hour and the machine will stop making ice at that point.  Then if you don't empty it of ice the ice will melt and you have nothing left.  If you keep up on emptying the tray and refilling with water it will make a 10 lb bag of like you buy at the store in a day, but it's a lot of work getting there.  Instead of spending $85 and working at it all day, just go buy the ice at the store.

review_title: If your Samsung filter stopped fitting, **THIS** is the DA29-00003G replacement that actually works!
review_text:
There are apparently many people who are in the same boat of having Samsung's supposed "DA29-00003G" model filter suddenly stop fitting in their refrigerator. My fridge has always used that Samsung filter, and I had reordered the same exact item 4 times from Amazon...until it suddenly was impossible to screw in. The reason is because the plastic tabs at the top of the current iteration of the "Samsung DA29-00003G" filter are configured differently than the old one. Why they would call it the same part number is beyond me...

So I tried looking in a bunch of listings on here for tabs that seemed similar to my *previous* iteration of DA29-00003G filter...and for some reason most of the 3rd party (i.e. Chinese) filters don't clearly show the tab configuration. I tried a different brand that did not work, before finally arriving at this "ICEPURE" filter -- and it fits great!

The taste is frankly indiscernible from my prior Samsung ones -- though I understand from reading other reviews from more knowledgable people when I was researching a replacement that this ICEPURE filter does not filter out some types of contaminants that the Samsung one does. For me, since I am in a major metropolitan city, that was not of particular concern to me since I have to assume that the water treatment is pretty top-notch at the municipal level. My main concern was finding a filter that actually FITS my fridge -- which this one does fantastically...and also costs around 1/3 the price as the Samsung!

review_title: Absolutely perfect fit. Exact replacement for original in my Kenmore ...
review_text: Absolutely perfect fit.  Exact replacement for original in my Kenmore dryer.  Some advice.... consider buying the blower wheel as well or else try to remove the blower wheel (which you have to do in order to remove the old motor) before ording the motor so that if you end up needing the wheel you can order it along with the motor.  I say this because the plastic blower wheel's square hole, into which you're supposed to insert a 1/2" drive in order to remove the wheel, stripped.  I've read some other reviews on other sites where this happened to other people.  I suppose if you have Amazon Prime you can just get the motor and if you end up needing the wheel you can get one delivered in two days like I did.  The only way I could get the wheel off was to chisel it apart with a screwdriver and hammer unfortunately.  Overall though, a very easy removal and installation process and the motor works great.  Very quiet, like a new dryer.  Saved about $60 vs. buying it at SearsPartsDirect.com not to mention it beats paying several $ hundred on a new dryer.  Here's a link to an excellent video that shows how easy the replacement is:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2tfqkXtjvfI

review_title: OEM Replacement Ice Maker for my Whirl Pool Conquest Side by Side item 2198597
review_text:
My original ice maker stopped making ice. I performed the normal checks like first off checking to see if water (water valves also) was being delivered, and the additional checks for sensors functioning, power, motor working, etc. I diagnosed a few parts that may have been the culprit, but buying parts individually would cost much more. I also checked none OEM replacements at a lesser cost that probably would have worked fine. However, I decided to pay the extra money for the OEM ice maker, and I am very happy with my decision. The unit was an exact match and the performance did not disappoint. I expect it to last for years to come and if needed could probably use parts from the old OEM unit. Also, I selected standard shipping but the seller shipped this product very quickly; humorously they must have had sympathy that I needed ice immediately. I would recommend this product to others.

(my standard note: When I rate a product I impart as much clarity and actual personal experience of the product as possible to hopefully assist others. I do not use or allude to for the money; and more than likely neither will the manufacturer if they expect to sell a product. If I pay $15 for a product selling in the market versus $500 for an original; I expect the same performance regardless of price savings. Making and selling a product at a lower costs does not equate to cheap. Less cost should only mean that a competitor has learned to do the same or better at a lower cost.)

review_text:
This fit our Frigidaire/Electrolux stove very well, even though it was not listed for that application. The wire connections are angled slightly differently, but this made no difference in useability in my stove after a minor adjustment to the arrangement. It works as well as the original, but this one was significantly less expensive the standard replacement.

Replacing these surface elements is surprisingly simple. BE SURE TO UNPLUG YOUR STOVE, OR TURN OF THE CIRCUIT BREAKER FIRST, because some of the wires on the element have power all the time, as I was surprised to find out. Just remove two screws on the front of the oven, and lift the stovetop like the hood of a car, and prop it open with a stick of some kind. Look closely at style of wire connections you have, in order to make sure that you buy the least expensive element that will fit the size of your wire terminals. I had to re-arrange a few screws to make this element line up with my mounting clips, because it wasn't the factory original part that I could have bought for my stove. After about 5 minutes work with a screwdriver to move the mounting clips (the new element came with the screw holes already drilled in it), this element snapped right in place just like the original, for about half the price, and no service charge or appointment.

review_title: Looks nice but as far as quality, you get what you pay for
review_text:
This range good looks nice and I get a lot of compliments on it. However, there is not sufficient "chimney" for a standard 8 ft ceiling when the good is installed standard height from the stove top. It's also pretty flimsy material. You get what you pay for. It was not that easy to install for my husband due to the short and flimsy material, and he is a general contractor who can pretty much figure out anything.
I will say that the company's customer service was very good, answering multiple questions both before and after purchase via email, providing installation instructions (which are not included!), and rapidly mailing missing parts - washers for the screws in the glass.

The fan has good power. I'd rate it moderately noisy even at low speed. It does not draw as well as I would wish from the front burners. The lights are okay, would not depend on them for sole lighting as they are set toward the back of the hood.

review_title: Works well, easy to install, not 100% reliable, alerts are too slow for anything important
review_text:
Installed the base station and three sensors in a house. Installation and registration was easy, just need to do it in the right order. Installed the app for iPhone and that worked off the same account from registration. The sensors work well but lose connection roughly once a week. Signal strength is above 90% according to the app but sensors will not report for hours. Sensors are between 15 to 30ft away and on different floors, but no correlation to the failures.

The alerts are slow, I'll get a text alert at 8:30am for an event that happened at 6:30am according to the text. Charts in the app and online work but the x-axis is a pretty useless serious of random timestamps for a chart that spans 4-5 days. Touching the charts will highlight datapoints with temp and time, but no date. No ability to zoom or scroll through time. You can download a CSV file of the data via the website, but when I tried to download the file it occasionally gave me an empty CSV file with just a single row of headers. When it works it appears to have all the data going back months.

All in all useful product, but if you need something guaranteed reliable you might want to look elsewhere.
product_title: La Crosse Alerts Mobile 926-25100-WGB Wireless Monitor System with Temperature & Humidity

‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜUpdate‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ‚òÜ
Contact was made with seller via Amazon. They replied in ~ 10 minutes and offered a replacement at no cost with an apology. They back up the items they sell and offered a quick remedy. review_title: Totally legit and saved my coworkers from my unwashed fragrance
review_text:
My 1.5 year old $1400 samsung washer stopped working completely. I ripped the thing apart and learned just about everything about washers. They're stupidly simple. Every route with my e05 (I believe) error lead me to believe a hose was clogged. Pulled out every single hose and ran water through them, no issues. Finally somewhere I found that I need to grab a voltmeter and test the continuity of the connections of each valve/solenoid (idk whatever) and my cold water valve was just dead. The one next to it and my hot were fine, but my cold was reporting 0. Ordered this and had it one day shipped and I was up and running the next day. Seriously had low expectations but yall saved my hide. I had just gotten home from a 2 week camping/hiking trip and ran out of clothes to wear. Also side by side this looks exactly like my original Samsung valve. It must be the same manufacturer.

edit; Sorry, I should mention, my issue was that my washer would "run" for about 3 minutes but not fill with water then give me the E05 error. Basically a "washer cant fill with water" error. And installing this was literally 2 (maybe 4) screws on the back of the washer, then you unplug two electric plugs. It was stupidly simple. Putting the top back on my washer was more difficult by far.

review_title: Wonderful coffee without all the waste
review_text:
My husband and I use our Keurig coffee maker at least ten to fifteen times a day. We spend so much money on coffee pods but it is literally embarrassing! I was so thankful to get these reusable carafe coffee pods that I couldn't contain my joy when they came in. My husband and I tend to like really dark strong coffee and it is very hard to get that using regular Keurig coffee pots. However with these reusable ones I can pack as much of the dark roast coffee that I like in it and get the perfect cup of coffee. They are so easy to clean up you just tap them in the trash everything comes out cleanly and then you just rinse it off. Also love the fact knowing that I'm not wasting all that money and I'm not wasting all that plastic and container material that is produced with the K-Cup packs. And there's two of them so you don't have to wait for one to cool down before you can use the other one, just go right ahead on with the second one. They are very well constructed and I think we will be using these for a long time to come. It came with very clear instructions packaging was excellent you could tell that the seller took care and how they package the product so that it reached you in perfect condition, which it did. I would recommend these to my family or friends, I plan to purchase a few packs for them as they are curing addicts as well.

review_text:
After three months of multiple times a wee use I have been pleasantly surprised by this countertop dishwasher. If you keep your expectations reasonable you will be very happy with it.

Like other reviewers have stated, all of the countertop dishwashers on Amazon all come from the same factory and have the same innards, shop on price and looks. In my case, having a rental house away from home for a one year appointment, looks didn‚Äôt really matter. The Danby plain white one with push button controls is perfect.

No, this won‚Äôt wash your stock pot or large sauce pan (maybe the sauce pan and some utinsels by themselves). However, for the day to day 90%? It‚Äôs great. It will wash all of your utensils, plates (even big oversized American dinner plates), mugs bowls and glassware.

Simply replace the nozzle on your sink faucet and clip on the hose when you want to use it.

This does take a good amount of counter top space, but fits underneath cabinets. In my 1950s era rental with original cabinets it clears them with a few centimeters to spare in height, and a few centimeters front to back. If you put a large toaster oven and a drip brew coffee maker side by side it would take up similar horizontal space.

The inside is stainless steel with plastic coated metal wire trays that seem very high quality.

Cleaning quality is on par with $4-500 price range standard dishwashers. Yes, it‚Äôs probably best if you rinse your dishes thouroughly first. I haven‚Äôt tried the jet dry feature. When the cycle is over I pop the door and let the water evaporate.

It isn‚Äôt very noisy, but you will notice it unless your kitchen is blocked off from the rest of your dwelling. Mostly you can hear when the water is draining as it is coming out at high pressure.

If you have a small apartment or a rental house with no dishwasher, this thing pays for its self in convenience and time saved (really, 8-10 days worth of chinese takeaway meals will cover the cost). When it‚Äôs time to move? Ask the property owner to take off $250 from your last month rent and leave it with them.
product_title: Danby DDW621WDB Countertop Dishwasher with 6 Place Settings, 6 Wash Cycles and Silverware Basket, Energy Star-Rated with Low Water Consumption and Quiet Operation

review_title: Don‚Äôt settle for only an NSF Type 42 filter!
review_text:
Sure, you can find cheaper filters for your refrigerator, most of those cheaper models are only NSF 42 certified. Type 42 merely removes suspended contaminants to make the water look more pleasing.

In addition to NSF 42, this filter meets NSF 53 & 401 standards. These additional standards help remove contaminants that cause health effects as well as chemical and pharmaceutical contaminants.

Spend the extra money and get a good water filter for your refrigerator. I am very pleased with this one.

Ref: http://www.nsf.org/consumer-resources/health-and-safety-tips/water-quality-treatment-tips/standards-for-water-treatment-systems

review_text: These sensors are not very good for esp32, or 8266 using ESPHome. Tested on both. There are consistent commuication timeout errors in the logs. review_text:
I bought this wrench to help with the replacement of the mode shifter assembly on my 7-year-old GE profile washing machine. The wrench allows you to remove the hub nut that attaches the washer's inner tub to the mode shifter assembly.

The wrench itself is very simple. It is made of two pieces of steel that fit together as a stack. The handle portion of the tool interlocks with the nut driving plate. Both pieces are much thicker and stronger than the pictures seem to indicate. I was surprised at how much steel you are getting when you order this tool.

The circular nut driving plate is actually cut slightly bigger than the hub nut on my washer. My sense is that this allows you to grab onto highly corroded nuts that are no longer in good shape. To make the wrench easier to use I taped the two pieces of the wrench together with blue painter's tape. This took up most of the slack around the nut, and allowed me to use the wrench as a single unit.

There are several YouTube videos that clearly demonstrate how to disassemble GE washing machines. One thing I learned from the videos, and other online postings is to use penetrating oil on the hub nut threads before attempting to remove the nut. The other thing I learned from the videos is to not be shy about whacking the spanner wrench with a hammer to remove the nut. I did both of these things and had my hub nut off in about 1 minute. This tool is perfect for the job.

The TB123A wrench so cleanly removed the hub nut, it allowed me to re-use the original nut and save $8 on a replacement. This was totally worth the cost of the wrench.

I was skeptical that I could buy appliance parts on Amazon, but this turned out to be a great experience. I got everything I needed to fix my washer, and saved at least $300 on my repair. Thank you Amazon.
product_title: Supco TB123A Spanner Wrench

review_text:
To make your own coffee pods without purchasing the pod maker for $40, purchase a 2"x2 1/2" Galvanized Hex Bushing at your local hardware store (2/1/2 x2 1/2 would work better but I couldn't find that). Place the pod on the top part with the lip and push in carefully so the edges of the pod are on the lip. Put the coffee in the pod. With a steam iron, steam over the pod for 5 seconds or so. Then put the top part of the pod over the bottom part with the coffee in it and iron to close it up.

I was going to buy the PVC version of this but was told that it wouldn't hold up with the heat from the iron. The metal one cost me $6.85 - better than $40!!

review_title: Good replacement filters for the V11
review_text:
Good replacement filters for the V11

These are a nice replacement filters for the Dyson V11 at a fraction of the cost.

They appear to be well made of good materials. They fit the V11 well, the vacuum recognizes that a filter is installed to allow it to run. The V11 runs properly with one installed...it does not run any hotter and suction seems to be the same. No warning lights.

These are actually dual purpose filters. The soft part that goes into the body of your vacuum is a pre motor filter that keeps dirt from getting into the motor. The part that remains outside is the post motor filter. It prevents dirt from being released back into the room. Both parts are washable.

I suspect the original filter would probably last longer than these, but, given the price differential, you can replace these way more frequently and still be way ahead. Alternatively, you can use these while you are waiting for your original to dry after washing.

review_title: I still love it after six months
review_text:
I bought one of these about six months ago and I still love it madly. My Mr. Coffee is jealous because I don't use it anymore. "Simple" and "stainless steel" are two of my favorite words. Coffee won't develop that burnt flavor if it's been setting for a hour. For the most part, it keeps coffee and tea hot, but you'll want to rinse out the interior with hot water before brewing.

Tea. That's right, you can use it for brewing tea. Some of my friends convinced me of the error my ways and talked me into buying leaf and brick tea instead of bags. Use this. It's a revelation.

The only mark against this French press is that the powdered coating on the bottom is looking a little rough, but I do use it every day. As long as the interior keeps working as it has, this is a keeper.

I'll continue using since I bought it, but I wish this had a better design so I can just make a cup without all of the self adjustments.

review_text:
My dryer duct is about 25 feet long, so I actually needed two of these to fully plumb it out, but this did a great job for me. I went a couple of feet at a time and hooked it up to a handheld drill to make the brushing easier. The rods were flexible enough to fit around a couple of bends (and also to fold up in the relatively cramped space I had to work from).

My only word of caution would be to get a brush that's long enough to run the full length of your duct and work from the inside out; trying to work toward the middle from each end is not a good idea because it can create a blockage in the middle. Relatedly, I did run into a couple of very large blockages in the duct where I initially couldn't get through. They were about 12 feet from the opening and under my living room floor, so at first I couldn't tell whether there was a bend that I couldn't get around or just a bad blockage. I took the brush off the end and just poked the rods in to see if they could get through--they did, so I at least knew that the duct was passable, even if the four-inch brush couldn't make it through. Because I had two of these kits, I had two brushes, so I trimmed one of the brushes down to a smaller size and was able to fit it through the jam and open it up. I then put the larger brush back on and cleaned it out.

Anyway, this really did the trick. A+ would recommend
product_title: Deflecto DVBRUSH12K/6 Dryer Duct Cleaning Kit, Lint Remover, Extends Up to 12 Feet, Synthetic Brush Head, Use with or Without a Power Drill, accessory, Computer
