review_title: It washes. What can I say?
review_text:
Hi. I bought both the Magic Chef 2.0 cu ft. portable washer and 2.6 cu ft dryer at Walmart, so no damage, great packaging, extended warranty, and a brick & mortar to return it to if needed. Then I got the MC laundry rack for $50 at home depot, unfortunately realizing too late that they had the washer/dryer cheaper there than Walmart too. Everything was bought around Christmas time, so there might have been better deals. I paid about $522 total for w/d.
I have been using this washer for a few weeks. Just 2 if us in the apt. and I wash 3 times a week. Just to make sure I maintain it well I made sure to read the manual completely. It has no agitator, which leaves more room for more items. Also, because of that, the washing rhythm is a pulse action. Just imagine Chubby Checker's twist at per 2 second speed and you got the image. There is minimal noise, quiet even, much less than a dish washer and not enough to disturb neighbors. Each cycle can be run individually or as a whole. It has a powerful spin cycle so that clothes come out minimally damp when done. Follow the directions! Make sure washer is level and only 3/4 full or you'll be mopping up a swimming pool. I setup the washer in the kitchen, but the adapter that came with the washer did not fit my faucet. It looked like DANCO Dishwasher Snap Coupling Adapter from Amazon. At first, washing with water turned on continuously, there would be leaking at the faucet on low pressure, spurting when the machine was not drawing water. Then after using it some more, the adapter would blow clean off. So I bought the Smartfresh 7 piece adapter kit from Amazon. I also figured I'm a renter, so I might need the variety of adapters for new places. I was going to try the Danco Multi thread Garden Hose Adapter from Amazon, but to my surprise there was an adapter in the kit that looked just like it. That was the one that fit on the faucet. No leaking whatsoever. I had my hot and cold water turned on all the way using one intake hose at full pressure attached to the cold valve and that was a lot! Washer came with 2 quality intake hoses and one cheap looking drain hose. I just protect the hot intake using the intake cap, since I am able to get hot or cold from the kitchen faucet. I am now able to run it on full automatic instead of drawing buckets. The intake hose is probably a couple feet, which is long enough to reach my faucet, but the drain hose is too short, like 4 feet maybe. The washer has 2 adjustable back wheels, but I never used them. Even though I bought the Stalwart Rolling Dolly Cart before purchasing the washer, which makes it easier to maneuver it, I don't like the idea of having to put it in front of my kitchen sink during wash. It takes up much space that way. I bought another drain hose planning to replace it but the only video I saw for a portable washer involve opening up the machine. I didn't want to possibly void the warranty. I read reviews where other people just did a simple switch, but I might just use it to extend the discharge hose. I‚Äôll see if it works out. I make sure clean the lint traps on both for each use. Keep in mind that the trap for the dryer is inside of the dryer. Due to other helpful reviews, I also got an indoor dryer ventilation kit and a stainless steel kitchen sink strainer to catch excess lint, from Amazon. Can‚Äôt clog the plumbing! I am also considering a stainless steel retractable clothesline.

review_text: This is a great looking and performing gas stovetop for the price.  I got rid of a white glass (impossible to keep clean) electric stovetop with a bad burner and replaced it with this very modern and functional gas one.  I've done a bunch of work in my kitchen but installing this stove is the one thing that's upgraded the look of the entire kitchen.  The reason I knocked off a star is because I switched over to propane and the orifice for the center burner is impossible to remove.  It's not a challenge, it's not difficult... it's impossible.  I used the correct sized wrench, the WD-40, and everything else I had in my tool arsenal.  I eventually gave up and came up with an alternate solution.  Regardless, I've had this stove for over 4 months I don't regret the purchase at all.

review_title: Mostly Pros!!!  Just a few Cons
review_text: I have been using induction for at least 20 years. I had it when I lived in Japan and when I moved back to the states I was able to replace my oven range with an induction oven range. Using a typical electric glass cooktop was torture after being spoiled by induction. We recently moved and the house we bought had a 36 inch Jenn Air. It was original to the house so about 12 years old. Trying to adjust with the control knobs on this was  a major frustration and I had enough when a week ago I prepared a big Sunday meal with 4 burners going at the same time. I got on-line and found a good deal on this and purchased it straight away. It arrived last night and my husband who is a big breakfast person and everyday complained how he missed the induction we had installed it straight away. He is pretty handy but he did have some trouble installing since there is no plug in as it is wired. The wires from the old one did not match up perfectly. The controls are amazing(a huge plus from any induction I have used) and it is so quiet you will not even know it is on unless you turn it up to high. It also has a timer which is great if you are busy like us. The only reason I did not give it 5 star is because the hole for the old 36 inch is a bit bigger and I am having trouble finding a GE Trim Kit for the 36" size. We did find the 30/32 inch kit on-line. It is available in black and white for about $100. It would be nice if they had it available in stainless steel as well.  Also it has a vent hood you have to attach under it and it has made the drawer where I keep all my flatware not useable. This is major since I really don't have anywhere else to put my flatware which I have a lot of. Since this was just installed and we have only used it a day I will update has need be. I am hoping after I post this that GE reaches out to me with some solutions for the issues we are having.
product_title: GE CHP9536SJSS Cafe 36" Gray Electric Induction Cooktop

review_text:
I paid $4.00 for this 12 pack Mineral Absorption Pads. That is less than about 33 cent each. I used the mineral pad which came with my humidifier machine and used white vinegar lengthen the its use. The idea is to use vinegar to dissolve the minerals deposited on the pad and to regenerate it. The original pad eventually broke down after many usages. In my experience, the pad becomes less effective after consecutive vinegar regeneration method.

I were out of a pad and minerals deposited very quickly on the heating element of my humidifier. I had to soak the heating element in vinegar every week for hours to loosen the mineral. When I waited longer than a week, the deposited minerals became extremely tough to remove. There were a lot of scrubbing. These became very time consuming and labor intensive. When the new pad came, I can see a huge difference. I had been using the very first pad from the box. It has been 2-3 weeks and there is minimal deposit on the heating element, though some. 33 cents for saving me hours of scrubbing my machine -- what an excellent time saver.

The pad came bigger than my heating element, so I had to cut it to fit. No big deal. 10 seconds of work. With a 12 piece mineral pads, I expect they will last me through the next two winters.

I made this work for my dryer by cutting off the excess metal cap looking piece and had to slowly expand the the entry for the bolt with another bolt I had that was the same size as the dryer motor. Do this at your own risk and if you do what I did, make sure you have some sort of grease to make it easier to expand the bolt entry for the replacement part. Slow and steady will make it work. Doing a back and forth motion while it's greased up will prevent it from breaking the replacement part and will make it easy to attach it to the motor.

review_text:
It gets clothes very clean but I can only give It 3 stars I had the smaller version of this washing machine same brand the first thing I had to do was take the back off and fix the drain on It, It was just a strap was Not connected but It worked well after that but then a few weeks ago the motor on the spin cycle quit working which Is one of the things I liked about It Is the spin cycle got clothes almost dry enough to Not need a dryer I could put My clothes on wet and Not have some judgmental complaining that I Am wet. I think all appliances should be built like old cars and tell-lie-vision could get parts for them anywhere and was easy to fix so I started to take the washing machine apart and checked It for sure the spin cycle motor went out and It would have Not been an easy fix and Nether did I know where to get parts for It therefore I bought this washing machine about the exact same thing just a little bit bigger maybe this one will last more than 2 years but If You go to Lowes or Home Depot that Is about how long this big brand name washing machines last now days about 2 year Not over 10 years as they used to, that Is why It only gets 3 stars because I also rate how easy Is It to repair....
Here Is a secret I figured out, If You get clothes as dirty as Me might first go to the car wash and clean them but what I found out about this washing machine It can act as an old washboard, Instead of filling the tub up full of Water put the clothe In and turn It on while the clothes are being whipped back and forth take a Garden hoes connected to the hot Water and spray the clothes, this washing machine does Not operate with the drain open so You will have to every few seconds open and close the drain to drain off the dirty Water then fill the tub with Water and wash as normal

review_text:
I will echo the other reviews in saying that the fan speeds are certainly calibrated too high. Low would be a fine high in any other unit. It is deafening, but I could overlook that if it functioned exceptionally well. Therein lies the problem.

We had a unit installed in a new build home - so all new ductwork, electric, etc. The factory motor worked well for around 2 weeks before it quit. It took Frigidaire's subcontractor 2 weeks to procure and install the new motor and it quit AFTER 10 MINUTES OF USE. Not an exaggeration. 10 minutes.

Don't buy this unit. Find another brand. Trust me.

review_text: I love this little machine. I have 4 kids in a small apartment and my husband works in HVAC. We end up with a lot of dirty clothes. I was going to a laundromat once a week but with this pandemic I had been feeling increasingly anxious about going. With this little machine I can keep up with our laundry daily without going anywhere and ny husband can immediately wash his clothes right when he gets home so he is less likely to bring germs into our home. Also the pictures do not give justice to the pretty blue lighting of the machine. The only downsides are, it's not easy to move it around andthe buttons are too easy to press. I have accidentally turned it off mid cycle. It doesn't take up much more space than a large kitchen garbage can and it washes well.  One thing to keep in mind is it does not have the option to start at different stages of the washing process so if it gets shut off you have to restart it. This can be very irritating if you have kids that can press the buttons. I have it in my kitchen  which is blocked by a gate but even bumping into it in the small kitchen can turn it off. The hoses are not very long and the hook to put over the sink to hold the drain hose is not stable so you must attach it to something heavy enough to keep it in place or else you will flood your kitchen like I did the first time I used it.

review_title: UPDATE: BADLY engineered washer, leaves clothes MOLDY. Read on...
review_text:
UPDATE: As it turns out, I discovered that despite my many efforts to clean the machine, it ended up leaving my clothes smelling of mold. I live in the desert so this took a great deal of consideration to come to this conclusion. I've been more than fair in my review; the dryer works great but my disgust with the overall performance of the washer leaves me to rate this combo as one star. It's no longer available on Amazon but I'm not surprised as to why it's no longer for sale here. At first I thought that the HE performance may be removing the smell of fabric softeners from my clothes, but in the end it's the overall design of the machine that was causing my clothes to not only smell as though nothing was used to soften the fabrics, but that left the clothes smelling moldy. Keep in mind that I never let the clothes sit for longer than a few hours before drying, as I mentioned I did try running cycles with vinegar, tried using the cleaning cycle of the unit itself...to no avail. UGH. So I'm donating them to charity and will take the loss. I'll think twice before ever buying LG products again, that's for sure.
Former/prior review (left unedited):
Pros: Beautiful units, great quality - doors and buttons, features. Easy to use once you start to better understand the cycle definitions. All of the features work well, i.e., the fabric softener scent sticks with the laundered items, which isn't the case with some of the other HE washers with which I've had some experience. Pros highly outweigh the cons!
Cons: Love the units, except for a few things: mainly that the extremely large tub is somewhat deceiving with regard to the size of laundry that it will hold. Meaning, I tried to wash a few standard pillows in the "bulky" cycle and I would have thought that it would have sensed the size of the load and filled it enough to at least cover the pillows relatively well since the tub wasn't full by any stretch of the word. They did come out clean. This is but one example of how either I'm using the cycles wrong or it doesn't clean bulky items that well. Make sure that you read the owner's manual!!

i purchased this kit for my 14 year old LG front load washer. The original bearings had deteriorated so badly that the spin cycle caused a very loud roar and vibration. This was not any easy fix and also required replacing the spyder shaft that was damaged. Removal of the old bearings was relatively simple after separation of the two outer drum halves and removal of the motor rotor and stator. A big hammer and brass drift knocked the old bearings out. The old seal literally fell out (probably the cause of bearing failure). Installing the new bearings was somewhat difficult as the fit in the drum unit was extremely tight. You have to be very careful to avoid damage when driving the new bearings into the drum bore. I used the outer race of the old bearing as a spacer and seated the new bearings with the large hammer and brass drift. I also used some sealant on the outer edges when installing the seal.
It's been nearly a year since I did this repair and the washer is still just as quiet as new. If you're up to it, this kit can revive a machine at a very reasonable price that would likely otherwise require junking and replacement with a new machine.

review_title: These filters work well most of the time
review_text:
After reading several one star reviews for the Melitta disc filters I decided to try these with my Presto 12 cup percolator.

The filter covers all the holes in the 3 1/2‚Äù inch basket. There‚Äôs a circular perforation that allows the disc diameter to be reduced to 3‚Äù for smaller baskets (note: if you have a Presto percolator 3 1/2‚Äù fits). The filters come in a stack and some dexterity is required to separate the individual filters. The filter can be used with standard pre-ground coffee purchased from the grocery store.

A more demanding test of the filter is to grind your beans with an inexpensive electric grinder (e.g Krups), which typically produces some very fine grounds under the blade. I‚Äôve tried several different beans and have concluded that these filters are effective at retaining the small grounds produced by the electric grinder. Finally I added a tablespoon of espresso grind directly on top of the filter and then added coarse percolator ground beans. The coffee came through clear with no significant coffee residue.

Overall, I‚Äôm happy with these Brew Rite filters and will be reordering.

Updated 8/2/20: I‚Äôve been using these filters for over a year now. If you are looking for a percolator filter that will retain all the grinds all the time, you‚Äôll be disappointed. These filters do not work as well as the conical or basket filters used in drip coffee makers. It is not unusual to find some grinds or fine residue at the bottom of the cup. Finally, if your basket is 3 1/2‚Äù then you don‚Äôt need to tear the filter at the circular perforation (see above). It‚Äôs likely that the perforation decreases filter performance.

review_title: Wheels making noise after barely 2 months
review_text:
The pulley and belt are still running rock solid. From what I can tell two of the wheels seem to be operating alright, but at least one, if not two of them are making a lot of noise. Honestly though, its pretty impossible to know for sure.

Last week it was extremely loud, to the point that my wife didn't want to run it for fear of burning out the pulley and belt again. I took the dryer apart, sprayed some WD40 on the wheels, and put it all back together. The sounds went away for about a week and now its starting to make a low pitch growl of sorts. I did not expect the WD40 to last long, it never does, but I wanted to identify the root cause of the noises, of which it did.

In short, the pulley and belt have been running great. The wheels, not so much, to the point that I'm either going to try to buy a different set. I saw the comments about contacting the seller through their profile, but I must be too dense to figure out how to do that.

EDIT: Now August 30, I took the dryer apart AGAIN (this time due to the heating element going bad), and found the rear right roller had completely burnt out...melting a good bit of the plastic. Luckily I had one of the old original rollers sitting around to replace the replacement. Extremely frustrating.

On a side note, I will never buy another Samsung washer/dryer ever again.

review_title: Don't bother unless you like to waste coffee and like your drink watered down
review_text:
My suspicion was first raised when I noticed that the edges of the filter didn't quite cover the entire filter cap. Sure enough, as soon as I poured the water in onto the grinds, it started to drop through. "No way this was enough steeping," I thought.

I *had* noticed that the package read, "Ideal for inverted brewing." But surely, just because it's "ideal for" doesn't mean it's "only for". Whatever. So (against the AeroPress advice) I tried steeping it upside down.

NOPE.
Didn't help.

The air pressure being forced through the grinds and filter are part of the process. (Hence, "aero" press.)
The OEM paper filters creates enough of a temporary semi-permeable seal to allow steeping to happen and to require the plunger to force the air through the grinds. A leaking filter completely defeats the purpose.

Really disappointed.
product_title: The MESH: Reusable Metal Filter for AeroPress Coffee Maker. Also Fits AeroPress Go coffee press. No More Paper Filters

review_title: Works as it should. Compatible with model 5220JB2005A
review_text:
I own a LG LRFC25750ST refrigerator and my ice maker water valve stopped holding the water as it should and it caused a mess. Luckily I was home to shut off the main water line, otherwise my kitchen floor would have been destroyed.

My current valve model 5220JB2005A is no longer made, so when doing some research I came across this model (5220JB2010A) as well as MJX41178908 which looks similar and purchased both. MJX41178908 did not work because the connector for the rubber hose that goes into the refrigerator is wider so I returned it, but 5220JB2010A (which is this current listing) worked perfectly. Installation was also easy and there are Youtube videos in case you need.

Lesson learned: Remember to shut off your water when going on vacation or when going away for the weekend. These valves eventually die and if they don't hold the water current get ready for a big mess! I'll also buy one of those flooding sensors asap.
product_title: LG Electronics 5220JB2010A Refrigerator Water Inlet Valve

review_text:
My house and my clothes used to smell like the food I cook. If I sauteed onions and garlic, I would smell like sauteed onions and garlic. If I pan fried a steak, I would smell like steak. If I fried anything - I smelled like a fast food worker after an eight hour shift. My poor kids' eyes would tear up from sauteed onion fumes, while they were sitting 20 feet away.

My kitchen is located at least 15 feet away from a window, so opening a window is not an option (not that a window is a substitute to a vent) and I used to have an over the range microwave with what is ironically called a "vent". Needless to say, other than creating loud white noise, and blowing more food smell back on me, it would be utterly useless.

NOT ANYMORE!

Over a year ago, I replaced the over the range microwave with this fine product (by a professional, since I didn't have an air vent hookup to the outside). By far, this product has been the most impactful product I have purchased, and it has truly been life hanging. I no longer smell like food. My kids no longer tear up when I sautee onions. For heavy odors (which is most odors produced by pan frying and sauteing), I use the strongest power setting. For steam, I use lower settings.

Cleaning: After frying something, I can definitely feel grease on the bottom of the vent grills. They are super easy to remove, and depending what I cook, I clean them once or twice a month. I usually use a brush and soap to clean them in the sink before I put it through a dishwasher wash, because I take comfort in seeing the grease be brushed away (all those years of pent up microwave vent anger). The vent grills come out squeaky clean from the dishwasher and easy put back on the vent. I do wipe down any greasy area above the vent grills prior to putting the vents back, because oil is a witch with a capital B.

Power settings and noise level - Strong power setting naturally will be loud, and yes, if my kids try to talk to me across the room, they will have to talk loud, but I tell you this, they will much rather yell across the room than wipe away their irritated teary eyes.

I do believe that houses should, at the very least, come setup with vent hoses to the outside - if not already have a strong vent. A strong vent is a must have in any household that cooks - and yes, it is worth EVERY PENNY in getting a powerful enough vent. I wouldn't skimp on $100-$150 to get something cheeper that is not effective enough in keeping smell out.

Happy cooking!

review_text:
We had a TL GE that was really destroying our clothes. At first we thought it was the hard water in the city, but after hooking it up to a water softener, we realized it was more likely than not the center agitator. So, out with the old (rental) and in with this great buy! We used to have a FL HE washer but left that at the house we rented out, so we were also used to having to use less detergent. It really is necessary to use a detergent made for an HE washer and to use as little as possible. As such, we use country save, since it's also a cloth diaper friendly detergent. For the first time in over a year, our clothes *feel* clean, they smell clean, the diapers are getting super duper clean, and, best of all, my clothes are intact! It has a great capacity and I love the drum design. I also like the clear top, so that I can see what's going on (an important feature when stripping cloth diapers of build-up). Definitely going to investigate the dryer to compliment the washer.

The *one* thing I find odd, and I'm on the hunt for weather all of this model do this or if it is just our unit, is that the control panel "sweats" when washing with hot water. It doesn't appear to affect the controls, but definitely worth buying the added warranty protection just in case! I'd do that anyway with a machine with so many working parts, but figured I'd throw this into the review in case someone else experiences it or knows if this is ok/dangerous.

review_text:
I bought this cook-top last summer and absolutely love it. I have a white kitchen so I wanted the mirror finish and even though the price was higher than the black version I decided to just bite the bullet and go for it. And I am so happy I did.

Also in the running at the time was a Wolf gas cook-top but I just did not want to deal with the constant more complicated cleaning. What a wise decision as I am always sponging off spills and other messes which is so easy with the glass. And it does not show wipe marks like the black version tends to do as I have been told by someone who has one.

It is so easy to set the temperature. The more you use it the more intuitive it becomes to know the correct number to use. I can just set it and walk away. And you can also set a timer for each burner so it will turn off automatically.

There are some issues to be aware of but nothing that can't be adapted to just like any cooking source. You need pots that are compatible. I had to buy a few new ones as not all of my previous ones worked. No problem really and it gave me a chance to update some of my old ones. I carried a little magnet around with me when I went pot shopping.

You also cannot do the "chef shake" on the pans without potentially causing scratches. I am pretty careful about this but when I make popcorn I can just put a paper towel or parchment paper between the pot and the burner to avoid this issue. So this is really a non-issue for me but it might be for someone else.

Unlike a gas stove there are burner sizes which are more suited to various pot sizes. For example I have a small butter warmer which will only work on the small back right element. But again these are things which I have become accustomed to and in no way makes me wish I had chosen gas. I love that I do not have to guess what the right gas setting is for cooking.

I just love my cook-top and I am so happy with my choice. It works for me.

review_text:
We got this dishwasher when we were renovating the gutted house we bought. I was doing so many things (floors/cabinets/walls/electrical/construction) that I just went into Best Buy and randomly picked appliances. The first year the dishwasher started leaking from the lower right onto the floor. The Frigidaire warranty was still in effect so I called them and they came out and replaced the side splash guards, the bottom splash guard and the door gasket. The side and door splash guards were visibly ripped. The leaking stopped.

2 years later the same leak appeared. So called the home warranty company and they came out and did the same thing, replacing those parts and the leak stopped again. So if you own one of these and are getting leaks out of the front, check the gasket that runs around the tub and seals to the door. Costs $8 to replace and its easy to push in and replace yourself. My 7 year old could replace it, its that easy.

The dishwasher was also very quiet when we first got it, couldn't even tell it was running. Well 2.5 years later and its louder. I asked the repairman about this and he said over time the quiet motors just get louder and louder.

Avoid this dishwasher, unless it is like on sale for like $20 then the $8-20 of parts you need to buy every year shouldn't matter too much.

Its less than a week since I bought this on Amazon. Initially I was skeptical, but I think its a good product. Good looks and finish and performance is good. Only reason I gave it 4 stars instead of 5 is because I'm not sure of the 850 cfm rating it advertises - But it does its job. We do a lot of Indian style cooking and the previous GE hood we owned did a pathetic job (with extremely loud noise) - so this one is far-far better.
As a matter of fact, I think this was the right choice for me, since other branded models cost so much more and you can expect your electric / gas bill to go up - more the cfm, more surrounding air the hood draws out - meaning your AC / heater has to work overtime to keep up with all the air that is drawn out !

Keep in mind, I use a Chemex which this works perfectly for; it doesn't fit quite as snug on my Hario, which would be a problem.

So, based on the fact that I have a Burr grinder and a Chemex, this product works perfectly. If you have an inconsistent grind you may have an issue. You may also have a problem with it if you're using the wrong carafe.

Zero complaints.

review_title: Exact replacement, restored ice dispenser operation to "like new"
review_text:
Side-by-side refrigerators are incredibly complicated. Cold air just doesn't want to flow naturally from left to right; it wants to drop by gravity from the top down. So the refrigerators have a complex array of electronics, ducting, fans, tubing, and device actuators like this little solenoid. I my opinion, replacement of this solenoid was a simple repair, very much a one-hour do-it-yourself project.
It's an exact fit, genuine GE replacement part. You don't get much for your 25 dollars, but Amazon is cheaper than other sources.
My refrigerator is ten years old, I guess in that time the old solenoid slowly became corroded and lost strength. Finally the ice chute began freezing up and the water dispenser stopped squirting (I still haven't fixed that problem - thawing didn't help).
There are videos on the web that show how to pop off the door trim and disassemble the dispenser. My biggest advice: don't forget to pull the plug or kill the circuit breaker!
The solenoid is held in place with three screws, recessed deep in the dispenser cavity, so a magnetic bit holder helps a lot. The part does not include replacement screws, so I put a drop of olive oil over the old ones to lubricate and give them some protective coating. The solenoid DOES come with a new plunger (I put a little olive oil on it too). First hang the plunger from its hook, then slide it into the solenoid core as you wiggle the part into position. Now you've got a wire from the new solenoid, snake it toward the front so it's there while you reassemble the dispenser hardware.
Power on and you're ready to go!
I noticed that the Dispenser Door now snaps solidly closed; it hasn't done that for a long time!

Note: For a few dollars more, I also ordered and replaced the General Electric WR17X11653 Dispenser Door. Not completely necessary, but perhaps the old rubber seals were tired. Hopefully I won't have to disassemble these components for another ten years!

review_text: My old Blower was frozen motionless  in my 20 year old Kenmore (aka Frigidaire) gas dryer.  Blower has built-in 7/8" plastic nut (reverse thread) with a metal nut embedded in the plastic.  Socket drive (clockwise) would not loosen the nut.  Had to chisel it out to expose metal nut.  The metal nut was also fused to the motor spindle. See photo. I tried to cut the nut off with a dremel tool, but the metals were melted together.  So motor was kaput, too.  LUBE the spindle threads before you install the new blower to hopefully prevent the threads of the nut and the motor fusing together.  Make sure you insert the Blower tabs (feet) into the cabinet holes before securing the Blower with its two screws.  Dryer is now very quiet...

review_title: Easy to use, fast, cheap - but don't overpack the filters!
review_text:
Have had the EZ-Cup for about 2 months and used it daily. It's been great - cheaper than buying even generic K-cups, easy to use, fast and much less wasteful (environmentally). I don't have extra time in the morning and I was worried that this would take a lot longer than throwing in a K-cup but it doesn't. I leave mine in overnight after use so it's dried out by the time I take it out in the morning and is easy to trash without dripping all over. I then put in a new filter, scoop coffee in, and it's good to go.

The only caveat is that you don't want to overfill it. When I pack in the coffee grounds into the filter with the spoon (I mean really press them down), the machine doesn't function properly (it will produce only a very small amount of coffee). Also, after a few days of this, our machine got clogged, wouldn't function at all, and we had to call customer service to figure out how to fix it. Since then, we've put a normal amount of coffee into the filter without packing it down and haven't had any problems. I like my coffee pretty dark and it's still full flavored, even without packing the grounds into the filter!
product_title: Perfect Pod EZ-Cup for Keurig 1.0 brewers by Perfect Pod

review_text:
The hood is very nice, attractive and looks very modern.
The fan is exceptionally quiet at all speeds, however, the lights have only one setting, and they are not very bright. The fan controls are a little confusing as the light control is located between the fan speed settings and the fan on/off button.
Installation instructions are horrible. They show a very small, not so detailed drawing and the written instructions are terrible.
A few installation tips:
This is for a very high ceiling. If your ceiling is less than 8'2" I wouldn't try to install this model.
The unit has 8 angle iron brackets that bolt together to form 4 corners inside the SS hood. Make sure you bolt the lower leg on the outside of the upper leg, otherwise, when you get it all together, the fan body will not fit in between the four corners. I found this out the hard way. Also, make sure you have at least 8" of overlap on the bottom leg or it will not fit over the fan body. I also found this out the hard way. I had to cut several inches off the upper leg of the angle iron to make it work.
If it wasn't for the poor installation instructions, I would be very pleased with this unit.
Now that it is installed, I am happy with the product.

review_text:
My main gripe is that you do have to modify it. The My K Cup by itself makes some seriously weak coffee. So I've done what everyone else has done and cut the top off of a regular K Cup, put that in the reservoir, and then put the filter in that. Now, if your not comfortable with reusing the plastic K Cup, then you probably will not want to buy this product. You might want to check out the Ekocert stainless steel reusable K Cup. Without the modification, it makes weak coffee - so buy bolder coffee if you do decide to purchase and not modify.

I watched a review that stated these reusable K Cup filters held 10 grams of coffee, and that a regular K Cup can hold 11. Which seems like it would already set you up to make weaker coffee - hence encouraging people to buy K Cups? Maybe, but I grind my coffee and like to think that maybe it's a bit fresher, so therefore I can go with a little less. How I get my best cup is 1) use the modification, 2) grind my coffee on the espresso setting on my Hamilton Beach blade grinder, 3) fill the filter almost to the top with coffee (about 2.5 scoops of beans for me) and tap it down - I tap it on the counter and also gently press down the top with the back of my coffee scoop 4) use the 8 ounce setting for regular coffee or 10 if I'm using a darker roast. I also clean it after every use.

I own the http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0034J6QIY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 and love it so far.

review_title: It fits well in my Whirlpool but a few installation tips are in order.
review_text: four installation tips---first check to make sure the seal is the problem.  My leak ended up to be the hot air vent at the top left of the door.  Water leaked thru the gasket inside the door and came out the bottom looking like a seal leak.  Second the lip of the seal faces inward.  Third, locate the seal at the bottom of your door before installing.  On the whirlpool this seal is a flap integral with the door.  The new seal MUST overlap this door seal on the bottom or there will be a leak at that location.  Fourth, the new seal has three ridges along the v-shape portion that goes into the groove on the dishwasher.  I only pushed the seal in as far as the second ridge, then closed the door for an hour or so then ran a hot wash.  Sealed totally.  My first try had a slight leak at one location when I pushed the seal all the way in initially.  My 10 yr old door is probably a bit warped.

review_title: The parts fit fine, but those instructions!
review_text: I needed to replace a broken shelf adjustor on my KitchenAid dishwasher.  I found these at half the price of those on parts-specific web sites.  They also were delivered in one day, a great advantage.  But the Instruction sheet that came with these parts was terrible.  The first instructions were to remove the old shelf and then remove the old adjusters from the rack.  That will be easier said than done for some.  The old adjustors are held on by some clips that are not all that obvious.  After that is done, the 2 page instruction sheet had 10 photographs to show what to do, but every one of them is out of focus, and some details are fairly small.  I found you could go on YouTube and search on the part number and find very good videos showing exactly what to do.  This is quite helpful, especially when the new adjusters are a redesign of the old ones, so they don't look much alike.  After watching the video a couple of times, I was able to change the parts easily and quickly.  The new ones fit fine, and the whole replacement process took less than a half hour.  So, 5 stars for the parts, minus one for the instructions.

review_title: if you like to save money, but have a Nespresso Machine, this is for you!
review_text: ok I have to say I love my Nespresso machine, but I did not like the coffee choices I had, I like a tall cup of coffee about 14oz, and I like it strong, in my older Keurig I would use Espresso coffee and a custom cup, so that is what these allow you to do in a way. first you find the cup for the way you like your coffee, in Nespresso world, each cup has a bar code and the machine reads it and it tells the machine how long to add water , how fast to add water, etc... so you need to find the list of what each cups properties are and find the one that you like, use it and save the cup, cut the foil off the top and then clean it out, this is now the new cup, then you can buy or make 2" round filters and add the coffee to the cup and then a filter and then one of these lids, then put in the machine and make coffee, I do it in my sleep and it is nothing to do every morning, and it is worth it!! now I get a strong 14oz cup of coffee that tastes the same every day!!

review_text:
I have heard such great things about the Opal ice maker that I splurged and bought it.

Two months of amazing ice and then machine made some horrible noise and quit working. I cleaned it, I checked water levels, I unplugged it let it sit for a day-I tried everything I could think of.

Finally I contacted amazon, but they want me to return the machine. That would be fine, but it weighs about 50lbs and is large and I didn't save the shipping box from the original purchase (does anyone save the original packaging for months? No). I offered to bring it to a physical location, but alas that isn't possible.

So I contacted GE. I had registered the machine when it was purchased. GE asked for videos of the noise and the machine in operation. I sent those videos...then a week later I sent a follow up email...then a week later I sent another follow up email. At this point GE isn't responding, even to say yes or no to my warranty request.

Overall, we loved the ice maker when it was working. However, I am so disappointed that neither amazon or GE will help me with this issue. At this point (sept 2022) it hasn't worked for about three weeks and it was delivered less than three months ago (July 2022). I expect more out of a $500 appliance.

review_text:
I bought this to use with a Chemex. The strainer is well made and fits nicely. Quick and easy to rinse clean. For Chemex users, the biggest consideration moving from Chemex brand paper filters is that a stainless strainer kind of negates the whole purpose of the Chemex system. The paper filters are designed to drain at an ideal rate and fit snug to the glass so you can fill the paper filter past the level of your coffee and the water will still drain through the coffee at a pretty consistent rate. If you fill the stainless strainer above the level of your coffee, you will have straight water escaping the sides of the filter and diluting your coffee.

Because the stainless drains faster, a finer grind should be used. I like using the strainer and once you get things dialed in it brews a nice cup of coffee with a distinctly different flavor than paper. I still use paper once in a while but mostly use the stainless to reduce waste and save a few dollars over time.
